<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Award     08-12 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Award,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Wins India's Nehru Award for International
Understanding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar has won the 1987 Jawaharlal Nehru Award for International
Understanding, India's U.N. ambassador announced.
   The prize has been awarded annually since 1965 for outstanding
contributions to international understanding, said Ambassador C.R.
Gharekahn on Thursday.
   He said it reflects general achievements, but he specifically
mentioned the secretary-general's role in negotiating a cease-fire
between Iran and Iraq. The truce is to take effect Aug. 20.
   The award includes a cash prize of about $110,000. A jury of
Indian officials selects the winner.
   The ambassador said Perez de Cuellar had agreed to come to New
Delhi for presentation of the prize, but a date had not been set.
   The award is named after Nehru, post-colonial India's first
prime minister.
   Previous winners include former U.N. Secretary-General U Thant,
U.S. civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., missionary Mother
Teresa, Dr. Jonas Salk who developed a polio vaccine, South African
activist Nelson Mandela, Indian leader Indira Gandhi, and Swedish
Prime Minister Olof Palme.
</TEXT>
