<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Marcos-Mother     08-12 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos-Mother,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos' Mother Unburied Three Months After Her Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAC, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three months after her
death, the body of Ferdinand Marcos' mother is still unburied as
her son's dwindling followers maintain a wake in hopes the
government will allow him to come home.
   But civic leaders say that even here in ``Marcos country,'' many
believe the time has come to place the body of Josefa
Edralin-Marcos in the marble tomb prepared for her in the family
cemetery in a swamp on the eastern edge of this town.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos died May 4 at age 95, and her body was
transferred the following month from Manila to the Marcos ancestral
home in Batac, a town of about 50,000 people about 240 miles to the
north.
   Family members and Marcos supporters say no date for the burial
will be set until President Corazon Aquino allows her deposed
predecessor to return or until Marcos orders the interment.
   The body has been embalmed at least twice, and Marcos family
mortician Frank Malabed said the remains could remain unburied
until the end of the year.
   The former president has lived in Hawaii since a
civilian-military uprising toppled his 20-year administration in
1986. Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow him back for security
reasons.
   ``To be frank with you, we have not been able to set a definite
date,'' said Marcos' sister Fortuna Barba, who attends daily prayer
services before the open coffin in the family home. The mansion is
now a museum.
   Pictures of Marcos and his wife, Imelda, hang from the walls
alongside banners such as: ``God's will, I'll return to save my
nation and people from communism.''
   ``We're still hoping, perhaps against hope, that the situation
will change and something good may come out of it,'' Mrs. Barba
said.
   Whatever sympathy Marcos may have hoped to generate by his
appeal to come home appears to have dissipated in the months
following his mother's death.
   Filipino newspapers rarely mention the ongoing wake. In a rare
exception, The Manila Chronicle recently suggested an epitaph:
``Here lies Dona Josefa Marcos, died at age 95, buried at age 96.''
   Rodolfo Farinas, provincial governor of Ilocos Norte and a close
friend of the Marcos family, said if Marcos believes he has no
chance to return, ``he should give the word that his mother should
be laid to rest.''
   The Rev. Ruben Abaya, a Roman Catholic priest, said the arrival
of Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' body generated considerable enthusiasm in
Batac because many believed Marcos was returning for the funeral.
   Pro-Marcos politicians erected red, white and blue signs in
Batac and in neighboring towns welcoming the former president to
his provincial stronghold.
   But as the weeks dragged on without the Apo, or Grand Old Man,
both the signs and the enthusiasm are fading.
   Under a rotation system, residents take turns attending daily
prayers before the casket. But attendance has dwindled from
hundreds to a few dozens each day.
   ``The feeling seems to be that the woman has suffered enough and
should be laid to rest,'' Abaya said.
   Vice Mayor Rodolfo Yadao, a member of Marcos' New Society
Movement party, said townspeople were still eager for Marcos to
return.
   Yadao said, however, that townspeople were losing patience with
his nearly fanatical supporters from Manila who came here for the
wake.
   ``We have to provide for them,'' Yadao said. ``Sometimes, they
are quarelling with themselves. She should be buried now. That is
our tradition.'' He was referring to the practice of burying people
within nine days of death.
   At Laoag International Airport, about six miles north, the
military has placed metal barricades, mounds of gravel and six
concrete abutments on the runway, shortening it by 1,200 yards to
prevent Marcos from slipping in on a charter flight from abroad.
   Some Marcos supporters vow to continue the wake indefinitely
until their leader returns.
   But asked if the family were prepared for an indefinite
standoff, Mrs. Barba replied: ``Well, I suppose if there is no
hope, I'll get a call from him one day telling me to go ahead with
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
