<DOCNO> AP880812-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBIRacism     08-12 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI Racism,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Major Parts of FBI Agent's Racial Harassment Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major portions of a black FBI agent's racial
harassment lawsuit against the government have been dismissed as
technically defective, but the plaintiff's lawyer says the ruling
ultimately will be a victory.
   Attorney David Kairys said many of the legal flaws found by U.S.
District Judge Charles R. Richey in agent Donald Rochon's complaint
can be corrected and the case will go forward.
   The Philadelphia lawyer said Richey's order Thursday leaves the
essential element of the case intact.
   ``He has upheld our ability to get personal damages against the
individual wrongdoers,'' Kairys said. ``This is very important and
was not a matter of certainty when we started this.''
   In a highly technical opinion, Richey dismissed ``without
prejudice'' most of the claims against 21 white FBI agents, whom
Rochon contends engaged in a three-year campaign of harassment that
included anonymous telephone calls, obscene mail and death threats.
Rochon also contends agents threatened his white wife with sexual
assault.
   The ``without prejudice'' proviso Richey attached to most of the
dismissals gives Rochon an opportunity to file a new complaint to
try to correct the legal defects identified by the judge.
   Richey said the complaint, while raising ``repugnant and
chilling'' allegations, ``contains defects in both pleading and
legal theory that constrain the court to dismiss many of the
plaintiff's claims.''
   The judge, however, refused to dismiss common-law claims against
three white Chicago FBI agents _ Gary W. Miller, Thomas Dillon and
Kenneth Veach _ whom Rochon said spearheaded harassment when he
worked in that city.
   Richey also refused to dismiss Rochon's claim that his civil
rights were violated under Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
But he dismissed 21 FBI agents and top officials as defendants in
that claim, saying only the attorney general could be sued as head
of Rochon's agency.
   He also found that many of Rochon's claims against individual
agents, particularly supervisors who allegedly ignored the racial
harassment complaints, were pre-empted under other statutes by the
Title VII claim.
   Kairys chose to hail Richey's decision to preserve the civil
rights claim, saying it was the vehicle for the overall harassment
and discrimination complaint.
   ``The individuals, at least temporarily, some of them, are off
the hook, but the judge has clearly said the only problem is he
doesn't want Title VII and allegations about the individuals to be
merged,'' Kairys said.
   ``That is just a matter of filing an amended complaint which
separates them,'' he said.
   But Kairys conceded he will have difficulty sustaining claims
against the FBI supervisors and managers that Rochon claims
deliberately ignored his complaints.
   Kairys said he was gratified by Richey's stern warning to the
defendants to stop referring to the racial harassment incidents as
``pranks.''
   ``This utter lack of sensitivity is almost as disturbing as the
alleged acts themselves,'' Richey said, adding that ``the court
hereby warns defendants that a modicum of decency is expected for
all those who file pleadings in this court.''
   Kairys said, ``The judge really recognized how inappropriate it
has been for the FBI and the Department of Justice and their
lawyers to fail to acknowledge that something other than pranks
occurred here.''
   The judge also dismissed altogether complaints against three
agents arising from alleged racial harassment incidents when Rochon
worked in the FBI's Omaha, Neb., field office in 1983 and 1984.
Richey found that the statute of limitations had expired on those
claims.
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission upheld many of
Rochon's complaints about harassment in Omaha. The EEOC's
investigation of the Chicago incidents was suspended after the suit
was filed.
   Rochon, 38, now works in the bureau's Philadelphia office.
   Miller, who admitted during an internal investigation that he
forged Rochon's signature on an application for ``death and
dismemberment'' insurance, is the subject of a grand jury
investigation.
   The insurance policy was sent to Rochon's home as part of what
Miller called an attempt to get ``retribution'' for the black
agent's complaints of racial harassment. Miller was suspended for
two weeks without pay but fellow white agents took a collection to
pay his salary, according to statements made in court.
</TEXT>
