<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NearCollision     08-12 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Near Collision,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Checking Near-Collision Over Atlantic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are trying to determine
why a jetliner was flying at the wrong altitude over the North
Atlantic and almost collided with another jetliner earlier this
week.
   Word of the incident emerged Thursday when the National
Transportation Safety Board said it was investigating a report
filed by one of the pilots, who estimated the two aircraft came
within 200 to 300 feet of each other.
   The incident last Monday occurred about 700 miles east of Boston
and involved Lockheed L-1011 jetliners flown by American Trans Air,
a U.S. charter airline, and LuftTransport, a West German charter
carrier, according to the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Capt. Richard Reb, the American Trans Air pilot, said he was
talking to his co-pilot when he suddenly saw the other plane
through a side window of the cockpit. He immediately lowered the
nose of his plane and descended 1,000 feet, according to an airline
spokesman.
   At the time, both jets were cruising at about 550 miles per hour
at 35,000 feet with American Trans Air Flight 665 flying directly
west and the LuftTransport Flight 410 heading southwest and
converging, according to government and airline officials. The FAA
said the LuftTransport plane should have been flying at 31,000 feet.
   Flight 665 with 250 passengers and 12 crew members was bound
from Lisbon, Portugal, to New York's John F. Kennedy Airport, said
David Recker, executive vice president of American Trans Air, which
is based in Indianapolis.
   It could not immediately be determined how many people were
aboard the other plane, but such European charter flights normally
are heavily booked during the summer months, according to aviation
experts. The LuftTransport jet was bound from Frankfurt to Cancun,
Mexico.
   The airspace over the ocean where the incident occurred is not
covered by radar, but jetliners are assigned specific routes, speed
and altitude by controllers at Gander, Newfoundland, and at New
York.
   According to the FAA, the West German plane had just left
airspace controlled by the Gander controllers and entered airspace
controlled by the FAA's New York control center when the incident
occurred.
   ``The (German) plane should have descended to 31,000 feet before
it entered New York airspace,'' said FAA spokesman John Leyden.
   Leyden said preliminary reports indicate that both planes were
flying the proper route but that ``it looks like a case of the
wrong altitude'' on the part of the LuftTransport plane.
   FAA and NTSB investigators planned to interview controllers at
both New York and Gander to determine whether the LuftTransport
pilot was assigned the wrong altitude.
   Leyden said both pilots saw the other aircraft.
   ``It was close and it's kind of frightening,'' said Recker. He
said no one aboard the American Trans Air plane was injured during
the incident and that it was over before the passengers were aware
of anything unusual.
   LuftTransport is based in Dusseldorf, West Germany, according to
the FAA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
