<DOCNO> AP880812-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Money     08-12 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Money,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Has Cash To Spare For His Small Share Of Convention Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush comes to the Republican
convention with more money than anticipated after rationing
everything from plane travel to office supplies to keep from going
over the federal cap on spending, his staff says.
   Although Bush doesn't have to worry about paying for the
multimillion-dollar Superdome convention, he does have to pay
related campaign costs such as housing and staff payroll.
   To make those ends meet, Bush has been forced to keep a tight
rein on campaign spending over the past few months to stay under
the $23 million primary spending limit that is set for presidential
campaigns.
   Candidates are allowed more than $4 million on top of that for
fund-raising costs, which Bush also raised and spent.
   Entering the last six weeks of the campaign, Bush began July
with less than $1 million to go before hitting the limit.
   He has only to make it through his nomination Wednesday night to
get $46 million from the federal treasury for his fall race against
Democrat Michael Dukakis. Until then, his campaign is ruled by the
primary limit.
   ``We've been penny-pinchers all along and we're very careful
with our finances,'` said finance spokeswoman Ede Holiday, who
added, ``Obviously we are very close to our spending limit.''
   She declined to say how close.
   Four Democratic state chairmen have accused Bush of overspending
the limit and filed a complaint with the Federal Election
Commission last week.
   Holiday said the campaign kept a tight budget that, as planned,
will last just through the convention.
   ``We have plenty of money to do what we want to do at the
convention,'' she said.
   Holiday would not say how much the campaign was spending for
convention activity, but said the belt-tightening in recent weeks
has left more money to spend on the convention than originally
anticipated.
   One campaign official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
it was well in excess of the $300,000 that Democrat Michael
Dukakis' staff says he spent at the Democrats' convention in
Atlanta last month.
   Some of the Bush staff are working voluntarily until they go on
the general election payroll after the nomination, said Holiday.
   Staff members have talked about having to scrimp on office
supplies, and Bush restricted his travel sharply in the waning
weeks of the campaign to keep from topping the limit.
   The lion's share of the extravaganza in New Orleans _ including
the convention itself, communications equipment and Bush office
space in the Superdome, and balloons and banners _ will be paid for
by the Republican National Committee, and to a lesser degree the
local host committee.
   The Republicans, as the Democrats did in Atlanta, receive $9.2
million from the federal treasury to put on their conventions.
   The money comes from the same taxpayer-supported federal fund
that doles out primary matching money to the candidates and gives
each general election candidate $46 million.
   Mary Mead, deputy convention manager for communications, said
most of the money went into construction and logistics costs, while
many of the decorations inside and outside the hall were paid for
by the city of New Orleans.
   The Louisiana Host Committee's efforts centered on promoting New
Orleans through such projects as decorating the airport, providing
media kits about the area, and plastering the city with banners and
billboards reading ``New Orleans, Host to the Future and the 1988
Republican Convention,'' said Bonnie Hymel, executive director of
the committee's media and hospitality effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
