<DOCNO> AP880812-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma-Analysis     08-12 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Analysis,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Clear Indication Of How Burma Revolt Will End</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those who follow the rapidly moving
events are uncertain of the outcome in Burma, where unarmed
citizens are angry enough to confront rifles and the government is
willing to shoot them down.
   Diplomats and other observers sketch a variety of finales to the
drama that began with President Sein Lwin's accession to power late
last month and has progressed through increasing levels of popular
protest and violence.
   Security forces initially were restrained and disciplined, but
soldiers opened fire Tuesday on thousands of demonstrators in the
streets of Rangoon. Official reports say protest has spread to
virtually every town and city in the the Southeast Asian nation of
38 million people.
   High school students in their mid-teens were the vanguard but
witnesses say Buddhist monks, workers and ordinary townspeople have
joined the mass denunciation of 26 years of authoritarian rule and
economic deprivation.
   These are some of the results foreseen by diplomats in scenarios
by diplomats in Rangoon and Bangkok:
   _ Continued ruthless suppression of all protest by Sein Lwin and
a loyal army until all opponents are rooted out or cowed into the
passivity that characterized the political scene until recent
events.
   _ The ouster of Sein Lwin by former strongman Ne Win, who
overthrew the democracy in 1962. He formally retired from political
life last month, but some believe he still pulls the strings.
   _ An intensified and bloody uprising that would compel the army,
Burma's most powerful institution, to overthrow the government and
install a more moderate leadership.
   Unlike the Philippines or South Korea, where mass popular
protest achieved greater political freedom, Burma has no prominent
personalities advocating democracy who could lead the growing but
diffuse opposition.
   Aung Gyi, the most outspoken critic of the system, is 70 and
retired from politics after falling out with Ne Win in the early
1960s. Sein Lwin has jailed the former army officer, a relative
liberal.
   Protesters seem to illustrate this dearth of political
alternatives by resurrecting old symbols and the images of leaders
long dead.
   Rangoon marchers carry portraits of Aung San, the dashing
fighter for Burmese independence who was assassinated in 1947, and
wave the peacock flag of days when Burma struggled against its
British colonial masters.
   Like the Philippines under Ferdinand E. Marcos, Burma has a
strong military in which increasing disaffection is reported. Some
diplomats speculate that elements of the army, as in the ``people
power'' revolution that ousted Marcos, could provide the muscle to
bring down Sein Lwin, a former general.
   The military has been Burma's privileged class since Ne Win
seized power, however. Retired or active military officers
currently hold all but two Cabinet positions, and even the rank and
file has privileges civilians do not enjoy.
   Ne Win assiduously built, or bought, the loyalty of a generation
and more of army officers. Although his proclaimed ideology has
been a mix of socialist economics, Buddhism and isolationism,
political control has rested with the military and the
army-dominated government political party.
   ``I find it hard to believe such a man steeped in power since
1962 giving it all up in one fell swoop. Something smells here,''
said a Western diplomat based in Rangoon who spoke on the condition
he not be identified.
   He added, however, that if Ne Win returned the question remained
whether the people now would accept ``the lesser of two evils''
even if he pursued urgently needed economic reforms.
   Some protesters still call the government the ``Ne Win regime''
and demand restoration of democracy. Marchers applauded loudly this
week when passing the U.S. Embassy in Rangoon.
   Others say they are fighting for socialism minus Sein Lwin, who
is widely hated for ruthlessly suppressing dissent since the 1960s.
   ``The young people haven't known anything in their lives but
this system,'' a Burmese intellectual said recently. ``They don't
know exactly what they want or how to get it.''
   Many Westerners arriving from Rangoon say Burmese from many
walks seem certain of one thing: They have had enough of leaders
who provide neither freedom nor rice.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Denis D. Gray is Bangkok bureau chief of The
Associated Press in Bangkok and has reported on and from Burma for
a decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
