<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOPConvention-Schedule     08-12 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Convention-Schedule,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bush Rivals To Address Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the main order of business of the
four-day Republican National Convention next week is to nominate
George Bush for president, all of his vanquished rivals will get
some time in the spotlight.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, New York Rep. Jack Kemp and television
evangelist Pat Robertson are to speak in prime time, according to a
draft of the convention schedule released Thursday by the
Republican National Committee.
   The others _ former Secretary of State Alexander Haig and former
Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont _ will address the 2,277 GOP delegates
on Monday, just before Maureen Reagan, the president's daughter and
co-chairman of the Republican National Committee.
   Russian comic Yakov Smirnoff will kick off the convention Monday
morning by leading the delegates in the pledge of allegiance. Other
celebrities scheduled to recite the pledge later in the week during
prime time include musician Lionel Hampton and Charlton Heston.
   The president _ in his farewell convention address _ will speak
Monday night, following a tribute to his wife, Nancy.
   Actress Helen Hayes will participate in a salute to senior
citizens during the Tuesday morning session before the delegates
get down to the work of dealing with reports from the convention's
committees.
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean will deliver the convention's
keynote address Tuesday night, followed at the podium by former
President Ford.
   Wednesday night, the delegates will give their presidential
nomination to Bush, following a nominating speech by Sen. Phil
Gramm of Texas. Among the six seconding speakers are Penn State
football Coach Joseph Paterno, Rep. Robert Dornan of California and
Jeb Bush, the vice president's son.
   Also on the list are Republican activist Ninfa Lorenzo of
Houston, who says she plans to speak Spanish during her remarks,
Kansas City Councilwoman Joanne Collins and Federal Maritime
Commission Chairman Elaine Chao.
   On Thursday night, the delegates will pick a vice presidential
nominee and hear the acceptance speeches by Bush and his running
mate before adjourning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
