<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WesternSahara     08-12 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Western Sahara,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Hopes For 1988 Independence Referendum In Western
Sahara</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
says he hopes an independence referendum can be held in the Western
Sahara this year and offered detailed proposals to end the
guerrilla war there.
   The U.N. chief urged Morocco and the Polisario pro-independence
movement to respond to his proposals by Sept. 1. Details of the
ideas were not released.
   Morocco has occupied the territory since the Spanish colonial
administration withdrew from what had been the Spanish Sahara
protectorate in 1975. Fighting with the Marxist-led Polisario
movement began soon after.
   Morocco and Mauritania jointly ran the Western Sahara until
Mauritania withdrew from the conflict in 1979. Morocco's battle
with Polisario has engaged most of its 100,000-man army and has
cost Morocco up to $2 million a day.
   Nearly 10,000 people have been killed in the war.
   Perez de Cuellar presented his proposals for organizing a
cease-fire and a referendum on Thursday to representatives of
Morocco and Polisario, and to the Organization of African Unity,
Algeria and Mauritania.
   He said details are being kept confidential, but added that the
``rather long document'' was the result of extensive discussions
among the parties, so ``they won't be extremely surprised'' by his
suggestions.
   ``The current chairman of the OAU and I have carried out a
number of consultations with the parties to the conflict in order
to find the means to bring about practical conditions which would
allow the people of the Western Sahara to freely exercise their
right to self-determination through a credible referendum, and
without military or administrative constraints,'' said the
secretary-general.
   Asked if the referendum will be held this year, Perez de Cuellar
replied: ``That is our hope.''
   Spain made little effort to develop the 110,000-square-mile
wilderness, about the size of Colorado. It is rich in phosphates
and possibly potash and iron ore but had a population of only about
75,000 when Spain pulled out.
   Polisario claims to have 16,000 heavily armed guerrillas
operating in the desert. Moroccan officers estimate guerrilla
strength at fewer than 4,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
