<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     08-12 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Wound Troops, Damage Helicopters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels ambushed a military
patrol on Negros island, wounding five soldiers, and damaged three
helicopters that were flying in reinforcements, the military said
today.
   The military's Visayas Command said New People's Army guerrillas
ambushed the patrol Thursday near Guihulngan, 350 miles southeast
of Manila.
   Six helicopters were dispatched from nearby Bacolod with
reinforcements but the rebels fired on the aircraft. Two of the
helicopters were forced to land at the scene but the third returned
to base with the wounded, the report said.
   There was no report of rebel casualties. The wounded include the
patrol leader, Lt. Juanito Bero, and the gunner of one of the
damaged helicopters, the report said. It did not say what happened
to the helicopters and helicopter crews that were forced to land at
the scene of the battle.
   A reporter for a Bacolod radio station, DYEZ, quoted soldiers as
saying one civilian militiaman was also wounded and seven others
were missing.
   Civilian militiamen often accompany soldiers on patrols in rebel
areas.
   The military said it could not confirm that any militiamen were
missing because reports were sketchy.
   The New People's Army, the armed wing of the Communist Party of
the Philippines, has been waging an insurgency to establish a
Marxist state for 19 years.
</TEXT>
