<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CircleK-AIDS     08-12 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Circle K-AIDS,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Health Plan Exclusions Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's second-largest convenience
store chain says it will postpone a plan to deny medical benefits
to employees with ailments related to drugs, alcohol or AIDS
because of a ``general misunderstanding'' of the policy.
   Adopted in January by Circle K stores, the policy met with a
storm of protest when it was publicly disclosed last week.
   The company said it would no longer pay for employees' medical
care for illnesses resulting from ``personal lifestyle decisions,''
including the use of alcohol or drugs, self-inflicted injury, or
infection with acquired immune deficiency syndrome through any
means other than blood transfusions.
   The policy applied to about 3,000 Circle K employees hired since
Jan. 1. The company said no employee has been denied coverage so
far as a result of it. Since the company is self-insured, its
health care plan is not covered by state regulations banning such
restrictions. Most health insurance policies exclude coverage for
suicide attempts but cover claims related to AIDS and substance
abuse.
   The Phoenix-based company has about 26,000 employees at more
than 4,000 stores in 27 states. It also has about 800 other stores
in Japan, the United Kingdom, Canada, Indonesia and Hong Kong. It
had sales of about $2 billion last year.
   Karl Eller, Circle K Corps.'s chairman and chief executive
officer, announced Thursday that the plan's implementation would be
delayed while it was reviewed by company officials.
   ``A general misunderstanding of the policy has arisen and that
needs to be clarified,'' Eller said. ``We were and still are
extremely concerned about containing costs of medical insurance for
employees.''
   Ed Buck, a Phoenix gay-rights activist, met with company
officials Wednesday in an attempt to negotiate a change in the
policy. He called the announcement ``an excellent, excellent
signal.''
   Buck said he and Circle K officials agreed on four points:
   _There are ambiguities in the corporation's health-benefits
policy.
   _The intention of the policy, which is to cut the cost of health
insurance, ``is legitimate and well-meaning.''
   _The policy is open to review and possible revision.
   _The company and the gay-rights activists will meet again Monday.
   Ray Cox, a Circle K senior vice president, said the company
agreed that clarification of the policy was needed but noted the
agreement was to review the policy, not cancel it.
   ``I don't feel we're conceding anything at this point,'' he said.
   Buck, who gained prominence by directing the 1987 campaign to
recall then-Gov. Evan Mecham, said the primary problem with the
policy was that the company became the judge of its employees'
lifestyles.
   ``That creates two problems,'' Buck said. ``One is that the
employee doesn't know whether he is covered in any given instance.
The second is that it creates an administrative nightmare for the
company in deciding on a case-by-case basis what claims it will pay
for.''
   Buck said some gay activists favored picketing and boycotts of
Circle K stores, but he counseled against it.
   ``I think that they (Circle K) are willing and anxious to open
good-faith negotiations,'' Buck said.
   ``I told them that this is an emotional issue and they (the gay
community) are reacting emotionally,'' he said. ``I told the other
side that they must recognize the company's goal of
cost-containment is legitimate, but the policy became confused,
muddled and misdirected.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
