<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Waldheim     08-12 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Waldheim,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Says Waldheim Named Allied Prisoner Saboteur, Who Was
Then Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of Parliament says Austrian President
Kurt Waldheim, while an officer in the German army during World War
II, caused the execution of a British prisoner who led an Allied
escape attempt.
   Robert Rhodes James, a Conservative Party member, said Thursday
that Waldheim should be tried on war crimes charges.
   The House of Commons member told The Associated Press by
telephone that he based his accusations on a British historian's
claims that Waldheim signed a Germany army intelligence report
labeling British army Capt. David Warren a saboteur.
   The action constituted a virtual death sentence for Warren,
because Nazi leader Adolf Hitler issued a standing order to execute
Allied commandos linked to sabotage, said Rhode James.
   ``We're talking about murder _ cold-blooded murder of a prisoner
of war, and that is a war crime,'' Rhodes James said. ``It didn't
happen in the heat of battle. It was a cold-blooded criminal act.''
   Rhodes James headed Waldheim's private office from 1973-76 when
Waldheim, elected president two years ago, served as U.N.
secretary-general in New York.
   Waldheim has denied any role in executing Allied prisoners when
he served as an intelligence lieutenant for Gen. Alexander Lohr's
Army Group E, which committed many atrocities in the Balkans.
   Rhodes James said Waldheim, 69, should be prosecuted.
   ``I wouldn't particularly worry about a lower-ranking person,
but Waldheim was a former secretary-general to the U.N. and is now
head of state in Austria,'' Rhodes James said.
   In March 1986, it was revealed that Waldheim was a German army
lieutenant in the Balkans from 1942 to 1945 after Hitler's troops
took control of Austria.
   The World Jewish Congress has accused Waldheim of massacres of
Yugoslav and Greek civilians and partisans, as well as deportation
of Greek Jews to Nazi death camps. He was also accused of
involvement in a slaughter of about 70,000 people at the Yugoslav
town of Kozarra in 1942.
   Waldheim has denied these accusations.
   Even so, the debate over his war past has badly marred relations
between Austria and Israel and frayed Austria's ties with the
United States and Britain as well. The U.S. Justice Department in
1987 placed Waldheim on its list of aliens prohibited from entering
the United States.
   The Australian-born Warren belonged to the clandestine Special
Operations Executive but wore his regular army uniform while
leading an escape attempt of Allied prisoners of war across Greece,
Rhodes James said.
   The uniform entitled the captured officer to be treated as an
ordinary POW, Rhodes James said. But he charged that Waldheim
interrogated the prisoner and signed the report declaring him a
saboteur. A firing squad executed Warren on May 15, 1944.
   Rhodes James said his charges stem from conversations with
Christopher Montague Woodhouse, a historian and former member of
Parliament who ran Allied operations in Greece from 1943 to 1945.
   Woodhouse's report on Warren is to be published later this month
in Encounter magazine. Meanwhile, Woodhouse has refused to talk to
the press.
   Rhodes James said he has not read the report but discussed its
contents with Woodhouse, 71, now a professor of Greek studies at
King's College, London.
</TEXT>
