<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Calls Anti-Government Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's largest opposition
organization called for a demonstration Sept. 4 to demand a
``national salvation government'' and protest a recent crackdown by
the leftist government.
   Ramiro Gurdian, vice president of the Nicaraguan Democratic
Coordinate, said Thursday the demonstration will take place in
Managua's downtown Plaza of the Revolution. The Coordinate groups
opposition labor and business organizations and political parties.
   There was no immediate comment from the Sandinista government,
but there is little chance it will grant the necessary permit. The
government rejected two opposition requests to stage demonstrations
in the past month.
   Police violently broke up the last Coordinate demonstration held
July 10 in Nandaimes, about 40 miles south of the capital. Dozens
of people were injured and more than 40 opposition figures detained
during the protest, which had been authorized by the government.
   The Sandinistas closed down Radio Catolica, the Roman Catholic
radio station, and slapped a 15-day suspension against the
opposition newspaper La Prensa for their coverage of the incident.
   The Sandinistas also expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and
seven other U.S. diplomats from Nicaragua, saying Melton
collaborated with the domestic opposition to destabilize the
government.
</TEXT>
