<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Panel Proposed to Police House of Reps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressman, saying they want to restore
the public's faith in Congress, have introduced legislation to
create an independent panel to investigate alleged ethics
violations in the House of Representatives.
   Reps. Joseph DioGuardi, R-N.Y., and Barney Frank, D-Mass., also
proposed creating the office of an independent inspector general to
audit financial matters of the House and its members.
   ``What we're trying to deal with here is the perception that
congressmen are not fulfilling their public trust,'' DioGuardi said
at a news conference Thursday.
   He said the public ranks congressmen ``just below snake oil
salesmen'' when it comes to ethics.
   Both congressmen stressed the conflicts inherent in the current
system, nder which House members police themselves through the
Committee on Standards of Official Conduct. That panel, composed of
an equal number of Republicans and Democrats, enforces the code of
conduct and recommends to the full House sanctions against members
who violate the code.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Costs Americans a Cool $255 Million Extra in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans spent $4.3 billion on air
conditioning in July, which the government says is more than a
quarter-billion dollars more than usual for the month.
   The hot month, which brought high temperatures and little rain
to much of the nation, added some $255 million more to the national
air conditioning bill than would be expected in a normal July, the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration reported Thursday.
   That averaged out to a July air conditioning bill of $104 for
the typical home, $6 more than normal.
   Only the west south central states _ Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas
and Oklahoma spent less on cooling than in a typical July. The
highest increase were in the East North Central region _ including
the Great Lakes States _ which showed an average bill $16 more than
normal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Official, Researcher Differ Over Response to Global Warming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Reagan administration official says more
research is needed on the effects of the ``greenhouse effect,''
even though a private weather researcher told Congress action is
needed soon to slow the global warming.
   Donna Fitzpatrick, associate undersecretary of energy, told a
congressional panel Thursday that ``scientific uncertainties must
be reduced before we commit the nation's economic future to drastic
and potentially misplaced policy responses.''
   But climatologist Stephen Schneider told the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee the administration is expressing
``political value judgments, not scientific opinions.''
   ``We should not use platitudes about scientific uncertainty as
an excuse for inaction,'' Schneider, who works at the National
Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., testified.
