<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Gulf     08-12 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Gulf,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Prepares For Battle After End Of Gulf War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's military chief of staff says his
troops have already held drills to prepare for possible warfare
with Arab armies after the Iran-Iraq war ends.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of staff, said on Israel
television Thursday his troops ``completed a maneuver based on the
presumption that the war had ended and (Iraqi) forces are free. We
also took Syria into account.''
   Iraq has sent ground forces to fight Israel in three of the five
wars the Jewish state has fought since 1948.
   Shomron said his troops held the maneuvers two weeks before
Iran's July 18 announcement that it was ready to accept a
cease-fire with Iraq.
   ``This was because of an assessment of the situation,'' Shomron
said Wednesday night. ``We knew this war was winding down.''
   The U.N.-mediated cease-fire, announced Monday, is to take
effect Aug. 20.
   Israel has monitored the war carefully, believing the outcome
has an important bearing on Israel's security and the future of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Military and intelligence officers said Israel was safer while
Iran and Iraq were fighting each other, but they worried about
Israel becoming an eventual target for Iraqi forces that were
better trained as a result of the war.
   While it will take Iraq some time to recover from its losses
after the 8-year-old conflict, ``in the longer run, this will mean
a bigger danger for Israel,'' reserve duty Brig. Gen. Aharon
Levran, a former intelligence officer, told foreign reporters at a
government-sponsored briefing.
   ``The gulf war appears to be ending, and I don't add `Thank God'
... Israel will have to think about it and start preparing,'' said
Levran, an analyst at Tel Aviv University's Jaffee Center for
Strategic Studies.
   Levran said any future war between Israel and Syria ``will be
much more costly, more bloody, than it has been in the past''
because Damascus has significantly improved the quantity and
quality of its military equipment.
   He noted Syria recently had developed chemical warheads for its
surface-to-surface missiles.
   Also, Syria had doubled its number of ground forces from five to
10 divisions and increased the number of tanks from 1,700 to 4,000
since the 1973 Golan Heights war, he said.
   Damascus also has obtained advanced weaponry from the Soviet
Union and more than doubled the number of attack aircraft in its
arsenal, Levran said. He refused to give a figure.
   On the other hand, he said Syria's military expenditures had
forced it to cut back on the size and training of its ground forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
