<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Earthquake, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Rocks Tokyo Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rocked the Tokyo area today,
halting many subways and rail lines and bringing elevators to a
stop. There were no immediate reports of serious damage or
injuries, police said.
   Office workers in Tokyo scrambled under desks during the quake,
and trains on all three of the region's high-speed ``bullet'' train
lines and many other rail lines were stopped while workers checked
tracks for damage, officials said.
   The earthquake struck at about 2:15 p.m. and registered 5.3 on
the Richter scale, Central Meteorological Agency officials said.
   The quake was centered in southern Chiba prefecture, about 40
miles southeast of Tokyo, the agency said.
   The Japan Broadcasting Corp. said residents of Tateyama, near
the epicenter, ran from buildings when the rumbling began.
Elevators in many buildings stopped automatically at the closest
floor and opened their doors, as they are designed to do during
earthquakes.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable
damage, 6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
