<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     08-12 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Recalls President Proposing Marriage For Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost two years after the fact, the story is
out that President Reagan proposed to a Louisiana state senator's
wife for him.
   ``I didn't think there was a chance he would do it,'' said Sen.
Fritz Windhorst, a member of the Louisiana delegation to the
Republican National Convention.
   ``It was obviously a once-in-a-lifetime experience from more
than one point of view,'' said Barbara Turner, who became Mrs.
Windhorst thanks in part to a gentle shove from the president.
   Turner said she and Windhorst, who had been dating for about 18
months, attended a luncheon in September 1986 for Henson Moore, a
Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate.
   In a line of well-wishers meeting Reagan, Windhorst asked the
president for the unique favor. ``He said, `I'll do it. I never get
to do good things like this,''' Windhorst recalled.
   Reagan, said Turner, ``walked up to me, took both of my hands
and smiled at me broadly (and said) `It's been a long time since I
proposed to anyone,' which took me aback.''
   Turner said she was left speechless and ``looking devoid of any
intelligence whatsoever. He said, `I think you should marry the
senator.''
   She said she remained silent before the president said, ``Honey,
say something. Say yes.'' Turner said she finally ``gasped a yes
out'' and ``kind of wobbled off at that point.''
   Reagan wrote the couple a congratulatory note after they were
married Nov. 22, 1986, Windhorst said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kansas Delegates Pushing Dole in V.P. Stakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kansas delegation to the Republican
National Convention is actively pushing to have favorite son Bob
Dole named as the party's vice presidential nominee.
   Gov. Mike Hayden, the delegation's chairman, said Thursday he
and other state GOP officials have met with Vice President George
Bush's campaign to discuss the possible selection of Dole, the
Senate minority leader, as Bush's running mate.
   Dole asked state party officials Wednesday not to put his name
in nomination for the slot, a move some Kansans interpret as a sign
Dole is a top candidate to be the vice presidential nominee.
   ``In order for George Bush to win, he must be strong in the
Midwest,'' Hayden told reporters at a news conference. ``George
Bush needs a boost, and Bob Dole is the one to do it in the
heartland.''
   Bush aides leaked polling results Thursday conducted for the
campaign that showed Dole helping Bush more than other running
mates, but not by a margin the campaign aides consider significant.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Bush Weak On Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush has done little
to further civil rights and has supported policies that have
weakened the national defense, says former Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson.
   ``George Bush is weak on defense,'' Jackson said Thursday night
to delegates to a national convocation of the Christian Church
(Disciples of Christ).
   ``We've got more money spent, more weapons used, fewer
friends,'' he said.
   Jackson said misguided foreign policies of the Reagan
administration have undermined the United States' interests in
Central America and the Middle East.
   He also accused Bush of not speaking out in support of civil
rights.
   ``Back in '81, Reagan threatened not to extend the Voting Rights
Act, the most basic right in a democracy. Bush was silent,'' he
said. ``In 1988, Reagan vetoed the Civil Rights Restoration Act.
Bush was silent.''
