<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-12 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Move Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened lower and then moved up
slightly against the Japanese yen in Tokyo on Friday, while stock
prices moved higher.
   The U.S. currency finished the week's trading at 133.05 yen,
down 1.02 yen from Thursday's close. After opening at 132.85 yen,
it recovered moderately, fluctuating during the day between 132.77
yen and 133.30 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average,
which gained 230.11 points Thursday, added an additional 48.53
points or 0.17 percent Friday, finishing the day at 27,833.51.
   Traders said the dollar moved higher after Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa told reporters Friday morning that exchange rates
should be left to market forces.
   They said the market reacted favorably to Miyazawa's comment,
taken as an indication that Japanese monetary authorities are not
planning to intervene or raise interest rates in an attempt to curb
the dollar's rise.
   In mid-week trading Wednesday, the dollar had risen as high as
the 135-yen level for the first time in three weeks.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a 230.11-point winner on Thursday, gained 65.84 points to close the
morning session at 27,850.82.
   The Nikkei index, the market's main barometer, was up more than
149 points just after the opening but pulled back later in reaction
to concern over U.S. trade figures slated to be released next
Tuesday in Washington.
</TEXT>
