<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HangGlidingDeaths     08-12 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hang Gliding Deaths,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporter, Pilot Killed In Hang Glider Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>XENIA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reporter researching a story on a
hang glider pilot died along with the pilot when the craft
plummeted about 300 feet and crashed, authorities said.
   Nick Adams, a feature writer for the Springfield News-Sun, and
pilot Scott Beyer died Thursday at the Greene County Skydiving
Center about three miles east of this southwest Ohio city.
Witnesses said the glider crashed nose-first.
   Adams, 33, was doing a story on Beyer, 36, and his business,
High Attitude. Adams had gone along for the ride, taking pictures
with a camera mounted on one of the wings. A counterweight was
installed on the other wing.
   Sgt. David Albrinck of the State Highway Patrol said the
glider's tow rope may have wrapped around one wing when the craft
was banking for a turn. The tow rope is attached to a vehicle on
the ground to get the craft airborne.
   Adams, a Yellow Springs resident, had been with the paper for
three years.
   Dick Minnig, the paper's assistant city editor, said Adams
always looked for offbeat stories. ``He shined at doing people
stories,'' Minnig said.
   Sky-diving instructor Rob Seibel of Skydive Greene County
described Beyer, also of Yellow Springs, as an expert hang glider
pilot.
</TEXT>
