<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugSweep     08-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Sweep,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Kingpin Named During Arrest Sweep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed drug kingpin in prison and 36 other
people, including his parents, wife and girlfriend, were charged
with running a narcotics cartel linked to the assassination of a
police officer and nine other murders.
   Lorenzo ``Fat Cat'' Nichols, serving a 25-years-to-life sentence
for state narcotics and weapons law violations, was accused of
controlling the $20-million-a-year organization through his
lieutenants and family members.
   According to a federal complaint released Thursday, Nichols
continued to direct his drug operations from jail.
   ``This is really a story of how a handful of women kept this
drug operation together while their men were in prison,'' said Sgt.
Michael McGuiness.
   James Fox, head of the FBI's New York office, described the
Nichols group as ``the most active and most vicious drug ring in
New York City.''
   Thirty people _ including Nichols' parents, sister, three
nieces, wife, girlfriend and brother-in-law _ were arrested in a
sweep Thursday. Others were arrested out of state, said police
spokesman Joseph Gallagher.
   They were charged with distributing heroin and cocaine.
   No murder charges were filed. But the federal complaint stated
that members of the Nichols organization are suspected in at least
10 narcotics-related homicides since 1985, including that of police
Officer Edward Byrne and Nichols' parole officer, Brian Rooney, in
1985.
   Byrne was shot execution-style in February as he sat in his
police cruiser, guarding the home of a drug witness.
   ``The death of Officer Byrne was a catalyst to all of us in law
enforcement,'' said U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney. ``Whatever made
them commit that insane act of murder has backfired on this
organization.''
   Nichols, his alleged lieutenant, Howard ``Pappy'' Mason, and
others were previously charged with Rooney's murder.
   The complaint attributed its information to 12 confidential
informants and taps on the phones at the house of Nichols' sister,
Viola, and a deli which allegedly served as a Nichols headquarters.
   The Nichols organization was said to include a network of drug
suppliers, baggers, dealers and money handlers who distribute
heroin and cocaine throughout the New York City area.
</TEXT>
