<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BizWeekProbe     08-12 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Broker Agrees to Plead Guilty, Cooperate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former stockbroker implicated in the widening
insider trading scandal involving leaked copies of Business Week
magazine has agreed to plead guilty to the first criminal charge
leveled in the case.
   William Dillon, 33, of Old Lyme, Conn., also agreed to cooperate
with federal investigators probing the alleged scheme to gain and
trade on advance knowledge of information due to appear in Business
Week's ``Inside Wall Street'' column.
   Dillon, a former Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker, was charged
with a single count of wire fraud in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan.
   As a formality, he pleaded innocent before a federal magistrate
but his attorney, Henry Putzel, and U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani
said Dillon subsequently would plead guilty.
   Dillon also agreed to give up all profits and to plead guilty to
a similar charge _ yet to be filed _ at federal court in
Connecticut, prosecutors said.
   He faces a maximum five-year prison sentence and $250,000 fine
on each wire fraud count.
   The U.S. attorney in Connecticut, Stanley A. Twardy Jr., said
Dillon agreed to cooperate with the investigation into securities
trading by people using information misappropriated from
McGraw-Hill Inc., publisher of Business Week, and R.R. Donnelley &
Sons Co., which prints the magazine.
   Seven Donnelley employees have been fired or have quit since the
printer began an in-house investigation.
   Dillon was charged with using the telephone in conjunction with
the inside information to buy 3,000 shares of Regency Electronics
Inc. common stock in January 1987.
   Federal court documents stated that, all told, Dillon allegedly
purchased 129 different securities between May 1986 and last month,
making some $94,000 in profits.
   Dillon's mother, Elizabeth Baird, whose brokerage account at
another firm allegedly was used for making trades on the inside
information, will have to give up her profits, although officials
had placed no fixed sum on that amount, Giuliani said.
   Giuliani said that as part of Dillon's cooperation agreement,
his mother would not be charged with wrongdoing.
   Merrill Lynch fired Dillon, a financial consultant in its New
London, Conn., office, late last month.
   The dismissal came a week after Business Week said it was
probing pre-publication trading linked to ``Inside Wall Street.''
The Securities and Exchange Commission and the major stock
exchanges also have launched investigations.
   At the time, Merrill Lynch said Dillon was fired after company
lawyers uncovered records suggesting stocks might have been bought
and sold on tips from articles due to be published in the magazine.
   Court papers indicated Dillon and an unidentified person paid
various Donnelley employees $20 to $30 an issue for advance copies
of Business Week on Thursday mornings. The magazine generally was
made available to the public after the markets closed Thursday
afternoons.
   Dillon was accused of trading Thursday mornings on the
securities of companies that got a favorable mention in ``Inside
Wall Street.''
</TEXT>
