<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AnonymousSources     08-12 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anonymous Sources,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Guidelines For Use Of Anonymous Sources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A confidential source whose identification by
the Star Tribune resulted in a jury verdict against the newspaper
has prompted new guidelines at the newspaper on using anonymous
sources.
   In a front page announcement Thursday, the newspaper described
the new guidelines to its readers.
   ``We know that some readers are concerned about recent questions
involving the use of anonymous sources in the Star Tribune. So are
we, and we're taking action to deal with those questions,'' Star
Tribune Executive Editor Joel Kramer wrote.
   The announcement follows a verdict granting damages to a public
relations man who gave the paper and other news organizations
information about a political opponent's shoplifting charge six
days before a 1982 election. He gave the information on condition
he would remain anonymous and claimed in his suit that
identification of him by the Star Tribune and the St. Paul Pioneer
Press Dispatch hurt his career.
   Kramer also said a recent Star Tribune article on the University
of Minnesota Hospital that reported on ``alleged wrongdoing on the
basis of anonymous sources who didn't have firsthand knowledge to
support their account'' illustrated the risks to fairness and
accuracy that can result from use of anonymous sources.
   In a third recent incident, the Star Tribune recalled all
640,000 copies of its Sunday magazine scheduled to appear one
weekend because, Kramer said, a person quoted by name in the
magazine said she had been promised anonymity.
   The guidelines make three main points, Kramer said:
   _While anonymous sources are a critical element of some
important stories, frequent reliance on them increases the risk of
inaccurate or unfair journalism and can adversely affect the
newspaper's credibility with readers.
   _Anonymous statements and quotes should be published only when
necessary to provide important information and only after both a
reporter and editor are satisfied that the paper is meeting its
standards for accuracy and fairness.
   _Promises of confidentiality to sources that are not in the
newspaper's or the readers' best interests should be avoided, but
once made, will be honored except in the most extraordinary
circumstances.
   Kramer said the guidelines ``replace the mostly unwritten
guidelines and standards we've relied on before.''
   On July 22, a Hennepin County District Court jury found that the
Star Tribune and the Pioneer Press Dispatch broke a contract by
identifying Dan Cohen as a confidential source for a story and must
pay him a total of $700,000 in damages. The newspapers are
appealing the verdict.
   Reporters for the two newspapers, who separately accepted court
documents from Cohen on condition his identity not be revealed,
were overruled by their editors, who decided to name Cohen.
   Kramer said that, under the new guidelines, ``a reporter should
not promise anonymity in a situation similar to Cohen's, but if the
reporter makes such a promise, the editors will honor it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
