<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CincinnatiArchbishop     08-12 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cincinnati Archbishop,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati Archbishop Daniel Pilarczyk,
dressed in a bathrobe and pajamas, waved as a nurse wheeled him out
of Good Samaritan Hospital 2{ weeks after brain surgery.
   ``It's the best I can do,'' he said said in a strong, clear
voice. ``My doctor won't let me do any more.''
   The spiritual leader of 545,000 Roman Catholics in 19 Ohio
counties was released Thursday with the assurance that his recovery
would be complete. He will rest at home for two weeks, doctors said.
   Pilarczyk, who is 54 today, underwent surgery July 25 to repair
a ruptured aneurysm, or weakened artery wall, at the base of his
brain.
   ``All his mental functions are 100 percent intact. There will be
no long-term effects of the surgery,'' said Dr. Thomas Brott.
   During his recuperation, Pilarczyk will conduct no business,
said the Rev. Ted Kosse, the archdiocese's spokesman. Auxiliary
Bishop James Garland is running the archdiocese in Pilarczyk's
absence.
   The aneurysm ruptured while Pilarczyk was vacationing in
Gatlinburg, Tenn. He was airlifted to Cincinnati by helicopter.
   His recovery went smoothly until July 28, when he suffered a
common side effect of the surgery called an arterial spasm, which
narrows the artery so blood cannot get through. He was given an
experimental drug called nicardipine, which relaxes the artery wall
and prevents further spasms.
   About 5,000 of the 25,000 people who survive burst aneurysms
each year die from arterial spasms after surgery.
</TEXT>
