<DOCNO> AP880812-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IntensiveCare     08-12 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intensive Care,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Intensive-Care Patients Would Undergo Treatment Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study finds that most elderly patients who
survived one life-threatening illness would submit to intensive
care a second time, but doctors say that finding leads to serious
questions about the use of resources.
   ``We undertook this study to help doctors deal with one dilemma
_ when to use life-sustaining treatment _ and we've come up with
another,'' said Dr. Marion Danis, one of the authors of the study
published in today's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   The subjects of the study were 160 people, 55 or older, who were
admitted to intensive care at North Carolina Memorial Hospital in
Chapel Hill for at least 24 hours during 1983, the authors said.
   Of those interviewed, 74 percent later reported they would be
completely willing to undergo intensive care again to prolong
survival for any period, even as brief as one month, the study said.
   Four percent said they were unwilling to undergo more intensive
care for any period. Of the remaining 22 percent, most expressed
varying preferences depending on duration of survival.
   ``The patients in our study are saying they want to receive
highly technical care under almost any condition _ as late as the
last month of their life,'' Ms. Danis of the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill said Thursday.
   ``And our society is going to have to think about what's the
most appropriate use of our medical-care resources. It may turn out
that these are wishes that will prove very difficult to fill.''
   The patients' preferences appeared to hold true regardless of
quality of life, life expectancy, age, severity of illness, length
of stay or intensive-care cost, the study found.
   Families surveyed on behalf of patients who had died or been
left incompetent after intensive-care treatment felt the same way,
indicating the feeling did not depend on successful treatment.
   ``You have to recognize the limitations of the study,'' Ms.
Danis said. ``The patients who provided our subjects already had
shown a willingess to undergo intensive-care treatment in the face
of one life-threatening illness. But that could also be one of its
strengths.
   ``Many times, doctors face life-sustaining decisions without any
input from the patients. This study informs physicians about the
opinions of patients who've been in that spot.''
   But one researcher questioned the finding that quality of life
concerns had just a small impact on patient preference.
   In an editorial accompanying the study, Nancy R. Zweibel of the
University of Chicago's department of medicine, said the study
dealt with quality-of-life considerations only in a general way.
   ``Evidence suggests that when faced with such decisions,
patients consider a number of more concrete factors,'' such as the
presence and level of long-term pain, likelihood of getting better,
ability for self-care and mobility, ability to think straight and
burden on family, said Ms. Zweibel, a researcher in social policy
and aging.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
