<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Nazi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Asks West Germany To Try Nazi Camp Guard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to ADD that 33,700 died at Czech
concentration camp where Maloth worked. Pickup 3rd graf pvs,
``Italian officials...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia has asked West
Germany to try a former Nazi SS concentration camp guard the
Czech's sentenced to death in absentia in 1948, the Communist daily
Rude Pravo said today.
   Czechoslovakia sentenced Anton Maloth, 76, after convicting him
of committing war crimes at the Theresienstadt concentration camp,
where about 33,700 people died. On Tuesday, Czechoslovakia asked
Italy to extradite him.
   Italian officials put Maloth on an airplane from Verona to
Munich on Wednesday, after his arrest last week at his wife's home
in the northern Italian town of Merano.
   Italy and Czechoslovakia have no extradition treaty, and Italian
law bars extraditing someone facing the death penalty. Italy does
not have capital punishment.
   West German Foreign Ministry spokesman Peter Rothen said
officials determined Maloth is a West German citizen and cannot be
extradited under its constitution.
   A West German prosecutor said Thursday that Maloth was
hospitalized near Munich with unspecified ``serious illnesses''
that will prevent interrogation for at least three weeks.
   Prosecutor Klaus Schacht, who is leading the inquiry into
Maloth's past, said he has no plans to bring criminal charges
against the former concentration camp guard.
   West German officials say Maloth, who wants to return to Italy,
is free to move about as he pleases.
   Rude Pravo said Czechoslovakia's ambassador in Bonn, Dusan
Spacil, has asked West German authorities to ``take necessary steps
to bring Maloth to court.''
   It said Czechoslovakia is handing over results of its
investigations into Maloth's past to West German authorities to
facilitate prosecution.
   The director of the national memorial in the town where the Nazi
camp was located told Rude Pravo that 2,400 documents provide
evidence of Maloth's crimes.
   The CTK news agency, which carried excerpts of the interview,
quoted Vaclav Novak as saying the crimes included ``grievous bodily
harms, killings and murders.''
   Maloth ``voluntarily and with pleasure asked to be a member of
execution squads,'' Novak told Rude Pravo.
   CTK quoted Novak as saying ``several dozen'' witnesses to
Maloth's crimes are still alive.
   Vienna-based Nazi hunter Simon Wiesenthal said Maloth hid with
his family in Italy for 15 years.
</TEXT>
