<2ND_LINE>PM-Love-Smitten Defector,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Dancer-Defector Hides At Israeli Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish dancer who defected to Israel to join
a woman he fell in love with has learned she already was engaged to
be married, Israel radio and the woman's friends said today.
   Polish officials in Israel said they would not force the dancer,
identified as Sigmund Irinauch, to return, and Israeli officials
said he could stay at least until his visa expires on Aug. 29.
   Irinauch, in the late 20s, disappeared Tuesday after his
46-member Slovianki dance company performed at a festival in the
northern port of Haifa.
   Haifa police said he defected to join an Israeli folk dancer he
met when both were performing in Canada two years ago. The daily
Maariv newspaper said Irinauch wrote regularly to the woman, who
the radio identified as Mira Katz, a nurse and a member of the Hora
Jerusalem dancing troupe.
   The woman's friends said in interviews that Irinauch told Miss
Katz he planned to defect, but she then disclosed she was engaged
to be married.
   Irinauch still decided to defect, partly because he is Jewish,
the friends said on condition of anonymity. They said Miss Katz and
her fiance, Doron Alter, agreed to help.
   The radio said Irinauch was hiding at Alter's home in the town
of Beer Yaakov near Tel Aviv. Telephone calls to the home today
went unanswered.
   Miss Katz refused to discuss the defection, except to say: ``I'm
calm. I know he has nothing to fear, and that everything will be
all right,'' the radio reported.
   Bronislaw Stavinsky, a diplomat at the Polish interest office in
Tel Aviv, said Poland would not seek the dancer's extradition, but
he was free to return to Poland if he wished.
   Under Israel's Law of Return, all Jews have the right to
automatic Israeli citizenship. The legal adviser at the Foreign
Ministry, Robert Sabel, said a non-Jewish defector could receive
political asylum also, as long as the defector proves political
persecution in his or her home country.
</TEXT>
