<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SatelliteDishPrank     08-12 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Satellite Dish Prank,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deep-Dish Prank: Ad Tries to Sell Observatory Satellite Dishes for
$500</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOCORRO, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The classified ad offering to sell an
observatory's satellite dishes worth millions for $500 was
obviously a prank to everyone but the reader who called up to buy
five.
   The ad, taken out by four students who worked as summer
employees at the observatory, appeared in Wednesday's Albuquerque
Journal. It read: ``Must go! 28 used 82 ft satellite dishes, HBO _
you bet! $25 million new, must leave state,'' and said it would
sell them for $500 or ``or best offer.''
   Rick Perley, an official with the National Radio Astronomy
Observatory whose name was listed in the ad for prospective buyers
to call, said one caller obviously thought it was the buy of a
lifetime.
   ``They wanted to reserve five of them,'' Perley said. ``We don't
know who (the would-be buyer) is. The secretary who took the call
hadn't seen the ad; she didn't know what it was he was talking
about.''
   ``It was just kind of a practical joke,'' Ed Murphy, who will be
a senior at the University of Illinois this fall, said of why he
and friends took out the ad. ``We heard it had been done once
before at an observatory in West Virginia, so we had the idea and
decided to do it.''
   ``It's very funny from their point of view,'' Perley said, ``but
we take our responsibility of having the public's money very
seriously. We can't possibly condone this. We don't want people to
think we don't do our jobs.''
   The observatory's Very Large Array cost $78 million and began
operating in 1980. Most recently it was linked with radio dishes in
California to receive signals from deep-space probe Voyager 2 as it
approaches Neptune.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
