<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Nuclear     08-12 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Nuclear,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Starts Talks on Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha
today held talks with U.S., Soviet and British diplomats on
Pretoria's joining the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, a South
African diplomat said.
   The talks took place at the U.S. mission in Vienna, said a
secretary at the mission who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The South African diplomat, who also spoke on condition of
anonymity, said a series of bilateral meetings were planned along
with the talks.
   The South African Broadcasting Corp. reported Thursday that
Botha and South African Energy Minister Danie Steyn would convey
their government's willingness to open its nuclear facilities to
international inspection.
   In the past, South Africa has refused to sign the 1969 Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty and to submit all its nuclear facilities
to inspection by the Vienna-based International Atomic Energy
Agency.
   South Africa is widely believed to have the technical capability
to produce an atomic bomb, but there is debate about whether it
actually has produced any.
   The U.S. delegation to the talks is headed by Ambassador Richard
T. Kennedy and the Soviet delegation led by Moscow's permanent
representative to the international organization in Vienna, Timer
Baev, U.S. officials said.
   The British delegation is reportedly headed by Under Secretary
John Goulden. Botha and Steyn arrived in Vienna on Thursday.
   The International Atomic Energy Agency has said it is not
invloved in the discussions.
   South Africa has been under increasing pressure at the
International Atomic Energy Agency to submit its nuclear facilities
to inspection.
   African and other Third World member countries have repeatedly
attempted to have South Africa ousted as a member, largely because
of apartheid, the policy under which the nation's 26 million blacks
have no vote in national affairs.
   At last year's general assembly, a decision on South Africa's
expulsion was postponed after Pretoria announced it was considering
joining the treaty.
   Last month, diplomats in Vienna said they expected South Africa
to make a move before the next annual general assembly of the
International Atomic Energy Agency in September.
   The United States, the Soviet Union and Britain are the three
``nuclear weapon states'' that have joined the treaty, which so far
has been signed by a total of 137 countries. France and China, two
other countries with a known nuclear weapons potential, are not
signatory to the treaty.
   Under the treaty, signatories pledge to submit their nuclear
programs to agancy controls, and the agency's inspectors must make
sure material is not diverted to other than peaceful uses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pendragon     08-12 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pendragon,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Murder Conviction in Weird Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court has upheld the
life sentence of a contractor convicted of murdering a man while
planning a bizarre plot to take over Marin County with guns and
laser beams.
   The justices voted unanimously on Thursday not to grant a
hearing on an appeal by Mark Richards, who was convicted of killing
Richard Baldwin in July 1982 while making plans for the
paramilitary takeover of the county.
   According to police, Richards originated the plot known as
Pendragon, which involved blowing up bridges and taking control of
Marin County and seceding from the United States. The plot was
never attempted.
   It came to light after Baldwin's death and did not result in any
additional criminal charges.
   Authorities said Richards and one of his young proteges, Crossan
Hoover, entered Baldwin's garage, where Hoover hit Baldwin in the
head with a baseball bat.
   Richards owed Baldwin money in his business, and police said
Hoover was told he would be helping to solve Richards' financial
problems. Hoover's murder conviction also has been upheld.
   Richards was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility
of parole for the death of Baldwin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
