<DOCNO> AP880812-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan-Floods     08-12 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Floods,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official: More Than 83,000 Houses Destroyed by Sudan Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods have destroyed about 83,000 homes in
Sudan's capital of Khartoum, more than twice the number previously
estimated, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
   The floods, which hit over the weekend after torrential rains,
caused shortages of electricity, drinking water and food in
Khartoum, a city of 4 million residents. At least 11 people were
killed, and Sudanese Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi said 1.5 million
people were left homeless.
   The United Nations said a lack of boats was hampering relief
operations for people stranded on piles of rubble.
   The Egyptian state-owned news agency quoted an unidentified
Sudanese official as saying the floods destroyed 83,240 houses in
the Khartoum area alone. Previous estimates ranged from 10,000 to
40,000.
   The new figure did not include the number of houses destroyed by
floods in eastern and northern areas of the country.
   Cairo newspapers today said Khartoum state television showed
Mahdi touring flooded areas in Khartoum and complaining that tents,
food and medicine were not reaching flood victims fast enough. He
blamed lack of coordination among government agencies.
   Among those worst hit are southern refugees, estimated at
750,000 to 1 million, who fled a 5-year-old civil war in the south
and are living in canvas, tin and mud huts on the outskirts of
Khartoum. Many of their flimsy shacks were washed away by flood
waters.
   Sudanese officials blamed the floods on inadequate drainage
systems. Last week, Khartoum and surrounding areas received 8.4
inches of rain, compared with 1.44 inches in all of 1987.
   Officials say the country faces more destruction from the annual
flooding of the Nile River in coming weeks. They said the river
level has risen dangerously after heavy rains in Sudan and
neighboring Ethiopia, whose rivers feed into the Nile.
   International aid has poured into Khartoum from Arab and West
European countries. But in Geneva, a senior U.N. official said a
lack of boats is hampering relief distribution.
   ``The problem is how to reach people,'' said Hybad Chowdhury,
senior officer at the U.N. Office of the Disaster Relief
Coordinator. ``Many have taken to high ground, on piles of rubble.
You can't commission a lot of boats like in southeast Asian
countries.''
   About 2,500 tents and 80,000 blankets have been airlifted to
Sudan, but more are needed, he said. Cash aid by the international
community so far totals $3 million.
   No disease outbreaks have been reported despite the dangers of
stagnant water, which cannot drain into Sudan's non-porous soil, he
said.
   In Geneva, the International Red Cross appealed today for more
international aid to Sudan.
   National societies and governments have contributed more than
100 tons of relief supplies, including 1 million water purification
tablets, the Red Cross said. Cash contributions through the Red
Cross totaled $840,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
