<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0438,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede UNITED NATIONS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iran Denies Iraqi Claims On Shelling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Iranian denial of shelling,
Khamenei comments, arrival of British diplomat and U.N. chemical
weapons team. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran today denied it shelled Iraqi military
positions, and President Ali Khamenei urged his forces to remain
vigilant at the front.
   Also today, a British diplomat arrived in Tehran for talks about
British and other foreign hostages held by pro-Iranian groups in
Lebanon.
   Iraq on Thursday accused Iran of shelling Iraqi military
positions near the Shatt al-Arab waterway, where the Persian Gulf
war broke out in September 1980.
   But a spokesman for the War Information Headquarters in Tehran
denied the charge as ``false propaganda,'' the official Islamic
Republic News Agency said.
   The Iraqi charge came in a statement issued by the Iraqi Mission
at the United Nations in New York. It also came three days after
U.N. chief Javier Perez de Cuellar said Iran and Iraq agreed to
observe a formal cease-fire beginning Aug. 20 with direct peace
talks to begin five days later in Geneva.
   According to the statement, which was not carried in newscasts
in Iraq, ``the Iranian armed forces bombarded Iraqi military
positions'' with howitzer fire, mortar shells and small missiles.
The Iraqi statement reported no casualties, and there was no
independent confirmation of the attack.
   Earlier this week, Iran gave Perez de Cuellar a letter pledging
it would not launch any attacks before the cease-fire begins.
   Iraq did not submit a similar letter, but Perez de Cuellar has
said he received assurances from both Iran and Iraq that they would
exercise restraint.
   Khamenei, in a prayer sermon at Tehran University, today urged
his forces to remain at the war fronts for defense of Iran, Tehran
radio reported.
   A throng of worshipers chanted ``Down with the U.S.A!'' ``Down
with the Soviet Union!'' and ``Down With Israel!'' and pledged to
obey revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The crowd was noticeably smaller than during a similar sermon
attended by an Associated Press reporter four weeks earlier.
   IRNA said British diplomat David Reddaway arrived in Tehran and
planned talks on ``mutual relations'' during his stay in the
Iranian capital.
   It did not elaborate, but before leaving London Reddaway said he
would speak with officials about the 18 foreign hostages believed
held by pro-Iranian extremists in Lebanon. The hostage held longest
is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press. He was abducted March 16, 1985.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals held by
pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists _ Anglican envoy Terry Waite,
journalist John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast man
with dual British and Irish nationality whose release is also
sought by the Irish government. Britain says it also seeks word on
Alec Collett, a New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian
abductors claim they killed him. His body was never found.
   Iran has been making conciliatory statements about relations
with Western nations since it accepted on July 18 a U.N. call for a
cease-fire in the gulf war. Iraq accepted the resolution shortly
after it was passed in July 1987.
   A U.N. fact-finding team also arrived today in the Iranian
capital to investigate allegations of Iraq's renewed use of
chemical weapons, IRNA said.
   The Iranian news agency said the four-member team of chemical
weapons experts would travel to the northwestern Kurdish town of
Oshnaviyeh in the province of West Azerbaijan.
   Iran alleges that a chemical weapon attack on the town earlier
this month injured more than 2,000 civilians. U.N. reports have
confirmed Iraq's use of chemical weapons in the past.
   A U.N. observer group with 350 officers from 24 countries is to
monitor the planned cease-fire.
</TEXT>
