<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-SovietTeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0513 08-12 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Learn New Ways To Teach About Each Other's Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to delete incorrect reference to Novosibirsk as
a republic.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and Soviet educators are learning
new ways to teach students about each other's country by grappling
with such tough issues as the death penalty in an unusual program.
   But the educators are also discovering how common their worries
are.
   ``I am struck by how much we are all in the same boat,'' said
Alexander Mitrofanovich Bannov, the principal of a secondary school
in Novosibirsk. He is one of 40 teachers, administrators and
researchers at the two-week program at Hampshire College.
   Among the many problems the groups share, he said, were ``the
evaluation of teachers and students and staff, and the improving of
education. Everybody says teachers should teach better, as if a
child was a pan into which you could pour information like water.''
   The program was planned by the Academy of Pedagogical Sciences
in the Soviet Union and Educators for Social Responsibility, a
non-profit U.S. organization with 15,000 members, founded in 1981
to help educators teach students a sense of social responsibility.
   The purpose of the education summit is to share insights into
the ways each country teaches its children about the other and to
break through the propaganda for a better understanding of the two
nations.
   Lessons about each other's country ``are fraught with problems,
strong feelings, misinformation, deeply embedded assumptions and
resistance to new information, all related to tensions in
U.S.-Soviet relations,'' said Lawrence Dieringer, associate
director of Educators for Social Responsibility.
   The program opened Tuesday with frank talks about how each group
thought the other perceived it.
   The Soviets, for example, said they thought Americans saw them
as aggressors ``trying to take over the world,'' Dieringer said.
   ``We thought that they thought there was a great disparity
between the rich and poor in our country and that we don't care
about the poor,'' he said. ``In many cases there's some kernel of
truth in these stereotypes, but they are so exaggerated ... that
they serve to distort and limit our understanding of each other.''
   Also on the agenda is an examination of each country's
textbooks, a look at educational reforms in both countries and
strategies for teaching controversial issues using human rights as
case studies.
   Thursday, the groups learned ``believing exercises,'' a way of
suspending judgment to understand other viewpoints before looking
at them critically.
   They were asked to make statements supporting the position that
``there are some crimes so horrible and so abusive that they demand
capital punishment.''
   For many participants, it was impossible to suspend their doubts
about the death penalty enough to understand how others could
support it.
   ``This issue is so loaded for me that it comes up against my
strongest bias,'' said an American woman.
   A Soviet woman said she couldn't ``imagine this institution,''
although the Soviet Union, like many U.S. states, has a death
penalty.
   The idea for the gathering was laid out in a 1987 memorandum of
cooperation between the Academy and Dieringer's group, he said. The
list of cooperative ventures also included working together on
curriculum and exchanging articles that would be published,
unedited, in each organization's respective journals.
   A team of U.S. educators visited the Soviet Union for a week
last year to plan the program and a Soviet team came to the United
States in March for further planning. The next institute, on
critical thinking, will be held next summer in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
