<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParkRiot     08-12 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Park Riot,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>81 Claim Police Brutality; Feds Enter Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor said his office and the FBI
will investigate last weekend's riot at a lower Manhattan park to
determine whether police violated federal civil rights laws.
   As of Thursday night, 81 people had filed charges of police
brutality with a city police review board.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani's office said in a statement
Thursday that it would conduct a preliminary review of the melee at
Tompkins Square Park to determine whether a formal investigation is
warranted.
   Fifty-two people were injured and seven were arrested during the
riot at the park late Saturday night and early Sunday morning. The
incident began with a protest against police enforcement of a 1
a.m. park curfew.
   Meanwhile, residents of the East Village area planned a park
cleanup, followed by a march, concert and rally protesting the
violence. The activities are expected to begin Saturday morning and
end around nightfall.
   Capt. Thomas Fahey, a police spokesman, said ``if there is not
an undue amount of people, the plan is to have nine or 10 seasoned
police officers enforce the noise laws and other laws inside the
park. If there's a lot of people, we're going to have to change our
plans.''
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward has criticized the initial
police response, saying it lacked adequate planning and that
tactical errors were made.
   However, a group representing 400 merchants sent a letter to
Ward defending the police, saying they ``do not countenance the
anti-social activities of drug addicts, vagrants and anarchists,
and we demand and expect strong police response to such
activities.''
   Ward asked four members of the review board to investigate the
brutality charges, as well as the management and planning of the
police at the scene.
   The police probe also will investigate allegations that some
officers covered their badges or took them off, in violation of
police policy.
</TEXT>
