<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiberaceTrial     08-12 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberace Trial,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entertainer's Sister Tells of Efforts to Cremate Brother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberace's 74-year-old sister sobbed as
she testified that the executor of her brother's estate talked of
his cremation even before his death.
   Angie Liberace, testifying in a lawsuit challenging her
brother's last will, said the subject came up in late January 1987
while Liberace was at Eisenhower Hospital in Palm Springs, Calif.
Liberace died Feb. 4, 1987 of complications of AIDS. She said the
entertainer's longtime attorney, Joel Strote, came to the hospital
and began discussing cremation of the entertainer at the time of
his death.
   ``He was discussing cremation before my brother even died,'' Ms.
Liberace testified. She said the subject was raised again later at
Liberace's Palm Springs home when the entertainer returned there to
die.
   ``I told him: `We're Catholics. I will never cremate my
brother,''' she said, beginning to cry.
   State District Judge Michael Wendell called a recess and the
subject was not discussed when her testimony resumed.
   Liberace was not cremated.
   Ms. Liberace said she did what she could to help the family
financially, and felt she should be compensated accordingly when
the famed pianist died.
   ``Our family went through Lee's money like gangbusters,'' she
said. ``There were a lot of expenses with my mother's health and my
brother, George, went through millions with all his wives.''
   George, who became well-known as Liberace's straight man during
his television series in the 1950s, died in 1983.
   Earlier, Ms. Liberace had testified that she was penniless while
a defense attorney countered she had been given more than $100,000
the past year from a $590,000 trust left by her brother.
   Ms. Liberace's two days of testimony came in a bitter court
battle between Strote, a Beverly Hills, Calif., lawyer who is
executor of Liberace's vast estate and five people challenging the
will signed 13 days before his death.
   In her second day of testimony Thursday, she criticized the
trust that was set up to take care of her. She said her brother had
intended for her to have everything she needed without having to be
accountable to anyone.
   ``If I didn't have this trust, I wouldn't have to answer to you
people for every piece of food I swallow,'' she testified.
``Liberace didn't intend for me to have a trust.''
   The sister is one of the plaintiffs in the case, along with
housekeepers Gladys Luckie and Dorothy McMahon, Liberace's longtime
manager, Seymour Heller, and the entertainer's companion of six
years, Cary James. The five contend Liberace was too ill to
understand more than 100 pages of documents when he signed a new
will and trust Jan. 22, 1987.
   Las Vegas attorney Richard Oshins, who prepared the will for
Strote, said the California attorney took steps to save the estate
money and consulted with Liberace before drafting the documents.
   Oshins noted that many of those in the will were given more in
the documents Strote drafted than in prior Liberace wills.
</TEXT>
