<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Shop-Suit,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Shop Class Drives Student To File Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school student claims a teacher's
advice in auto shop class steered him in the wrong direction, and
he's been driven to file suit over a botched clutch job.
   David Price is suing the Corona-Norco Unified School District
for $250 in damages, claiming he received incorrect instruction on
how to replace his car's clutch last semester.
   ``I was allowed to leave school in a malfunctioning car and had
to pay for a full clutch job privately,'' said Price, who was a
junior when he took the class. ``I also had to buy parts per
teacher's instructions that were not necessary.''
   Trial on the small claims court case is set for Aug. 29.
   Price's father, Duane, said Thursday that his son tried
unsuccessfully to get the school district to reimburse him for the
cost of the parts and repairs. The Prices decided to sue because
school administrators were unresponsive, the elder Price said.
   Bob Crank, the school district's assistant superintendent of
business services, said he had received a copy of the lawsuit
Wednesday but had not had time to study it. It would be forwarded
to the district's attorneys, he said.
   He said he was unaware of any other complaints about the auto
shop program.
</TEXT>
