<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0530 08-12 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0530,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blames Reagan Deficit For Interest Rate Jump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with Dukakis appearance, new ad,
picking up in 3rd graf pvs, ``A 10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said today that
overspending by the Reagan administration is to blame for
interest-rate increases that will raise the federal deficit $15
billion and impose hardships on families, farmers and businesses.
   The Democratic presidential nominee, speaking to a breakfast
gathering at the Virginia governor's mansion, said interest rates
would continue to rise ``if we continue to live on a credit card.''
   ``As we all know, sooner or later the bill collector comes to
the door,'' Dukakis said. ``That's what happened yesterday in the
United States of America.''
   He was referring to an increase in many banks' prime lending
rates.
   Dukakis has been criticized in Virginia because he opposes
construction of two new Navy supercarrier task forces which would
be built at the Newport News, Va., shipyard. Gov. Gerald L.
Baliles, who introduced Dukakis, said he disagreed with Dukakis on
that point but did not question his commitment to a strong national
defense.
   ``Gov. Dukakis and I may debate the individual choices we must
make, but in his commitment to the security of this nation I have
no doubts, no reservations and no hesitations,'' Balile said.
   Also today, Dukakis aides said his campaign would run a
one-minute advertisement this weekend in California and in the
Houston area. The ad, Dukakis' first since the primary campaign,
stresses his major themes, such as economic revival, and contains
footage from his acceptance speech at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Dukakis first blamed the administration for spurring the
increase in the prime lending rate in remarks he made Thursday
after touring Fort Dix in New Jersey.
   ``A 10 percent prime rate. It's 3{ in Japan,'' Dukakis said at a
rally in Hartford, Conn. ``Why? Because we haven't been able to pay
our bills for eight years in Washington, D.C.''
   Dukakis blamed the soaring federal deficit on Reagan's failure
to make ``tough choices'' on spending.
   ``We have to say no to a lot of things we'd like to say yes
to,'' Dukakis said. ``We've got to decide whether we want Star Wars
or star schools in this country.''
   ``I think it's regrettable,'' he said. ``I think it's what
happens after eight years of borrowing and spending, borrowing and
spending.''
   The Massachusetts governor spent most of Thursday trying to
establish himself as a tough leader on military and foreign policy
issues _ areas Republicans frequently cite as Dukakis' greatest
weaknesses.
   Dukakis toured Fort Dix, where he had eight weeks of basic
training after joining the Army in 1955. Earlier, he delivered a
speech in New York in which he said the country needed ``new
leadership in the White House'' prepared to carefully manage the
defense budget and negotiate further nuclear arms reductions with
the Soviet Union.
   ``Deterrence requires vigilance, and determination, and
leadership,'' Dukakis said. ``But it does not require the seemingly
endless development of new and more expensive nuclear weapons
systems, particularly when, thanks to President Reagan and
Secretary Gorbachev, we may have the best opportunity in our
lifetime to build a safer world.''
   Because of that progress, Dukakis said, a greater share of the
defense budget should be spent to improve conventional forces.
   ``We need strong, well-equipped, well-trained conventional
forces,'' Dukakis said after the tour of Fort Dix, where he met
with two men with whom he went through basic training.
   He also said the military should be prepared to help with
anti-terrorism and anti-drug operations.
   ``We have to build strong military forces in this country based
on sound planning and tough management, not wishful thinking and
blank checks,'' he said, criticizing expensive weapons systems
favored by Reagan and the current Pentagon procurement scandal.
   While in Connecticut, Dukakis attended two fund-raisers which
raised well in excess of $500,000 for the Democratic National
Committee's 1988 ``Victory Fund.''
   After a reception at the Virginia governor's mansion today,
Dukakis was headed to Jacksonville, Fla., where aides said he would
emphasize his commitment to anti-drug efforts and criticize the
Reagan administration for cutting Coast Guard funding and other
moves Dukakis contends have undermined the war on drugs.
</TEXT>
