<1ST_LINE>u i PM-MedicalConference 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medical Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0418,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Urge Reform Of Doctors' Training To Keep People Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with declaration issued. Pickup
6th graf pvs, ``He said...'' DELETES last graf pvs to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World health officials today approved
a strategy to promote better world health care by training doctors
to emphasize disease prevention and to pass this knowledge along to
their patients.
   ``We want doctors everywhere to concentrate on how to keep
people well, rather than always be thinking of new ways to cure
them when they fall ill,'' said Dr. George Miller of Clinton, N.Y.,
a former head of the Center for Educational Development at the
University of Illinois.
   The World Conference on Medical Education issued its declaration
at the close of the five-day conference today. The document sets
out principles to change and improve world health.
   ``Thousands suffer and die every day from diseases which are
preventable, curable or self-inflicted and millions have no ready
access to health care of any kind,'' said the declaration, which
was approved by 160 experts invited to the conference.
   ``The aim of medical education is to produce doctors who will
promote the health of all people _ not merely deliver curative
services to those who can afford it, or for those for whom it is
readily available,'' the declaration said.
   It set out steps for the radical reform of medical education
through cooperation with education and health ministries and
community health services.
   Dr. James Grant, executive director of the U.N. Children's Fund,
said it was now possible to improve dramatically the health of the
next generation.
   But he said parents were not being instructed on how to protect
their children at small cost from the ``great scourges'' of disease
including diarrhea, measles, tetanus, whooping cough and acute
respiratory infection.
   He said these diseases account for more than two-thirds of the
14 million child deaths in the world each year.
   Grant said ways must be found to give people the knowledge to
improve their own health.
   Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, newly appointed director-general of the
World Health Organization, told reporters that some countries had
too many doctors trained in curative medicine when the real need
was for disease prevention.
   The conference was told that Scots were turning to alternative
medicine and setting up self-help groups because of dissatisfaction
with doctors.
   ``They are doing this because they feel they are not getting
enough time or consideration or applied concern from their
doctors,'' said Linda Headland, secretary of the Scottish
Association of Local Health Councils, a liaison body of regional
health authorities.
   Mrs. Headland said women's self-help groups were set up in
Scotland to try to reduce dependence on tranquilizers, a problem
they blamed in part on doctors who prescribed the drugs over long
periods.
   ``People want more information about their treatment and they
want to be involved more in the decisions taken. They want to be
treated with a bit of dignity and respect,'' she said.
   Henry Walton, a psychiatrist, educator and president of the
Edinburgh-based World Federation for Medical Education which
organized the conference, said in an interview that too often,
doctors do not listen to their patients nor consider how to keep
them fit.
   ``They only think about them when they are ill. Medical
education must extend to take care of people in the community _ in
their homes and at work,'' Walton said.
   He said there is a serious problem in some countries of too many
doctors.
   ``Mexico, for example, has 1,500 unemployed doctors and a union
for unemployed doctors. They are taxi drivers, waiters ... Mexico
can't find the salaries to pay doctors whom they could well use,''
Walton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0093 </DOCNO>
