<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0524,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail Pounds Minnesota, North Dakota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `In northwest ...,' to delete erroneous
reference to church set on fire by lightning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled through the central United States today,
pounding Minnesota with hail the size of baseballs, while much of
the Southwest was drenched with lingering rainstorms trailing
tropical storm Beryl.
   Strong thunderstorms that formed along a stationary front
Thursday evening dumped the hail and brief heavy rains over
portions of North Dakota and central and western Minnesota. Many
windows were broken by the large hail at Marble, Minn. Hail the
size of golf balls hit Beach, N.D., and up to an inch fell at
Coleraine, Brainerd and Deep River, Minn.
   In northwest Minnesota, rainfall was heavy in some localities
such as Flom, which got half an inch in 15 minutes. An intense
thunderstorm at Ada, Minn., dumped over 1} inches.
   The remnants of Beryl brought thunderstorms and heavy rains to
parts of eastern Texas, eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas. Rain
near Austin, Texas, ranged from 1 to 4{ inches.
   High winds from severe thunderstorms over western New York late
Thursday afternoon flipped over several docks and snapped a utility
pole in Chautauqua County. The thunderstorms moved to the northeast
part of the state by early today.
   Utah was hit by high winds Thursday afternoon, with gusts of up
to 70 mph reported in Garfield County.
   Thunderstorms over Arizona caused flooding in Tucson, where
nearly three-quarters of an inch of rain fell in little over half
an hour. Scattered thunderstorms continued this morning over
portions of Arizona, Colorado, New Mexico, Florida, eastern Georgia
and lower Michigan.
   Hot temperatures remained over much of the nation Thursday.
Newark, N.J., recorded its 14th consecutive day of 90 degrees or
higher, the longest heat wave there since record keeping began in
1929.
   The high for the nation Thursday was 112 degrees at Bullhead
City, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
due to the remnants of Beryl from the middle Mississippi and lower
Missouri valleys through much of Oklahoma and Arkansas into
northeast Texas and the northern half of Louisiana. Showers and
thunderstorms were also predicted for much of Mississippi and
Alabama, the central Gulf Coast, Florida, the Great Lakes region,
the northern Plains, northeast Colorado, southeast Wyoming and
across the Southern Plateau.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 80s or 90s across
much of the nation; in the 70s along the Pacific Coast; and 100-110
degrees from central Texas into the Rio Grande Valley and across
the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Arcata, Calif., North Bend, Ore., and Flagstaff, Ariz.,
to 92 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 foggy; Boston 79 hazy; Buffalo 78 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 75 fair; Cincinnati 75 hazy; Cleveland 73 partly
cloudy; Detroit 73 foggy; Miami 77 fair; New York 78 foggy;
Philadelphia 79 foggy; Pittsburgh 73 hazy; Portland, Maine 73 hazy;
Washington 78 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 73 partly cloudy; Chicago 77 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 79 fair; Denver 69 partly cloudy; Des Moines 76
fair; Indianapolis 75 foggy; Kansas City 78 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 72 fair; Nashville 75 foggy; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 81
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 71 partly cloudy; Anchorage 56 cloudy; Las
Vegas 81 fair; Los Angeles 63 partly cloudy; Phoenix 88 fair; Salt
Lake City 67 fair; San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 57 drizzle;
Seattle 56 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 70 fair; Toronto 68 foggy.
</TEXT>
