<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--CIARecruiters     08-12 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--CIA Recruiters,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Won't Recruit at University of Colorado This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Intelligence Agency,
apparently weary of the controversy and protests surrounding its
recruiting at the University of Colorado, has decided to move off
campus this year.
   In 1986 and earlier, CIA recruiting on the Boulder campus
resulted in demonstrations and arrests.
   Some students uninterested in CIA work waded through the pickets
anyway to talk to recruiters as a sort of counterprotest,
university placement director Gordon Gray said Thursday. Many with
sincere interest stayed away. For recruitment purposes, the entire
process was inefficient, he said.
   This year, the agency will accept individual applications and
interview potential employees elsewhere, Gray said.
   ``The process avoids big one-time, one-place confrontations,''
Gray said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
