<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Insurgency     08-12 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Insurgency,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outlawed Tribal Group Agrees To End 10-year Insurgency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outlawed tribal group today agreed to
end its 10-year-old campaign for an independent homeland in the
northeastern state of Tripura, a government official announced.
   The Tribal National Volunteers signed a memorandum of
understanding with federal and state governments, India's interior
minister, Buta Singh, said in Parliament.
   Under the agreement, worked out in three months of negotiations,
the insurgents agreed to surrender their weapons within a month and
abide by the Constitution. In return, the tribal group will be
given 20 seats in the new state legislature.
   The chief minister of Tripura, S. R. Majumder, said the accord
would bring peace and stability to the state, bordering Bangladesh.
Authorities estimate nearly 600 died during the insurgency.
   The problem started in 1951 with a steady influx of settlers
from Bangladesh and parts of India. The economic and social
patterns in the state shifted when the tribe members who originally
settled the area were outnumbered.
   In the 1970s, tribal unrest gave rise to the Tribal National
Volunteers, which declared ``Independent Tripura'' as its objective
and took up arms.
   The violence escalated, and in June 1980, nearly 400 people,
mostly non-tribals, were massacred.
   The group set up its underground headquarters in the Chittagong
Hill Tracts in southern Bangladesh and started training volunteers.
   In April 1983, the leader of the underground movement, Bijay
Hrangkhawl, rejected suggestions by then-Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi for a negotiated settlement between the organization and the
state government.
   In 1984, the organization was outlawed. But the violence
continued.
   In January, 97 people were killed. Non-tribals threatened
retaliation, and the Tribal National Volunteers vowed to disrupt
scheduled state elections, prompting the federal government to
deploy the army.
   The elections were held a month later despite the threats, and
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress Party wrested control of the
state from the Marxist Communist Party.
   In May, the Tribal National Volunteers said they were willing to
negotiate a settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
