<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Punjab     08-12 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Bus Passengers Killed in Bomb Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A time bomb planted by suspected Sikh
radicals exploded today on the roof of a state-owned bus, police
said, and at least seven people were killed and 35 injured.
   The bomb exploded late this afternoon, 20 minutes after the
vehicle left the crowded bus terminal at Chandigarh for the town of
Shazadpur in neighboring Haryana state, police chief Surinder Singh
Brar said.
   Almost at the same time, police detected and defused another
time bomb planted in Chandigarh's most popular shopping center,
Brar said. Both bombs are suspected to have been planted by Sikh
militants, he added.
   Chandigarh is the joint capital of Punjab and Haryana states. A
separatist campaign by Sikh insurgents in Punjab has killed 1,680
people this year.
   ``It was an encounter with death,'' said Yash Bir, a passenger
on the bus who suffered burn injuries in the explosion. ``I was
unconscious. I do not know who brought me to hospital.'' Bir spoke
to reporters from a bed in a Chandigarh hospital, where most of the
injured were taken.
   Doctors said five were in serious condition. The victims were
not immediately identified.
   Brar said the bomb was planted on the bus' rooftop luggage
carrier. About 70 passengers were in the vehicle when the bomb
exploded, he said.
   In other parts of Punjab, Sikh militants were blamed for five
other killings that occurred Thursday night and today, the United
News of India said.
   At least three victims were Sikhs, the news agency said. The
militants have targetted members of the Hindu community and
moderate Sikhs in their campaign.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 800 million people but form
a majority in Punjab. Radicals have been agitating for an
independent Sikh homeland since 1982, claiming discrimination by
Hindus, who form 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
