<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Boat People,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Vietnamese Boat People Returning Home Voluntarily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Vietnamese who fled to Hong Kong by boat
left the British colony voluntarily for home Friday, the government
reported.
   About 23,000 boat people remain in Hong Kong camps, including
about 90 others who have asked to be sent back to the communist
nation, about 500 miles to the south.
   The Vietnamese who arrived before June 16 are viewed as
political refugees eligible for resettlement in third countries.
   But under a new policy to curb the surging number of arrivals,
the about 7,000 boat people who arrived since mid-June are
classified as illegal immigrants subject to repatriation unless
they can prove political persecution.
   Vietnam said it will accept people who volunteer to return.
   The five repatriated Vietnamese men arrived in the same boat in
December. No reason was given for their decision to return.
</TEXT>
