<1ST_LINE>u p PM-JacksonVideo 1stLd-Writethru a0534 08-12 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson Video, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0534,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Video Maker Acknowledges He Never Got Jesse Jackson's Persmission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with judge issuing ruling,
quote; Picks up 3rd graf, `Ali, president ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson won an extension today of a
temporary court order barring a businessman from selling or
distributing videotapes of Jackson's speech to the Democratic
National Convention.
   U.S. District Judge James B. Zagel extended the temporary order
until Tuesday when he said he planned to issue a written opinion on
Jackson's lawsuit seeking to permanently bar MPI Home Video from
selling or distributing the videotape.
   ``I'm pleased with the result,'' said Henry Mason, one of
Jackson's attorneys. But Mason said he expected the lawsuit would
be heard in a trial unless the two sides reach some type of
settlement.
   Waleed B. Ali, the suburban businessman who sold the videotapes
of the former presidential contender's convention speech, testified
Thursday that he was motivated by money and the event's historic
importance.
   ``I thought we had a hot-seller,'' Ali said.
   Ali, president of MPI Home Video in suburban Oak Forest,
acknowledged during the hearing that he had never obtained
permission to sell the tapes from the former presidential candidate.
   But attorneys for MPI contend the company didn't need Jackson's
authorization because his hourlong speech July 19 in Atlanta was a
news event, unprotected by federal copyright law.
   Ali's attorneys have argued that MPI legitimately purchased
ABC-TV's coverage of the speech from the network for $6,500.
   Ali said that while viewing the speech live on ABC-TV, he knew
it was newsworthy and worth preserving for historic reasons.
   ``Our position is that it is news,'' Ali testified.
   ``You admit that Reverend Jackson never authorized you to make
this tape?'' asked Jackson's attorney, William Conlon.
   ``Absolutely,'' Ali testified. ``I don't have any arrangement
with the Rev. Jackson.''
   The 60-minute tape, ``Jesse Jackson: We Can Dream Again,'' is
comprised of uncut ABC coverage, including commercials and camera
shots of the convention floor, Ali said.
   Ali said that until a July 29 temporary restraining order barred
the sale and distribution of the tape until today, his firm had
shipped about 7,100 cassettes, at a list price of $14.95 each.
   Jackson, who did not appear in court Thursday, testified last
week that MPI's tape ``has hurt our ability to make a living off my
work.''
   He said he reaped $100,000 four years ago from marketing a
videotape of his speech to the 1984 Democratic National Convention,
and that MPI's distribution of this year's speech has cut into its
market potential.
</TEXT>
