<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Generals Bjt   08-12 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Generals, Bjt,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Military Chiefs Play Increasing Role in Election Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's pre-election debate on the future of
the occupied territories is turning into a battle of the generals.
   The liberal Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon Peres is
reassessing policy based on the recommendations of retired military
chiefs who believe giving back land may not jeopardize the nation's
security.
   But their positions are disputed by ex-generals aligned with the
right-wing Likud bloc of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. They argue
that a smaller Israel is a more vulnerable Israel.
   ``Could we leave Judea and Samaria (the West Bank) and be safe?
The answer is no,'' said retired Maj. Gen. Yehoshua Saguy, a Likud
candidate for Parliament.
   The Nov. 1 elections may turn on whether Israeli voters are
willing to risk giving up all or part of the 2,266 square miles of
West Bank and Gaza Strip captured in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Much of the new thinking about the territories is coming from
the liberal, Labor-oriented Council for Peace and Security, which
includes among its members 30 major generals, 80 brigadier generals
and 100 colonels.
   Spokesman Moshe Amirav says after four months of internal
debates, the private think tank is getting ready to publish a
series of papers on the military implications of giving up
territory.
   Amirav said participants reached a consensus on four major
points:
   _ Evacuated areas would become demilitarized, except possibly
for some troops along the Jordan River.
   _ The Jordan River would be the military frontier.
   _ Israel's air force would control of the skies over any
territory yielded to the Arabs.
   _ Israel would maintain early warning stations in the West Bank,
perhaps existing bases, on 50-year leases.
   Retired Maj. Gen. Menachem Meron of the peace council said it
could take years to establish adequate security safeguards.
   ``Our group believes territorial compromise can be achieved and
defense arrangements can be made, even if they cover a long period
of time,'' he said in an interview.
   The daily Yediot Ahronot newspaper said a withdrawal plan was
being drafted for the Labor Party by a group of senior reserve
officers headed by Avigdor Ben-Gal, a retired major general and
leading figure in the peace council.
   It would replace a Labor Party policy paper that envisioned
Israel holding onto the Jordan Valley and other strategic areas of
the West Bank for security reasons.
   ``Under the previous plan, Israel would keep 50 to 60 percent of
the territory. But in terms of security, we say it can give up to
100 percent if these conditions are met,'' Amirav said.
   He said the council has reached a consensus that a Palestinian
state ``is not by itself a mortal threat to Israel,'' although this
has become a slogan of the right.
   Saguy, who has emerged as a leading Likud spokesman on defense
policy, said Israel's defense strategy is built on its ability to
mobilize reserve troops and the ooccupied land is needed to buy
time for troops to get into position.
   He said maintaining the Jordan River as a defensive line allows
Israel to send troops to the frontier without being subject to
attack in hostile areas of the West Bank in between.
   Some pro-withdrawal generals said accurate long-range missiles
make it unnecessary to hold onto the territory as a buffer. But
Saguy said the extra time provided by territorial depth is more
critical than ever.
   Alouph Hareven, a former intelligence colonel and leading figure
in the peace council, said former generals will play a key role in
selling the public on the need to get rid of the occupied lands.
   ``The Israeli public is not sentimentally attached to Nablus,
Hebron or other areas of the West Bank. What matters to them is the
security dimension,'' he said.
   Saguy, a former head of military intelligence, agreed voters
would decide on the basis of security issues. But he said, ``Nobody
sees an alternative to holding the territory right now.''
   Raphael ``Raful'' Eitan, a former chief of staff and now a
leading figure in the nationalist Tehiya Party, said Israel should
annex all occupied land.
   ``We must annex all of (the territory) and massively settle
every spare corner of the Land of Israel,'' Eitan, a legislator,
said on Israel radio.
   Saguy was forced to resign and Eitan retired after a judicial
commission criticized them for failing to prevent the massacre of
Palestinians by Christian militiamen in the Beirut camps of Sabra
and Chatilla in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
