<DOCNO> AP880812-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CityYear Bjt   08-12 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Year, Bjt,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Youth Corps Seeks To Serve as National Model</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders are Harvard Law graduates who could be
earning more than $100,000 a year. The participants are high school
and college students who could be at the beach. Instead, they're
working as a sort of urban Peace Corps that organizers hope will
set a national example.
   The program, called City Year, is a privately funded community
service project. Fifty students ages 18 to 21, from high school
dropouts to Brown University students, were culled from 150
applicants.
   They begin their days at 8 a.m. sharp on Boston Common with 20
minutes of calisthenics. If they're late, they do extra exercises.
They spend the rest of the day on various projects, battling the
summer's searing heat and humidity as well as urban blight.
   One day they sort surplus food in a warehouse, other days they
help paint and renovate shelters for the homeless, clear brush from
vacant lots or work with disabled children.
   ``We call it City Year, because we thought of it as being like
junior year, senior year, then City Year,'' said Michael Brown, 27,
a recent Harvard Law School graduate who is one of the group's
directors. ``We say, `Why not spend a city year helping your city
before going on to college?'''
   City Year ends this summer but organizers hope to get enough
funding to make the program year-round. They plan to start it up
again next year.
   Raquel Mello, 17, said she's ``learned a lot about other
people.'' She said she enjoyed working on a project with disabled
children so much that she found it ``painful to leave.''
   Though youth corps exist in other cities, City Year President
Alan Khazei said most of them are government-funded. Khazei began
working on the program during his last year at Harvard Law with two
other students and a fourth person from another college. They took
their idea around to Boston's business community in the hope of
receiving funding and were rewarded.
   Bain & Company, Bank of Boston, Equitable Financial Services and
General Cinema each donated $25,000 to fund four of the five
10-person City Year teams. Citizen contributions funded the fifth
team.
   ``One of the big issues with national service is how do you fund
it?'' said Khazei. ``Well, we've reached out to the private sector
to show it can be done.''
   Khazei said he and his colleagues prefer working to ``promote
the idea of national service'' rather than taking high-paying
corporate jobs.
   ``This is a lot more fun,'' he said. ``We love what we're doing.
I can't think of anything more rewarding than working with
wonderful young people.''
   Kristen Hollister, 27, a Brown graduate, is one of the
individual team leaders. Because she knows sign language, the two
hearing-impaired participants were assigned to her team.
   ``When I read the (program) proposal, I said, `This is it, this
is what I have to do to make a difference,''' she said.
   Hollister said the highlight of her team's work came on a recent
sweltering day at a shelter for the homeless. The students spent
the day on the third floor of the shelter reupholstering chairs for
the women in the shelter.
   ``Each of them got to carry a chair down to the women at the end
of the day,'' said Hollister. ``When the women saw the chairs, they
all cheered. It was such a high.''
   A stint spent working at the Massachusetts Hospital School for
disabled children was the high point for many of the students.
   Winda Maldonado, 17, who is deaf, said it was a revelation to
her to care for children with greater disabilities than herself.
   ``It was my favorite place,'' she said. ``I loved it. I din't
want to leave. I made so many friends.''
   Caleb Jacobson-Sive, 17, a prep school student, said that prior
to City Year, he ``might have avoided people like the ones there.
But I look at handicapped people totally differently now. This
(City Year) has changed my outlook on a lot of things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
