<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     08-12 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Says Violent Demonstrations Must Stop For Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL9,10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo threatened
Friday to crack down on student demonstrations to safeguard the
Olympics. Radicals on six campuses hurled firebombs and rocks at
police, who fired tear gas.
   ``An eruption of demonstrations involving firebombs, stones and
tear gas during the Olympics would disrupt the Olympics, and our
nation would become an object of worldwide scorn,'' Roh told a
meeting reviewing preparations for the games, scheduled to begin
Sept. 17.
   Also Friday, South Korea asked North Korea to meet at the truce
village of Panmunjom in one week to discuss the possibility of full
parliamentary talks on easing tension on the Korean peninsula.
   About 6,000 radical students from 22 universities held rallies
or staged violent street demonstrations in Seoul and six provincial
cities, protesting a police blockade of a march to North Korea for
unification talks. The march is planned for Monday.
   Riot police fired tear gas to drive students back at six
campuses. Witnesses reported some arrests and injuries, but police
declined to give any figures.
   National Police Headquarters in Seoul said 2,099 radicals were
detained Wednesday and Thursday for taking part in demonstrations
to support the march. It said all but 243 were released.
   Riot police continued to ring college campuses and stand guard
at government buildings to try to foil preparations for the march
to the Panmunjom border truce site. The government banned the march
and police have mounted a major security effort to block it.
   Police officials said students have attacked 13 police stations
around the country this week, and several dozen officers were
injured.
   Roh accused radical students of trying to overthrow the
government and siding with North Korea's demand to be a co-host of
the Olympics,
   Roh appealed to opposition leaders Kim Dae-jung and Kim
Young-sam, who attended the Olympic briefing, to dissuade radical
students from the march and violent protests. The opposition
promised support for the Olympics but stressed the need for
dialogue between the government and student leaders.
   ``It is deplorable that a small number of dissidents and radical
students are huring a successful Olympic mood with demonstrations
and calls for joint Olympics,'' Roh said.
   North Korea sought the meeting on tension-easing measures for
Wednesday, but South Korea counterproposed Friday. The two-day
delay apparently is aimed at protecting celebrations of the
``Olympic Mood'' on Wednesday, 30 days before the start of the
Olympics.
   North Korea has called for a meeting of the two countries'
legislatures to discuss its bid to become a co-host of the Olympics
and draft a non-aggression pact.
   The peninsula has been divided since 1945 at the end of World
War II. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean
War.
</TEXT>
