<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilSpill     08-12 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Spill,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Slick In Gulf Misses Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The light sheen of oil left by a ruptured
barge in the Gulf of Mexico was drifting away from barrier islands
on the Mississippi Gulf Coast and should eventually evaporate, the
Coast Guard said today.
   ``The situation is definitely improving,'' said Coast Guard
Petty Officer Bob Morehead. At one point Thursday, the oil slick
had threatened to wash onto the beaches of Ship and Cat islands
about 10 miles off the Mississippi mainland.
   An estimated 5,000 gallons of oil leaked from the barge after it
struck a submerged barge early Thursday a few miles off the
Mississippi coast. The submerged barge, which was loaded with scrap
iron, had sunk Monday during the rough seas of Tropical Storm Beryl.
   Morehead said 10,000 barrels of oil was pumped from damaged
areas of the oil barge onto another vessel Thursday night, allowing
the barge to float free. It was moved away from the site of the
accident and was no longer leaking oil, he said.
   The patches of oil remaining from the leak were too light to be
skimmed from the water, but the sun and wind should evaporate most
of the crude as it drifts out to sea, Morehead said.
   ``We talked with the Mississippi Bureau of Marine Resources and
they said there was very little potential for major environmental
damage due to the oil,'' Morehead said.
</TEXT>
