<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOP-BourbonStreet Bjt   08-12 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Bourbon Street, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Town Awaits Biggest Republican Party of the Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bourbon Street has always appealed to the
prurient, but French Quarter merchants have draped New Orleans'
famous party street with red, white and blue to attract the
patriotic as well during the Republican National Convention.
   American flags hang next to drawings of bare breasted women
beckoning to passers-by while multicolored bunting competes for
attention with a fake pair of women's legs that swing forward and
back from two stories above.
   On this naughty street of take-out drinks and knockout strip
shows, merchants are hoping to lure Republicans with traditional
tawdriness and newfound politics.
   ``He's tan, rested and ready _ Nixon in 1988'' adorns one
T-shirt bearing a black and white likeness of the former president.
Other shirts found in various souvenir shops carry the standard
logo of the official 1988 GOP convention.
   Bourbon Street is ready for the Republicans. The question,
however, is are the Republicans ready for Bourbon Street?
   ``Everybody should see this city,'' said Jeff Levy, a delegate
from Los Angeles. ``There are lots of weirdos here, but everyone
should see them. It's hot, but excellent.''
   Wrought-iron balconies, bars named for pirates, provocative
dancers of both sexes and 24-hour liquor attract an eclectic group.
   Michael Montolbano, the doorman at Pat O'Briens where tourists
slurp rosy-colored Hurricanes in a glass they can take home, said
some Republicans have already experienced the street.
   ``You can spot `em by the way they dress in those $800 suits and
the way they carry themselves. Power tie, power look, the whole
bit,'' he said.
   Dancer Bonnie Holloway said she expects the Republicans to party
just like everyone else.
   ``If they get drunk, they should spend money. There's going to
be a lot of men at this convention, they said, so it'll be good for
us,'' she said.
   The doorman at Papa Joe's, which bills itself as having the only
female impersonators on Bourbon Street, said Republicans seem to
enjoy looking at men dressed up like women.
   ``They seem to be having fun. At least they get a couple of
laughs out of here,'' said Manny Moreland.
   But a hostess at the Coffee Pot, around the corner from Bourbon
Street, and a bartender at Court Liquors To Go said they've noticed
little change _ yet.
   The French Quarter, of course, is not the only place New Orleans
likes to party.
   ``A Grand Party for the Grand Old Party'' started the convention
festivities on Friday with a picnic in City Park. Probably the only
family event scheduled for the week, the Grand Party featured
bands, choirs, fireworks and free rides on the park's narrow-gauge
trains and flying horses, a turn-of-the-century carousel.
   The Elephant Romp on Saturday will attract delegates and people
willing to shell out $100 per person for a trip to the Audubon Zoo.
The Greater New Orleans Convention Fund hopes to raise $400,000 to
help defray city costs for hosting the convention.
   Tents featuring Louisiana themes, food and music will be spread
about the zoological park.
   Beginning Sunday, fancy clothes and political bigwigs will
dominate the many private parties on social calendars.
   Among those featured convention week are a masked ball for
Senate insiders at the New Orleans Museum of Art and the
Conservative Victory Committee Ball featuring comedian and
impersonator Rich Little.
   New York real estate tycoon Donald Trump has accepted an
invitation to a jazz brunch at the home of Freeport-McMoRan chief
Jim Bob Moffett for 30 of his Fortune 500 counterparts. Other
guests expected to attend are Texas Air chairman Frank Lorenzo, The
Washington Post's Katharine Graham and Allen H. Neuharth of Gannett
Corp.
</TEXT>
