<DOCNO> AP880812-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma-SeinLwin     08-12 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Sein Lwin,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sein Lwin Made Name by Killing Rebel Leader, Suppressing Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sein Lwin rose to prominence by
personally killing a Burmese rebel leader in 1950 and commanding an
army company that shot down rioting Rangoon University students in
1962.
   When thousands of students went on a rampage last March in some
of the worst riots Burma has experienced, Sein Lwin led the forces
that stopped them.
   Analysts had suggested the 64-year-old former general would be a
logical scapegoat as the government of Ne Win, his close ally,
sought to appease critics and stabilize the country.
   Instead, Sein Lwin emerged last month as Burma's most powerful
leader to succeed Ne Win, who resigned after wielding near absolute
power since a coup 26 years ago.
   Protests of authoritarian rule intensified this week and
soldiers killed at least 95 demonstrators. Protesters carried
placards calling Sein Lwin a ``dog, Nazi and butcher of students,''
and many Burmese said he was the most hated man in the country.
   On Friday, Sein Lwin resigned as president of Burma and chairman
of the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Little has been published about Sein Lwin and others in Burma's
senior hierarchy, most of whom live in seclusion.
   According to John Badgley, a Burma expert at Cornell University
in the United States, Sein Lwin is a Mon tribesman born in Mattama
village. The Mons are one of several ethnic minorities in the
Southwest Asian country.
   He completed the fourth grade at most in a Buddhist monastery
school. Many Burmese still look down on him for his low level of
education and relative lack of manners.
   Sein Lwin joined the army in 1942 when Burmese officers,
including Ne Win, were siding with Japan against the Allies _
specifically Britain, colonial master of the former kingdom.
   As the war progressed, the officers switched allegiance,
realizing Japan was as much a threat to Burma's independence as
Britain. Independence in 1948 was followed by a chaotic, 14-year
experiment with democracy.
   Maj. Sein Lwin became known during that period as the man who
cornered and killed Sabaw U Gyi, leader of the ethnic Karen
rebellion. He developed a reputation as a man with courage and
decisiveness, but limited vision and a strain of brutality.
   Among the troops, his nickname was ``chinthe,'' for the mythical
lion that guards the entrances of Buddhist temples in Burma.
   He once was Ne Win's personal aide, and was at the leader's side
when Ne Win seized power in 1962 and began enforcing his brand of
economic socialism, military-backed authoritarian rule and
isolation from much of the world.
   Soon after the coup, Sein Lwin led his army unit in quelling the
riots at Rangoon University, firmly establishing his reputation as
an unbending leader prepared to wield an iron fist to root out
opposition.
   Most Burmese are interested in the supernatural, but Sein Lwin
has a preoccupation with astrology, magic and black arts and for
three years was the secret publisher of a magazine called Veda
dealing with such matters, Badgley said in an interview.
   Sein Lwin retired from the army and in 1977 joined the party's
Central Executive Committee. He won the No. 4 party post of joint
general secretary in 1985 and also became secretary of the Council
of State, the No. 3 position in the government after president and
vice president.
   He has held ministerial portfolios for cooperatives, transport,
communications, and home affairs.
   On March 18, a day later dubbed ``Bloody Friday,'' thousands of
students swept through downtown Rangoon, burning cars and shouting
anti-government slogans. It was the second student outburst in
three months.
   The ``Lon Htein,'' or riot police, were called out, reinforced
by regular army units and armored vehicles. Western diplomats and
Burmese sources said Sein Lwin commanded the police from a tactical
headquarters at the government broadcast station.
   They said he overruled some leaders who wanted to be more
lenient. The government has acknowledged 43 deaths, but more than
100 people are believed to have been killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
