<1ST_LINE>u w PM-USSmuggling 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 08-12 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Smuggling, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three US Officials Caught Taking Material Out of Soviet Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead to clarify that Fitzwater did not specify that the
Energy Department was the agency involved; INSERTS 8th graf, The
team, to show that individuals involved were geologists.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of a U.S. government team taking
part in a nuclear testing experiment in the Soviet Union engaged in
``some unauthorized souvenir collection'' there, the White House
said today.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, however, said that
based on information available so far to U.S. officials, ``we don't
believe it was intelligence activity of any kind.''
   ``The individuals picked up and attempted to ship on for their
personal use some rock samples, a piece of barbed wire, an Allen
wrench and a hammer,'' Fitzwater told reporters at the White House.
   ``The individuals involved have been removed from the list of
those who might return for the experiment,'' he said.
   Fitzwater noted that the team was in the Soviet Union under the
auspices of an agreement, announced by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, for a joint verification experiment in
the field of nuclear testing.
   ``We don't believe it was intelligence activity of any kind, but
it was a personal mistake on their part,'' Fitzwater said, adding
that ``we have informed the Soviet Union of this, yes.''
   Fitzwater declined to divulge the names of the three people
involved.
   The team apparently was under the auspices of the Energy
Department. Fitzwater said only that it included geologists who
were there to work with rocks and minerals related to the
experiment.
   The materials were discovered by Soviets inspecting equipment
crates being prepared for shipment back to the United States, said
Deputy Press Secretary Roman Popadiuk.
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that Moscow had
issued a formal diplomatic protest over the July 17 incident.
   But Fitzwater said there had been no formal exchanges.
   A U.S. official told the newspaper that both the Soviet Union
and the United States were trying to resolve the problem in a
``low-key'' manner.
   The team was in the Soviet Union under an agreement by which the
superpowers are allowing each other to observe and monitor each
other's nuclear blasts. The agreement is not connected to the
monitoring of weapons under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces
treaty, a Defense Department spokesman said.
   ``There's no question but that we stepped over the bounds of the
agreement,'' the newspaper quoted an unidentified senior
administration official as saying Thursday. The official said the
incident presumably stemmed from an innocent mistake.
   The attempted shipment by the Americans, who were not
identified, involved materials such as tools and wire associated
with Soviet nuclear test preparations at the test site near
Semipalatinsk in south-central Russia as well as soil and rock
samples of potential use in assessing yields of Soviet nuclear
blasts, the newspaper quoted officials as saying.
   The items were found by Soviet authorities during a search of a
crate of personal belongings of a U.S. official and two employees
of private firms under contract to the federal government, the Post
said.
   Spokesmen for the departments of energy and state as well as the
Soviet Embassy declined to comment. The Energy Department,
according to the Post, has conducted a secret investigation of the
incident.
   Robert Barker, assistant secretary of defense for atomic energy
and chairman of the military liaison to the Energy Department, told
the Post the Americans were ``absolutely not'' deliberately trying
to collect prohibited materials.
   When contacted late Thursday by The Associated Press, Barker
denied making the comment to the Post and refused to speak about
the issue.
   The Soviet Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a private protest
July 25 to U.S. diplomats that demanded permanent expulsion of the
three and a detailed explanation, the newspaper reported.
   The U.S. official and one of the contractor employees had left
the country before the protest was issued, and the other contractor
employee was allowed to remain in the Soviet Union after the United
States denied he was responsible, the Post said.
   A U.S. official not identified by the newspaper said, ``We are
trying to resolve it in a low-key way ... and the Soviets are,
too.''
   The special nuclear experiment for which the team was in the
Soviet Union is scheduled for next month at the test site near
Semipalatinsk.
   The Post quoted unidentified senior U.S. officials as saying the
incident was not expected to halt the progress of the agreement,
which also calls for observation of tests at the U.S. site in
Nevada.
   The project in question was part of the Joint Verification
Experiment concerning nuclear testing and ``has nothing to do with
on-site inspection or the INF Treaty,'' Navy Cmdr. Ken Pease told
The Associated Press on Thursday night.
</TEXT>
