<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SriLanka     08-12 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sri Lanka,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Finance Minister Resigns From Governing Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former finance minister resigned
from Parliament and the governing party Friday after accusing the
government of being unable to solve Sri Lanka's ethnic problems.
   Ronnie de Mel demanded new elections, saying it was the ``only
way to solve the present problems of our people.''
   De Mel, 63, was finance minister from 1977 until 1987. He said
the government had lost the right to rule by not holding elections.
   The United National Party of President Junius R. Jayewardene has
been in power since 1977. It held a referendum to extend its
governing period in 1982 after its five-year term expired, and
general elections are due in August 1989.
   De Mel, a Sinhalese Buddhist, criticized the government for
failing to end the Tamil insurgency.
   Tamil militants, who claim discrimination by the Sinhalese
majority, are fighting for a separate homeland in the island
nation's north and east. Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people.
