<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hinckley     08-12 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hinckley,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Drops Hinckley Field Trip After New Letters Uncovered</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St. Elizabeths, no apostrophe, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mental hospital Friday abandoned plans to
take John W. Hinckley Jr. on a field trip after the Secret Service
turned up a new cache of writings by the man who shot President
Reagan seven years ago.
   The decision by St. Elizabeths Hospital was announced at a
hearing originally convened by U.S. District Judge Barrington D.
Parker to consider the plan to allow Hinckley to join other
patients on a supervised outing.
   But letters by Hinckley found this week during an investigation
by the Secret Service prompted hospital officials to drop their
request.
   Based on ``recent materials received'' Thursday night, the
hospital ``determined that further clinical assessment by Mr.
Hinckley's treatment staff is necessary before it would permit him
to participate in such an off-grounds activity,'' said Dr. Raymond
F. Patterson, reading from a letter sent to the judge.
   ``The hospital no longer plans to include Mr. Hinckley in the
upcoming recreational activity in the community,'' Patterson,
director of St. Elizabeths Hospital's forensic services unit, added.
   Comments during the hearing by U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens and
defense lawyer Vincent Fuller indicated that the writings were
letters Hinckley had sent to an unidentified third party.
   Parker said he would not grant Stephens' request to release the
writings, which prosecutors had placed under court seal Thursday
night, until Fuller had a chance to file an objection.
   Fuller said Hinckley may have some ``proprietary interest'' in
the writings that would prevent them from being released.
   Hinckley, who wore a sport jacket and tie, sat impassively
throughout the brief hearing.
   The White House declined comment. ``We have never taken a
position on Hinckley matters, and we wo't now,'' spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   Outside the U.S. Courthouse, Stephens said he would continue his
efforts to make the writings public because ``they relate to a
matter of great national importance, they relate to an individual
who shot the president of the United States.''
   ``The public should be aware of what these materials are,''
Stephens said, indicating that the writings figured directly in the
hospital's decision the request to take Hinckley on a field trip.
   ``We provided materials to St. Elizabeths last night; they
withdrew their request for an off-site visit this morning,''
Stephens said.
   The decision also came after federal prosecutors cited
``disturbing entries'' made this week in Hinckley's treatment
record at the hospital.
   Hinckley, 33, has been confined to St. Elizabeths since he was
acquitted by reason of insanity of shooting Reagan, presidential
press secretary James S. Brady and two other men on March 30, 1981.
   Brady, who was shot in the head, remains confined to a
wheelchair and has difficulty speaking as a result of the injuries
he suffered.
   Hospital officials had not formally outlined its specific plan
for the outing. But court records indicate the field trip may be a
picnic or a party at a bowling alley.
   The hospital dropped a request in April 1987 to allow Hinckley
to visit his parents during the Easter weekend after investigators
turned up evidence he had traded letters with multiple murderer
Theodore Bundy, who is held on Florida's death row.
   A psychiatrist testified last year that Hinckley also had once
received a letter from Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, who is
imprisoned for trying to kill President Ford in 1975.
   Hinckley's correspondence with Bundy and other writings seized
from his room last year remain under court seal.
</TEXT>
