<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpeedyComposer     08-12 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Speedy Composer,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Software Allows Composers To Write More Music, Faster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ran in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Programmers hope a new software program that can
print out music as it's played will score a hit with composers.
   ``You play, it prints. It's a speeding up of the whole
process,'' said John Borowicz, a co-creator of the program. ``It
understands everything about standard music notation and it can
accurately transcribe what you play.''
   The program, called ``Finale'' by Coda Music Software of
Bloomington, Minn., was unveiled Thursday at the Macworld Expo
Boston '88. The program can translate information from a keyboard,
guitar or wind instrument.
   Borowicz, a composer and computer scientist, said he and his
partner Phil Farrand worked on musical transcription software for
about five years before producing the program.
   The software, he said, costs $1,000 and is ``aimed at the
professional level, or the intense amateurs.''
   Although he said the new program will allow composers to produce
more music in less time, some musicians were hesitant to applaud
the new development.
   Ran Blake, the director of the New England Conservatory of
Music's department of Third Stream Studies, said he was personally
interested but questioned whether it was an appropriate tool for
students.
   ``I wonder if they shouldn't have a mentor'' to teach them such
intricacies as harmony, he said.
   Although word processing has advanced rapidly, music notation
has benefited little from technology. Some software programs allow
composers to print music by punching in notes on a computer staff,
but the new program frees musicians from working separately on
composing, performing and editing.
   The new program, Borowicz said, is ``works the way the musician
works. The musician does not have to work the way the software
works.''
   Finale allows the musician to edit a piece at any point.
   ``You can play it back. You can stop it at any point. You can
manipulate down to the micro level,'' Borowicz said. ``You can also
point to the note, drag it to where you want it, or change it.''
</TEXT>
