<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-US     08-12 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Delivers Letter For Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter from President Reagan to Mikhail S.
Gorbachev was delivered to a top Soviet official Friday by the U.S.
ambassador, and a Western official hinted the message concerned
talks on the ballistic missile treaty.
   The Western official, speaking on the condition he not be
identified by name or country, said that after handing over the
letter, U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock and Soviet First Deputy
Foreign Minister Yuli M. Vorontsov discussed the talks on the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   The official, who was familiar with the meeting and the letter,
hinted that the message from Reagan also concerned the talks,
scheduled to start Aug. 24 in Geneva.
   The official news agency Tass reported that Matlock had
delivered a letter to Vorontsov from Reagan and said they discussed
``limiting nuclear and space arms, building on the talks held
during the Moscow summit meeting.''
   The Aug. 24 meeting is required under the ABM treaty, which
calls on the two superpowers to hold a conference every five years
to review its implementation.
   Disputes over the ABM treaty are among the stumbling blocks
toward reaching agreement on an accord that would halve the
superpowers' arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons. The Kremlin
contends Reagan's anti-missile program, popularly called ``Star
Wars,'' violates the ABM treaty, but Washington says it is allowed.
   At their summit in Moscow, Reagan and Gorbachev failed to
resolve the dispute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
