<DOCNO> AP880812-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthernForests     08-12 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Forests,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Sees Economic Problems if Softwood Depletion Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the South could suffer economically if
the depletion of softwood timber continues at the current pace
without being replaced, a senior Agriculture Department official
said Friday.
   Forest Service Chief F. Dale Robertson said a new study by the
USDA agency, state forestry agencies and universities, and the
forest industry found that the annual removal of timber is greater
than growth in many areas of the South.
   Timber is the region's leading agricultural crop, and the
processing of timber and timber products is the primary source of
employment, he said.
   ``Although the results of this study are of concern, we have
also found numerous opportunities for ensuring that timber
production can continue to prosper and grow in the South,''
Robertson said.
   ``Since the 1880s, when the South's first forest was devastated
by fire and poor management, two new forests have been regenerated
and harvested,'' he said. ``The South's fourth forest, the forest
of the future, can be even more productive.''
   According to the report, 22 million acres of cropland and
pasture in the South would be of more value if the lands were
planted in pine trees.
   Conversion to timber production could increase annual softwood
growth by 2.1 billion cubic feet, the report said. And the
replanting of cutover and non-productive trees on cutover lands
could increase net annual growth by an additional 3.2 billion cubic
feet.
   In other words, the study showed that conversion of cropland and
replanting could nearly double the South's current annual softwood
growth of 5.7 billion cubic feet.
   Robertson said the report presents a challenge and an
opportunity for southern farmers and landowners.
   ``Already, the owners of 1.5 million acres of highly erodible
cropland in the South have decided to plant trees on that acreage
under USDA's Conservation Reserve Program, he said. ``More
opportunities exist to increase timber growth profitably.''
   Copies of a summary of the report, ``The South's Fourth Forest:
Opportunities to Increase the Resource Wealth of the South,'' are
available from: USDA Forest Service, Southern Forest Experiment
Station, 701 Loyola Ave., New Orleans, La. 70113.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
