<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MspiLegislature 1stLd-Writethru a0607 08-12 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mspi Legislature, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0607,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Senate Debates Central Purchasing System for Counties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT that plan would go into effect
unless voters reject the plan; ADDS 1 graf to explain current and
new systems.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate today reviewed a
House-approved bill that would require counties to adopt central
purchasing systems, a reform proposal prompted by a widespread FBI
investigation into local corruption.
   The Legislature is meeting in a special session called by Gov.
Ray Mabus in an attempt to change the prevailing county system
under which each of five county supervisors directly oversees
operations in his or her district.
   As state auditor for the four years before he was elected
governor, Mabus assisted the FBI in its ``Operation Pretense''
investigation into corrupt county purchasing. It resulted in the
arrests of 52 supervisors in 24 counties, of which 43 were
convicted or pleaded guilty and 23 received prison sentences.
   The measure, which passed the House Thursday on a 111-10 vote,
is similar to a bill approved by the House at the end of the 1988
regular session.
   Under the House-passed bill, a unit system for road construction
and maintenance would have to be in place by Oct. 1, 1989.
Twenty-two counties already have a similar system. The central
purchasing system would remain in effect unless county voters
rejected the plan.
   The measure passed without debate and few amendments were
approved.
   One significant amendment adopted would prohibit a member of the
board of supervisors from acting also as county administrator,
central purchasing clerk or road manager.
   Members of the Senate County Affairs Committee met this morning
to discuss the bill after a brief session Thursday.
   Although the House and Senate were stalemated at the end of the
1988 session on the bill, Lt. Gov. Brad Dye said he believed things
would be different this time.
   ``These (Senate members) realize just like those House members
that we can't leave here wihout passing that legislation,'' he said.
   Under the new system, one appointed administrator would oversee
day-to-day purchasing for the county, a job currently shared by
supervisors.
</TEXT>
