<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JudgeAcker     08-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge Acker,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Wants Comment From Justice Department, Withholds Recusal
Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge removed from a Ku Klux
Klan case by an appeals court said today he wants to hear from the
Justice Department before deciding whether to bar himself from all
federal government cases.
   U.S. District Judge William M. Acker Jr., at the end of an
hour-long hearing on his own motion to ban himself from Justice
Department litigation, withheld any immediate ruling.
   He said he did not know how he would rule eventually but ``I
have made my mind up that I am not going to rule on my motion to
recuse until I hear from William Bradford Reynolds,'' who is
director of the civil rights division of the Justice Department.
   Acker said he wanted Reynolds' comments about his being assigned
to hear Alabama's college desegregation case, which has been marred
by judicial conflict, including bitter language over the removal of
a black federal judge, during the past several years.
   ``I will defer until I hear from him on that matter,'' Acker
said.
   Attending today's hearing was U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon,
who in 1980 became the first black federal judge in Alabama. He was
removed from the college desegregation case by the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals on grounds that Clemon's past role as a
state senator and civil rights attorney presented a judicial
conflict.
   Clemon, in a 10-page opinion this week, fired back that he was
the victim of a double standard demeaning to black federal jurists.
   Acker, a 60-year-old white judge who was appointed by President
Reagan in 1982, was not urged to disqualify himself from all
federal government cases during today's hearing. Three attorneys _
Leon Ashford, Joe Whatley and Doug Jones _ told the judge they had
found him to be fair and impartial. They are not involved in the
litigation that led to Acker's removal from the Klan case.
   Earlier this month, U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson instructed his
staff to stay away from today's hearing and said ``no one from the
Department of Justice'' would be on hand.
</TEXT>
