<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Cruiser     08-12 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Cruiser,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Drops Plan to Send Another `Aegis' Cruiser to Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has decided not to send another
of its billion-dollar ``Aegis'' cruisers to the Persian Gulf to
replace the USS Vincennes, which shot down an Iranian airliner July
3, officers said Friday.
   Lt. Cmdr. Tim Taylor, a spokesman for Mayport Naval Station in
Florida, said the departure of the USS Mobile Bay ``has been
temporarily postponed until further notice.''
   The Mobile Bay had been scheduled to leave the base Friday to
join the U.S. Navy Joint Task Force Middle East, which includes 27
warships in the gulf and Arabian Sea.
   Taylor said he could not discuss the reasons and Maj. Shelley
Rogers, a Defense Department spokeswoman in Washington, declined
comment on whether the delay was related to Iran-Iraq cease-fire
scheduled for Aug. 20.
   Military sources in Bahrain indicated privately the decision was
related to an expected cutback in the size of the U.S. force after
a truce in the 8-year-old war, but would not be specific.
   They said the Vincennes was expected to remain in the region
until early September, and one said an end to the war would
``sharply reduce any need'' for the Navy to send another of its
most sophisticated warships to the region.
   Ships normally serve about three months with the Middle East
force and the Vincennes, which arrived May 22, had been expected to
leave for its home port at San Diego in the next two weeks.
   The military sources described the practice as ``flexible,'' but
would not say why the Vincennes was being kept on longer than
usual. U.S. Navy policy provides for ships to be away from home
ports no longer than six months.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci repeated this week that the
force of 27 warships, including 18 in the gulf, would be reduced
sharply if the cease-fire held for a ``prudent'' period.
   All 290 people aboard the Airbus A300 were killed when the
Vincennes mistook it for an Iranian F-14 fighter on an attack
course and shot it down with missiles.
   An official report is expected to be released later this month
after study by Carlucci and the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Pentagon officials have said it will blame ``human error'' by
radar operators in the stress of first-time combat. The ship had
sunk two Iranian gunboats in a skirmish less than an hour before
the jet passed overhead on a flight to Dubai from a
military-civilian airfield in Bandar Abbas.
</TEXT>
