<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-12 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha: U.S. Sanctions Bill Could Wreck Namibia Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha on Friday
accused U.S. congressmen of ``recklessness'' and said a tough
sanctions bill passed by the House of Representatives could
jeopardize a regional peace plan.
   Botha said the legislation would not help South African blacks
and might ``obstruct or make impossible'' an initiative to end
South Africa's 73-year rule over South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   ``The recklessness of members of Congress who do not care in the
least whether their actions adversely affect the search for a
peaceful solution to the problems of southern Africa as a whole is
astounding,'' Botha said.
   The sanctions bill would halt U.S. investment in South Africa
and impose a near-total trade embargo. It was approved by the House
on a 244-132 vote Thursday.
   The bill faces a possible Republican filibuster in the Senate
and a likely veto by President Reagan. Earlier legislation, which
passed despite Reagan's veto, bars imports of various South African
commodities and forbids South African planes to land at U.S.
airports.
   Botha said the bill emerged ``for purely internal political
aims.''
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater also
denounced the bill, saying it would ``destroy America's
flexibility'' to seek change through diplomatic pressure.
   Republican members urged the House to adopt a policy of ``black
empowerment'' to increase the economic and political power of
blacks and weaken apartheid's foundations.
   But Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., a sanctions supporter, said:
``Black economic empowerment in the face of apartheid is an
impossibility.''
   Leading black anti-apartheid activists in South Africa,
including Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, have urged the West to
intensify sanctions as a means of pressuring the government to
grant full political rights to the 26 million blacks, who have no
vote in national affairs under apartheid.
   Many black moderates and conservatives, as well as several
prominent white liberals, support the government's contention that
sanctions will have the harshest effect on blacks and will harden
the white minority's resistance to political change.
   Botha said he found it ``particularly remarkable'' that the
House acted on the bill ``exactly at a time when positive progress
was being made with the peace negotiations between South Africa,
Cuba and Angola.''
   The three countries Monday announced a cease-fire in the Angolan
civil war. South Africa said it was prepared to begin implementing
a U.N. plan for Namibian independence Nov. 1, provided agreement
could be reached on a timetable for withdrawing Cuba's troops from
Angola.
   The estimated 50,000 Cuban soldiers have been supporting
Angola's Marxist government in a 13-year war against a South
African- and U.S.-backed rebel movement. The movement, the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, is not a party to the
cease-fire.
   ``It would be ironical if Resolution 435 (the U.N. independence
plan for Namibia) should reach the point of implementation only to
be obstructed or made impossible as a result of provisions in the
American legislation,'' Botha said.
   He said unspecified financial transactions necessary to
implement the plan could be affected by the sanctions bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BusinessInventories     08-12 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Inventories,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Up for 18th Straight Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories climbed for the 18th
consecutive month in June, the government said Friday, prompting
some economists to warn that companies may be stockpiling goods in
anticipation of higher prices.
   The Commerce Department said inventories jumped 0.7 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $733.9 billion in June, following an identical
0.7 percent rise in May. Inventory levels have not fallen since
December 1986.
   ``My guess is that there is a little buying ahead on inventories
in anticipation of higher inflation going on. When it happens, that
just adds to inflationary pressures,'' said Allen Sinai, chief
economist of the Boston Co.
   In a separate report, the Labor Department said wholesale prices
rose 0.5 percent in July, a 5.7 percent annual rate that was more
than double the 2.2 percent rate for all of 1987.
   However, other economists, noting that business sales have
increased more strongly than inventories, weren't troubled by the
gain in goods held on shelves and backlots.
   Business sales surged 1.5 percent in June to $490.6 billion
following a 0.8 percent gain in May. It was the fifth month without
a decline.
   ``Even though inventories were up sharply, they were still in
line with sales,'' said Kathleen Cooper, chief economist of
Security Pacific National Bank in Los Angeles.
   ``It's a reflection of the export-driven turnaround in
manufacturing. If you're selling more domestically and overseas,
then you need more inventory,'' she said.
   ``There's been some hedge buying against price increases, but we
think it's been fairly small,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, chairman
of the Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa., consulting firm.
   Inventories in June were 7.8 percent higher than a year ago,
while sales were 8.1 percent higher.
   The June inventory accumulation was boosted by a 1.0 percent
climb at the retail level, where sales were weakest, a 0.8 percent
increase at the wholesale level and a 0.4 percent gain at factories.
   The strength in business sales was paced by a 2.5 percent jump
at wholesalers. Sales from manufacturing plants climbed 1.5 percent
and retail sales were up only 0.4 percent.
   An advance estimate of retail sales for July, released Thursday,
showed a 0.5 percent increase.
   The combination of strongly rising sales and moderately rising
inventories pushed the inventory-to-sales ratio down slightly from
1.51 in May to 1.50 in June. That means it would take 1.50 months
to exhaust inventories at the June sales pace, a ratio not
considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
