<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     08-12 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,Bjt,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian President: War Made Iran a Regional Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ali Khamenei said Friday that Iran
has emerged from eight years of war against Iraq as a victorious
regional power with new worldwide respect.
   Also on Friday, Iran denied Iraqi claims that it shelled Iraqi
military positions. A U.N. fact-finding team arrived in the Iranian
capital to investigate allegations of Iraq's use of chemical
weapons.
   ``Today, the system of the Islamic Republic of Iran, for all the
ineffective efforts of the enemies, has turned into an important
power in the whole of the region,'' Khamenei said at a prayer
sermon at the Tehran University campus. His remarks were broadcast
on state-run Tehran radio.
   ``The nation of Iran is counted as an armed and established
military force in the region,'' he said.
   Khamenei said Iran gained worldwide respect because of the
military prowess it displayed in the war, which he said the country
acquired without depending on outside powers.
   ``These eight years of war and resistance taught other nations
that it is possible to defend themselves without depending on big
powers,'' he said, adding Iraq had been defeated because ``it has
not been able to achieve its despicable objectives.''
   Iran and Iraq agreed last week to an Aug. 20 cease-fire in their
conflict, which killed or wounded an estimated 1 million people.
   Iran had recently suffered a series of losses on the
battlefield, leading it to accept a U.N. cease-fire resolution July
18.
   In another development, British diplomat David Reddaway arrived
in Tehran Friday for talks about British and other foreign hostages
held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian groups. Before leaving London,
Reddaway said he would speak with officials about the 18 hostages,
who include Anglican envoy Terry Waite and two other Britons as
well as nine Americans.
   The foreign hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
   A spokesman for the War Information Headquarters in Tehran
dismissed Iraq's claims of Iranian shelling as ``false
propaganda,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency said.
   Baghdad accused Iran Thursday of shelling Iraqi military
positions near the Shatt al-Arab waterway, where the Persian Gulf
war broke out in September 1980.
   The accusation was made in a statement issued by the Iraqi
mission to the United Nations in New York. It was not carried on
newscasts in Iraq.
   In his speech, Khamenei urged Iranian volunteer and other forces
to remain at the front to defend the country and to give more power
to Iran on the international political scene.
   ``Even after the war, defense will continue and members of the
armed forces and volunteers must be present to defend Iran's
territorial integrity alongside the country's reconstruction,'' he
told the throng of worshipers.
   Worshipers chanted ``Down with the U.S.A.!'' ``Down with the
Soviet Union!'' and ``Down with Israel!'' and pledged to obey
revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The audience at Khamenei's sermon included about 100 Iraqi
prisoners of war, with about 25 of them wearing red headbands
indicating they want to fight Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
   The crowd was smaller than that at a similar sermon attended by
an Associated Press reporter four weeks ago.
   An official at the prayer service said the crowd was small
``because so many people have followed the call to go to the battle
front.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Plastic collection boxes were on hand at the sermon for
worshipers to contribute to the war effort.
   Since Iran announced it was accepting the U.N. cease-fire
resolution, the once all-pervasive slogan ``War, war until
victory!'' has been abandoned, said a Westerner based in Tehran.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency said a four-member team of
chemical weapons experts would travel to the northwestern Kurdish
town of Oshnaviyeh in the province of West Azerbaijan.
   Iran alleges that a chemical attack on the town earlier this
month injured more than 2,000 civilians, including many women and
children.
   U.N. reports have confirmed Iraq's use of chemical weapons in
the past.
   At the United Nations, a spokesman said Friday that the 350
unarmed U.N. military observers monitoring the cease-fire between
Iran and Iraq will have headquarters in both Tehran and Baghdad.
   Several members of the observer group are already in Tehran and
Baghdad, and the rest are to be in place Wednesday in preparation
for the Aug. 20 cease-fire.
</TEXT>
