<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Laos     08-12 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Laos,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Lao Officials To Meet on MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Laotian officials have agreed to meet
later this month to continue efforts at ascertaining the fate of
American servicemen missing in action from the Indochina war, the
State Department said Friday.
   The meeting between technical experts of both countries will
take place Aug. 22-23 in Vientiane, capital of Laos, department
spokesman Charles Redman said.
   ``We welcome this latest indication of Lao willingness to
increase cooperation in this important concern and other matters of
mutual interest,'' Redman said.
   Laos' agreement to hold the meeting is another sign of the
increasing openness of the communist government over the past year,
including economic reforms and plans to decentralize the
bureaucracy.
   The United States is trying to account for 555 Americans listed
as missing in action in Laos, many of them airmen downed during
missions against Laotian and Vietnamese communist positions.
   Under an agreement with the United States reached in August
1987, Laos ended a long period of inactivity on the MIA issue,
while the United States promised to consider Laos' request for
emergency food and other aid.
   Last May, U.S. and Laotian officials conducted a joint
excavation for the remnants of an American plane shot down in 1966
with two crewmen on board. No remains were found.
   Following the dig, the United States gave $13,000 worth of
medicine to a Laotian hospital. Laos' request for additional aid is
expected to be raised again in the talks this month.
</TEXT>
