<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Hungary-Jets     08-12 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hungary-Jets,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citizens Get Soviets To Turn Down Noise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarians angry about the noise caused
by low-flying Soviet military jets have succeeded in persuading the
Soviets to reduce the number of training flights and to fly at a
higher altitude, it was reported this week.
   A rare ``village meeting'' took place between residents of the
small towns of Szigethalom and Szazhalombatta in central Hungary
and commanders at the nearby Soviet base of Toekoel early this week.
   State television said the Hungarians pointed out cracks in walls
they said were caused by the piercing noise of low-flying jets.
   The Soviets agreed to stop any training flights on state and
religious holidays, Saturdays and Sundays, and between 2 p.m. and 4
p.m. on weekdays, television and radio reported.
   The number of training flights overall will be reduced and the
jets will fly at a higher altitude, the media said.
</TEXT>
