<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2nd-LdWritethru a0605 08-12 1032</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd-Ld Writethru, a0605,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Appeals Boosts Bush Before Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In 29th graf, `I can't, CORRECTS name of show from `Business
Week' to `Business World.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, claiming Americans ``don't
want to gamble their future on a blind date,'' told top
administration officials today that ``we are going to hold the
White House with George Bush.''
   Speaking to about 250 senior officials, including Cabinet
members, Reagan praised Bush, saying, ``he's been a great vice
president but I think he will an even greater president.''
   Bush, who spoke before the president at the pep rally in the Old
Executive Office Building, told the officials, ``I need you to help
mobilize our troops....I need you to march to victory again in
November.''
   The meeting today was one in a series of joint appearances
planned for the president and Bush, who will be installed formally
as the Republican presidential nominee next week at the Republican
National Convention in New Orleans.
   Many of the administration officials will speak on Bush's behalf
during the fall election campaign.
   ``Who's tending the store?'' Reagan jokingly asked the large
gathering of senior administration officials. ``Welcome to the
White House complex,'' he said. ``That's what our opponents have
after being eight years out of power,'' he joked.
   Reagan told the gathering he would be ``crisscrossing America
this fall'' for Bush's candidacy and to spell out the
accomplishments of the Reagan-Bush years.
   ``You all are part of a great and continuing success story,''
Reagan said.
   At the same time, Reagan said, ``We've got five full months
ahead of us. We're going to continue to advance our programs and
policies until we cross the finish line next January.''
   ``George Bush's policies work,'' Reagan said. ``The other folks
talk, George Bush will deliver...We are going to hold the White
House with George Bush.''
   ``Most people will vote for George Bush this year because, after
voting for him twice before, they know he's their guarantee that
peace and propsperity today will be followed by more peace and
prosperity tomorrow.''
   ``And frankly,'' Reagan continued, ``I don't think the American
people want to gamble their future on a blind date.''
   Reagan handed Bush a gavel at the conclusion of his speech,
claiming, ``I figure that with the convention coming up, you can
probably use that gavel. If not there, from experience there will
be a lot of meetings with the congressional leadership when you can
use that.''
   The meeting was attended by Cabinet and sub-Cabinet officials,
who are exempt from a federal prohibition on campaigning that
applies to lower-level federal bureucrats.
   Bush called the officials ``the field commanders of the Reagan
revolution'' and said, ``more than most Americans, you have an
important understanding of the importance of the election that
stands ahead.''
   Bush and Reagan are to meet again at an airport rally next
Tuesday in New Orleans, as Reagan leaves the convention city and
Bush arrives. The two also are expected to spend about four or five
days after the convention campaigning together, according to
campaign sources.
   Meanwhile, top Bush campaign advisers were to hold a strategy
session today to discuss convention logistics and the vice
president's closely guarded selection of a running mate.
   Bush said Thursday he would not discuss ``who's off the list and
who's on the list,'' although campaign sources did say that private
polls for the campaign show former rival Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.,
would give him a larger boost than others being considered.
   However, the sources also said that a Bush-Dole ticket showed up
as only marginally stronger than other potential combinations for
which polling was done.
   Dole's advantage ``is a little bit, but not enough to make much
of a difference,'' said one source.
   A ticket of Bush and Bob Dole ran stronger than a hypothetical
ticket of Bush and Dole's wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, the sources said.
   On Thursday, Bush met with a group of black Republican
supporters and vowed to make an aggressive effort to court black
voters who have traditionally voted Democratic.
   Bush said his campaign would demonstrate his ``commitment in the
field of civil rights and in opening the arms of this party.''
   He declined to say whether he would name a black to his Cabinet,
a promise he had made previously only to Hispanics. He also refused
to be dawn into a discussion of whether he was considering Lt. Gen.
Colin L. Powell, the first black ever to hold the post of national
security adviser, for the No. 2 spot.
   ``I have worked closely with Colin Powell and I have great
respect for him,'' Bush said. But, he added, ``Don't put it into
any vice presidential equation.''
   Several newspaper columns have suggested Powell as an ideal
running mate, an idea also backed by Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., who is
believed to be on Bush's ``short list.''
   Sources close to Bush's selection process said that Powell is
not being actively considered.
   Meanwhile, Bush said he's opposed to higher interest rates but
won't criticize the Federal Reserve's action this week raising the
discount rate, the rate it charges for short-term loans to banks,
from 6.0 percent to 6.5 percent.
   ``I can't assault them right now for this,'' Bush said in an
interview with ABC News' ``Business World,'' scheduled to be aired
Sunday. ``You've got to find the right mix'' to prevent inflation
or high interest rates from gaining the upper hand, he said.
   In raising the rate that usually provides a bellwether for other
rates throughout the economy, the Fed said it was acting to keep
the lid on inflation.
   A transcript of the taped interview was released Thursday by the
network.
   On another subject, Bush broke with the Reagan administration
and voiced support for the recommendation of a commission headed by
New York investment banker Nicholas Brady that a single agency _
preferably the Fed _ be given authority over financial markets.
   Brady, a close friend of Bush's, was selected by Reagan last
week to succeed James A. Baker III as treasury secretary. However,
the White House never has endorsed the findings of his report on
the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
</TEXT>
