<HEAD>Railway Workers Demonstrate To Demand Better Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 uniformed workers from the
state-run railway marched through the streets Friday to demand
higher wages and overtime pay.
   The workers from Taiwan Railway Administration handed a petition
to Communications Ministry officials.
   A spokesman for the workers, Yang Ching-chang, said the railway
company should raise their salaries and immediately make overtime
payments owed to the workers. The workers did not say how much more
they want.
   After a one-day strike by conductors in May that halted rail
service throughout the island, the railway had promised to make the
overtime payments over a four-year period.
   Railway workers earn an average of about $700 a month.
   Taiwan legalized strikes in June but banned strikes without the
authorization of labor associations.
