<HEAD>Two Prominent Politicians to Leave Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former conservative Prime Minister Kaare
Willoch announced Friday he won't run for parliament again in next
year's election.
   Willoch, 59, has been a member of the 157-seat Storting for 32
years and served as prime minister from October 1981 to May 1987.
He is chairman of the constitutional and foreign affairs committee.
   Willoch, who failed in a bid last year for appointment as
secretary general of the NATO alliance, said in a letter to his
party: ``Should I do something else the rest of my active
professional life, it has to happen now.''
   Willoch was expected to seek the position as Oslo county
governor, which falls vacant next year.
   Einar Foerde, the deputy chairman of the ruling Labor Party,
also announced his decision not to run again, enabling him to apply
for the job as general manager of Norsk Rikskringkasting, the
national radio and television company.
   Foerde, 45, has been in the Storting since 1969 and is Labor's
floor leader.
