<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Bases     08-12 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Bases,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2,000 Rally Against U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELES, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 students and some Roman
Catholic nuns chanting slogans denouncing the ``U.S.-Aquino
regime'' marched to an U.S. air base Friday to demand American
military facilities be closed.
   About 120 Filipino riot police guarded the main gate to Clark
Air Base as the protesters arrived from a church-run school two
miles away.
   The demonstrators included delegations from Manila, 50 miles to
the south. The group was to hold a similar protest Saturday outside
Subic Bay Naval Base, 30 miles southwest of Angeles.
   The U.S. military TV station, the Far East Network-Philippines,
warned viewers of the rally and urged American military personnel
to use other routes to avoid the protest.
   Clark and Subic are the largest American bases outside the
United States. About 40,000 U.S. service personnel, Defense
Department civilians and military dependents are stationed at
Clark, Subic and four smaller installations.
   Also on Friday, Capt. Douglas J. Katz, commander of the
battleship USS New Jersey, told reporters at Subic that the U.S.
Navy could relocate its facilities but hoped such a time would not
come.
   He said Subic was ``the finest base in the Pacific, and it would
be a loss'' to the Navy if the lease on U.S. military facilities in
the Philippines is not renewed when it expires in 1991.
   President Corazon Aquino is under pressure not to renew the 1947
bases agreement. She has agreed to honor the lease through 1991 but
refuses to say if she would support an extension.
   U.S. and Filipino panels have been negotiating for more than
four months on terms that should apply during the agreement's last
two years.
   According to sources close to the talks, Mrs. Aquino's
government is demanding compensation for the bases be increased to
$1.2 billion annually. The Americans now provide $180 million a
year in military and economic aid for continued use of the bases.
   The sources said the Americans are not willing to pay such a
drastic increase in compensation without assurances that the bases
will be allowed to remain beyond 1991.
   Speeches and slogans during Friday's rally accused Mrs. Aquino
of subservience to the Americans and said she already has secretly
agreed to extend the agreement.
   ``The truth is the Philippine government is ready to give the
Americans what they want in exchange for a big amount of money,''
said Elmo Manapat, a leader of the Nuclear-Free Philippines
Coalition.
   Zenaida Uy, secretary general of the left-leaning New Patriotic
Alliance, accused Mrs. Aquino of selling out Philippine sovereignty.
   In Cebu, the military's Visayas Command said Communist
guerrillas ambushed a patrol on Negros Island, wounding five
soldiers.
   The command said rebel fire also damaged three helicopters which
were flying in reinforcements after the clash in the mountains near
the Negros coastal town of Guihulngan, 350 miles southeast of
Manila.
   No rebel casualties were reported.
   The guerrillas have waged a 19-year insurgency to establish a
Marxist state.
</TEXT>
