<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush-Veep 1stLd-Writethru a0436 08-12 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Veep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thompson Says He's Out of Bush-Veep Running</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Thompson quotes, picking up in
2nd graf pvs, Originally</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Vice President George Bush promising he
won't name his running mate until next week's Republican
convention, the field of potential candidates shrunk today when
Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson said he had withdrawn from
consideration.
   Thompson said he called Bush this morning and said he didn't
want to be considered further because of the potential impact the
job would have on his family. He had been one of more than a dozen
people contacted as a possible running mate with Bush.
   Earlier, California Gov. George Deukmejian also had taken
himself out the running.
   ``The vice president's job requies a lot of national and
international travel,'' Thompson said at a news conference in
Springfield, Ill. ``My wife couldn't travel with me because I've
got a 10-year-old in school, and that's not true of the other
candidates.''
   Meanwhile, Bush's staff debated the best way to orchestrate the
announcement of Bush's running mate.
   Originally, Bush had planned to keep the name a secret until
next Thursday, the final day of the convention. However, his aides
now fear that would steal too much thunder from Bush's acceptance
speech, which is on the same day, so they are considering moving
the announcement up to Wednesday.
   ``Obviously, a consideration is a desire to maximize the
suspense factor,'' said a senior Bush campaign aide, speaking on
condition of anonymity. On the other hand, there is a rule that you
``don't step on other relatively good stories'' such as the
Thursday night speech.
   Another campaign official, also speaking anonymously, said there
was ``a lot of pressure to look at Wednesday'' for an announcement.
   In any event, one of the aides said, Bush is ``enjoying this
whole thing'' as suspense mounts over his choice.
   ``There won't be any leaks of this one because I'm not gonna
tell a soul and I haven't so far,'' Bush said in a CBS-TV
interview. He said some stories on the subject are ``close to
accurate and some of them are 180 degrees wrong.''
   Private polls conducted by Bush's campaign indicate that Sen.
Bob Dole of Kansas would give him more of a boost than any others
in contention for the No. 2 spot, but ``not enough to make much of
a difference,'' said one aide.
   A ticket of Bush and Bob Dole ran stronger than a hypothetical
ticket of Bush and Dole's wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, sources said.
   ``I don't think there is anybody under consideration who
guarantees (a Bush victory in) any state or region,'' said Roger
Stone, a Republican consultant with ties to the Bush campaign. As
for the timing of the announcement, Stone said, ``I don't think it
makes a whole lot of difference.''
   Bush, at an appearance with black supporters Thursday, declined
to say whether he was considering Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, the
first black ever to hold the post of national security adviser.
   Powell has been suggested by several newspaper columns and has
been backed by Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   People who were contacted by Bush, and asked to provide
financial data, include both Doles, Kemp, and Sens. Pete Domenici
of New Mexico, Dan Quayle of Indiana and Alan Simpson of Wyoming,
according to campaign aides.
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas, rumored to be under
consideration, said on national television she wasn't interested in
the job.
   Govs. George Deukmejian of California, Jim Thompson of Illinois,
John Sununu of New Hampshire, Carroll Campbell of South Carolina
and former governor Lamar Alexander of Tennessee were also among
those on the original list of those under consideration, the aides
said. Deukmejian has since withdrawn his name from consideration.
   Sources suggested that no polling had been done on Domenici,
suggesting that he may no longer be under active consideration.
   Meanwhile, Kemp said he has no expectations that he'll get
picked, and is ``not sitting by the telephone'' waiting to be
asked. But he said he would, naturally, jump at the job.
   Quayle said he, too, would accept an offer.
   Moreover, Quayle said his inclusion on Bush's list is not a
political favor to focus attention on Indiana's junior senator.
   `I don't think that's the case,'' he said. ``The answer is no.
N-O. Capital N-O,'' he said.
</TEXT>
