<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-US-Climbers     08-12 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-US-Climbers,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint India-U.S. Army Team to Attempt Himalayan Peak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint team of military personnel from
the United States and India will try to scale a mountain peak in
the Himalayas next month, expedition leaders said Friday.
   Maj. H.S. Chauhan, the leader of the Indian delegation, told a
news conference the expedition would assault the 23,860-foot Mana
peak in the second or third week of September, depending on the
weather.
   The two countries will send 13 men each on the expedition. The
Indian side comprises army men, while the U.S. delegation consists
of 11 Army officers and two from the Air Force.
   The peak, about 210 miles northeast of New Delhi in the state of
Uttar Pradesh, has been climbed only three times. The expedition
will try the climb from the southern side of the mountain, Chauhan
said.
   He said the climbers will have to negotiate a 1.2-mile-long
glacier before scaling the northwestern ridge. ``And that's a
razor-sharp ridge,'' he added.
   The last 4,950 feet to the summit will have to be attempted on a
fixed rope, Chauhan said.
   Chief Warrant Officer Robert Wood, the leader of the U.S. team,
said his squad was looking forward to the adventure.
   ``The Himalayas are acknowledged as the ultimate goal of all
mountaineers,'' he said. ``We hope to see significantly higher
altitudes than in other continents.''
   The team is the first to be sent to the Himalayas from the U.S.
military.
   The Indian army, which regularly sends expeditions to the
Himalayas, has collaborated on climbs with British and French army
teams in the past two years.
</TEXT>
