<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1517EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Bush     08-12 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bush,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Bush Urge Administration Officials to Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This stands for AM-Bush listed on digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan traded compliments with
George Bush in a campaign pep talk Friday to top administration
officials, and predicted Americans won't ``gamble their future on a
blind date'' in the November election.
   ``We're going to hold the White House with George Bush,'' Reagan
declared to about 250 Cabinet and other top administration
officials in a spirited pre-convention sendoff for Bush next door
to the White House.
   Bush, noting that many of the officials would be on the campaign
trail on his behalf as surrogate speakers this fall, said they must
persuade voters that ``not just one election but ... a way of
life'' is at stake.
   ``I need you to march to victory again in November,'' Bush told
the group of officials he called the ``field commanders of the
Reagan revolution.''
   He told them a victory by his Democratic rival, Michael Dukakis,
would ``totally reverse'' the ``successes of this administration.''
   It was Bush's last scheduled campaign event before he goes to
New Orleans next Tuesday. He will appear again with Reagan at an
airport rally there before he is formally installed as his party's
presidential nominee at the Republican National Convention.
   In the meantime, Bush will continue working on his acceptance
speech and make his final decision on a running mate _ although he
has repeatedly said he'll try to keep his choice secret until the
convention is well under way.
   Reagan, who spoke after Bush, told his audience: ``Some people
may cast their vote this year to thank us for the last eight years.
But I suspect most people will vote for George Bush this year
bcause, after voting for him once or twice before, they know he's
their guarantee that peace and prosperity today will be followed by
peace and prosperity tomorrow.''
   ``And frankly,'' Reagan continued, ``I don't think the American
people want to gamble their future on a blind date.''
   It was the first time the two had spoken together in a public
political setting since Reagan's endorsement of Bush last May 11 at
a Republican fund-raising dinner _ an appearance in which the
president barely mentioned his vice president's name.
   However, if that endorsement struck many as lukewarm, the
president made up for it in Friday's rally in which he frequently
mentioned Bush as his partner in ``a great and continuing success
story.''
   He referred to himself and Bush as ``the malaise busters'' who
brought ``eight years of steady change, change for the better''
after the administration of Democrat Jimmy Carter.
   ``There's no way that America will turn back now,'' Reagan said.
   ``George Bush's policies work. The other folks talk, George Bush
will deliver,'' Reagan told cheering officials.
   ``Who's tending the store?'' Reagan jokingly asked the gathering
of senior administration officials. ``Welcome to the White House
complex,'' he said. ``White House complex _ that's what our
opponents have after eight years of being out of power.''
   The president said he would be ``crisscrossing America this
fall'' for Bush's candidacy.
   He also said his own agenda was ``still full,'' and he called
for congressional action on a U.S.-Canada free trade bill,
administration-backed welfare legislation, new aid for Contra
forces in Nicaragua and a defense bill that supports his Star Wars
Strategic Defense Initiative.
   ``We've got five full months ahead of us. We're going to
continue to advance our programs and policies until we cross the
finish line next January,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan handed Bush a gavel at the conclusion of his speech,
saying, ``I figure that with the convention coming up ... you can
probably use that gavel. If not there, from experience I can tell
you there will be a lot of meetings with the congressional
leadership when you can use that.''
   The meeting was attended by Cabinet and sub-Cabinet officials
who are exempt from a federal prohibition on campaigning that
applies to lower-level federal bureaucrats.
   Bush said he was ``proud to be a part of this administration,
proud to serve this president.''
   ``We all know what will kill, definitively kill, this economic
expansion we've worked so hard to create,'' he said. ``Those same
Democrats, the McGovern or Carter or Mondale Democrats, are just
itching to get their hands back on the levers that you operate so
ably.''
</TEXT>
