<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Grouse Bjt   08-12 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grouse, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunters Roust Grouse On Glorious Twelfth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunters flocked to the heather-covered moors of
Scotland and northern England on Friday, ``The Glorious Twelfth of
August'' and the start of the grouse-hunting season popular with
landed gentry and wealthy tourists.
   But the hunters' gunfire was muted by declining stocks of the
wild red grouse, due to a parasite and vigorous protesters who
drove the birds away with a pre-dawn swoop on three grouse moors.
   The Hunt Saboteurs Association, which opposes blood sports, said
about 300 members beat the hunters to the bushes and rousted the
grouse at Stanhope and Gunnerside Moors in northern England and in
an area near Muirshell Country Park in Scotland.
   Ben Ponton, a spokesman for the protesters, said they would
remain on the moors all day. He described their early success as
the ``most glorious day'' in efforts to ban grouse-killing.
   ``It has become a `Glorious Twelfth,''' he said. ``We've saved
birds lives and that's glorious.''
   Dukes and lords traditionally lead hunting parties on ``The
Glorious Twelfth of August'' _ not to be confused with ``The
Glorious Twelfth of July,'' when Protestants in Northern Ireland
celebrate their victory over Roman Catholics in the Battle of the
Boyne.
   London restaurants, which used to hire helicopters, race-car
drivers and airplanes in an informal competition to whisk the first
grouse from the north to their tables, have toned down the
publicity stunts, partly because of the protests.
   ``I think over the last few years there has been very bad
press,'' said a spokesman for the Hilton International Hotel on
London's fashionable Park Lane, which ordered 10 grouse to serve
Friday night. ``As a result, a lot of hotels have not done as much
promotion.''
   Gourmets have always turned up their noses at the competition,
insisting grouse should hang for four r five days to bring out
their true gamey taste.
   The Ritz Hotel in London's Piccadilly area said grouse would be
on its menu Friday night for about $60 a plate, but ``it will be at
its best next week.''
   ``Most of our clients prefer it after its been hung for about a
week,'' a spokeswoman said.
   Passengers on Dan Air's 6:50 a.m. flight from Inverness,
Scotland, to London's Heathrow Airport were among the first to
taste this year's grouse.
   Grouse shot on a Scottish estate before dawn was cooked at the
Golsview Hotel in Nairn, driven to Inverness Airport four miles
away and served on board.
   The palatial Gleneagles Hotel in eastern Scotland, traditionally
one of the front-runners in the grouse-serving race, abstained for
the fourth successive year because of the serious grouse decline,
said general manager Peter Lederer.
   ``We feel we should do everything possible to preserve
Scotland's great sporting traditions in the interests of tourism as
a whole and for environmental and ecological reasons in
particular,'' he said.
   Scotland's Game Conservancy says the grouse population has
fallen steadily since the mid-1970s because of disease and because
their native habitats have been taken over as farmland.
   Grouse hunting is particularly popular among Britain's landed
gentry, and estate owners charge foreign tourists several hundred
dollars a day to shoot on their land.
   John Sheard, agent for the Duke of Devonshire's northern England
estate at Bolton Abbey, said propects for this year's grouse were
``not too good'' because a parasitic worm called the Strongyle has
weakened the stock.
   A Conservative lawmaker said the grouse season is also
threatened by a European Economic Community proposal which would
require that every bird in its member countries be inspected by a
veterinarian within 48 hours of death. The proposal is an effort to
ensure that wild animals used for food are healthy.
   The vet would need to remove the feathers and gut the bird, not
only delaying its passage to the dinner table but making it
impossible to hang game in a traditional way.
   ``Such an order is fatuous, dictatorial, militaristic, idiotic
and totally unacceptable to Great Britain or to sportsmen or to
anybody who has the brains of a grouse,'' said Sir Nicholas
Fairbairn, Conservative member of Parliament for Perth and Kinross
in Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
