<HEAD>Thompson Withdraws from Vice Presidency Consideration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James R. Thompson withdrew from
consideration Friday as a possible running mate for George Bush,
saying the vice presidency would place too much strain on his
family.
   ``I talked to the family about it and I now believe that at this
moment in the time of Jim Thompson and his family, it's not the
right thing to do,'' the Republican governor told reporters before
a speech at the Illinois State Fair.
   Thompson said he received background questionnaires from the
Bush campaign on Monday, but called the vice president Friday
morning and said he didn't want to be considered further.
   ``The vice president's job requires a lot of national and
international travel,'' he said. ``My wife couldn't travel with me
because I've got a 10-year-old in school, and that's not true of
the other candidates.''
   Thompson, 52, had said previously he didn't expect to be asked
by Bush.
   The governor also has also been mentioned for attorney general
in a Bush administration, but he said Friday he believes such an
appointment is unlikely.
   He noted that former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh was
confirmed Thursday as attorney general, replacing Edwin Meese III,
and indicated he believes Thornburgh will remain in the post if
Bush wins in November.
 
