<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Unisys-Judge     08-12 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unisys-Judge,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge To Review Whether To Unseal Unisys Search Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge will review an order that
sealed search warrant affidavits used to seize materials from
Unisys Corp. as part of a national investigation into Pentagon
procurement practices.
   U.S. District Judge Diana Murphy is expected to issue a decision
within two weeks.
   She acted Thursday at the request of attorneys for the Star
Tribune and St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch, which are appealing
U.S. Magistrate Earl Cudd's decision last month to grant the
government's request to seal the search records.
   They argumed the records should be released under the First
Amendment.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Vosepka countered that releasing
the search warrants and affidavits could jeopardize the government
investigation.
   Federal agents seized records at Unisys offices in Eagan on June
14 as part of an investigation into allegations of fraud and
bribery among defense officials, consultants and contractors.
   W. Michael Blumenthal, chairman and chief executive of Unisys
Corp., said Wednesday that an internal investigation was almost
complete and further action to eliminate questionable practices was
likely.
   The company is based in Blue Bell, Pa., but has substantial
operations in Minnesota.
