<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hostages     08-12 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Diplomat To Discuss Hostages With Iranian Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British diplomat David Reddaway said Friday
he will talk to Iranian officials about foreign hostages held in
Lebanon by pro-Iranian extremists.
   Reddaway, arriving for what he said was a two-week stay, would
not say which officials he planned to see Saturday.
   The state-run Islamic Republic News Agency said Reddaway would
hold talks on ``mutual relations'' during a short visit. It did not
elaborate.
   Before leaving London, Reddaway said he would speak with
officials about the 18 hostages, who include Anglican envoy Terry
Waite, two other Britons and nine Americans.
   ``I think it is bound to help,'' Reddaway said. ``The main thing
I will be able to do is to remind the Iranian government ... that
we would hope that any government that could influence people
holding hostages would do so.''
   Several of the missing foreigners in Lebanon are believed to be
held by a pro-Iranian group of Shiite Moslem extremists called
Hezbollah, or Party of God. Tehran wields considerable influence
over the faction. No group has claimed responsibility for
kidnapping the three Britons.
   In addition to Waite, Britain seeks the release of journalist
John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast man with dual
British and Irish nationality whose release is also sought by the
Irish government.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a
New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim
they killed him. His body was never found.
   Reddaway is a first secretary at the Foreign Office. While
stationed in Tehran in 1980, he helped Britons escape from the
besieged British Embassy.
   IRNA said he speaks fluent Farsi and has an Iranian-born wife.
His visit was not mentioned on the evening radio and television
news programs.
   Iran has been making conciliatory statements about relations
with Western nations since it announced July 18 it was accepting a
U.N. call for a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Iran's only representative in Britain, Charge d'Affaires
Mohammed Basti, said the hostage issue could be solved if all sides
showed good will, and his embassy announced it was sincerely trying
to help.
   A British official source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Basti has been told repeatedly that if Iran is in a position
to get freedom for the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon, it should do
so on humanitarian grounds.
   ``In a way this a very blatant admission (of involvement),'' the
source said.
   He stressed the government would make no deals with Iran and was
not involved with the Church of England talks. ``There is no change
and can be no change in our position that there will no deals.''
   Iran also said it appreciated the efforts of Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie, who met in London on Wednesday with a
representative of the Iranian Foreign Ministry from Tehran.
   Church of England representatives met again Friday with the
official, Mohamed Reza Said Mohamedi.
   In July, an Anglican bishop went to Lebanon to initiate
inquiries among Christians about the fate of four Iranians who were
believed kidnapped by Christians in Lebanon. Iran has repeatedly
sought information on the four.
   Waite disappeared in Lebanon in January 1987 while trying to
secure the release of American hostages.
   The longest-held hostage is American Terry Anderson, 40, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized
March 16, 1985.
   Relations between Britain and Iran have improved markedly in
recent weeks.
   Britain closed its embassy and withdrew the ambassador from
Tehran in 1980 after Revolutionary Guards stormed the building,
denouncing Britain as an ally of the United States.
   Last summer, Britain withdrew all its diplomats, who worked out
of the Swedish Embassy in Tehran, and virtually broke diplomatic
relations.
   The move came after a British diplomat was detained and beaten
in apparent reprisal for British police arresting an Iranian envoy
on shoplifting charges.
   On Thursday, the English-language Tehran Times said
``speculation looms large'' that Reddaway will visit Briton Roger
Cooper, held in Iran on espionage charges.
   Cooper, 52, a nephew of the late British poet and novelist
Robert Graves, was arrested in December 1985 and held in Tehran's
Evin prison.
   The newspaper said with the arrival of Reddaway, ``Britain took
a giant stride in expansion of bilateral ties with Iran.''
</TEXT>
