<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Nuclear     08-12 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Nuclear,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Considers Signing Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African delegation met with U.S.,
Soviet and British diplomats Friday about the possibility of
subscribing to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. No details
were disclosed.
   Under the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons,
which has been signed by 137 governments since its preparation in
1969, countries without such weapons open their nuclear facilities
to inspection by experts from the International Atomic Energy
Agency, a U.N. agency based in Vienna.
   Of the five acknowledged nuclear powers, the United States,
Soviet Union and Britain have signed but China and France have not.
   Also among the holdouts are countries believed either to possess
nuclear weapons or the potential of producing them, including
India, Pakistan, Israel and South Africa.
   A South African statement said the delegation was led by Foreign
Minister Roelof Botha and Energy Minister Danie Steyn.
   It said discussions covered ``the effect and interpretation of
the provisions of the NPT,'' a common official reference to the
treaty, and ``clarity was sought ... on the rights and privileges
which would apply should the Republic of South Africa accede to the
NPT.''
   The South African Broadcasting Corp. said Thursday delegation
would convey South Africa's willingness to open its nuclear
facilities to international inspection. In the past, South Africa
had refused to submit all its nuclear facilities to inspection by
the U.N. agency.
   South Africa is widely believed to have the technical capability
to produce nuclear weapons, but whether it possesses them has not
been established.
   A U.S. spokesman, Carl Stoiber, said concerns about its weapons
potential were raised in the discussions but gave not details.
   African and other third-world countries have repeatedly
attempted to have South Africa ousted as a member of the
International Atomic Energy Agency because of its refusal to sign
the treaty and its apartheid policy of racial segregation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0167 </DOCNO>
