<HEAD>Arafat Discusses Occupied Territories with Gadhafi</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat met met Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi in Tripoli on Friday and discussed financial aid
for Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories, the official
Libyan news agency JANA said.
   Gadhafi said earlier this week that Libya would pay the salaries
of 21,200 Palestinian officials in the territories who previously
had been paid by Jordan.
   King Hussein of Jordan announced July 31 he was severing legal
and administrative links in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
essentially turning over responsibility to the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   JANA said Gadhafi and Arafat stressed the need for other Arab
countries to follow Libya's lead in providing financial support to
the Palestinians.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official said privately Thursday it
was ``very hypothetical'' whether Israel would allow another Arab
country to send money into the territories.
   Israel has imposed strict restrictions in the past to prevent
PLO funds from coming into the country.
   JANA, monitored in Rome, said Gadhafi and Arafat also focused on
the necessity of creating a Palestinian government-in-exile to rule
the occupied territories, captured by Israel from Jordan and Egypt
in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Israel has denounced the idea of a government-in-exile.
