<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Slayings     08-12 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Slayings,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Bombing Kills Seven</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh separatists planted three time
bombs in two northern cities Friday, killing seven people and
injuring at least 37, police said.
   On Thursday, a gang believed to be upper-class Hindus attacked
two neighboring villages in the northeastern state of Bihar,
killing 11 Hindu untouchables, news reports said.
   A bomb placed on the roof of a state-owned bus went off 20
minutes after the vehicle left the bus terminal at Chandigarh,
killing seven people and injuring 35, said Police Chief Surinder
Singh Brar.
   In Jammu, the winter capital of Kashmir state, a bomb exploded
in a scooter rickshaw, injuring two people, said Police
Superintendent D.S. Salathia.
   Sikh militants also were blamed for placing a time bomb in the
most popular and crowded shopping center of Chandigarh, but the
device was detected and defused before it detonated.
   ``Another 15 minutes and it would have exploded,'' said
superintendent R.P. Singh. He said the device was detected after
someone reported seeing a suspicious canister with a watch attached
to it.
   Brar said a bomb exploded on a bus six miles south of Chandigarh
bound for the town of Shazadpur in neighboring Haryana state.
Chandigarh is the joint capital of Punjab and Haryana states.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 800 million people but form
a majority in Punjab. Radicals have been agitating for an
independent Sikh homeland in Punjab since 1982, claiming
discrimination by Hindus, who form 80 percent of the population.
The separatist campaign has killed 1,680 people this year.
   ``It was an encounter with death,'' said Yash Bir, a passenger
on the bus who suffered burn injuries in the explosion. ``I was
unconscious. I do not know who brought me to hospital.'' Bir spoke
to reporters from a bed in a Chandigarh hospital, where most of the
injured were taken.
   Doctors said five were in serious condition. The victims were
not immediately identified.
   Brar said the bomb was planted on the bus' rooftop luggage
carrier. About 70 passengers were in the vehicle.
   In other parts of Punjab, Sikh militants were blamed for five
other killings Thursday night and Friday, the United News of India
said.
   At least three victims were Sikhs, the news agency said. The
militants have targeted Hindus and moderate Sikhs in their campaign.
   The Press Trust of India news agency said at least two people
were seriously injured in the attack on untouchables in Bihar on
Thursday.
   No arrests were reported, but the killers are suspected to be
upper-class Hindus.
   More than 80 percent of India's 800 million people are Hindus,
who are mainly divided into four castes. Below the castes are the
Harijans or untouchables, the lowest group.
   Caste prejudices have lessened since India gained independence
in 1947, but divisions are more apparent in Bihar, the poorest
state in India.
   Prejudices often erupt into violence there because many
untouchables have joined Marxist groups that agitate for
distribution of land owned by upper-caste Hindus.
</TEXT>
