<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     08-12 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Fly to Moscow to Set Up Nuclear Test Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British scientists flew to the Soviet Union on
Friday to set up the only independent foreign-run seismic
monitoring station of Soviet nuclear tests, a colleague said.
   Jonathan Doody and Paul Coward plan to set up the monitoring
center at Garm near the Afghan border and 800 miles south of the
main Soviet nuclear test site at Semipalatinsk, said Andrew Parker,
a scientist who works with Coward at Leicester University. Doody
works at Glasgow University in Scotland.
   They hope their tests will help bring about a comprehensive
nuclear test ban treaty by proving that it is possible to monitor
even small nuclear explosions, said Parker.
   Opponents of such a treaty say that it could not be verifiable
because they believe low-level nuclear explosions cannot always be
detected.
   Doody and Coward plan to be stationed at the Garm center for two
weeks, after which they will be replaced by other British
scientists, said Parker. The center will be open for a year.
   Although U.S. scientists have set up five seismic monitoring
centers in the Soviet Union, they are operated by Soviets.
   The British center will be created under an agreement between
the Soviet Academy of Sciences and the British Seismic Verification
Research Project, an independent group of scientists who want a
nuclear test ban treaty.
</TEXT>
