<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     08-12 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebels Fight On; Say They Kill 42 Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels killed 42 government
troops in three clashes this week, ignoring a cease-fire declared
by Angola, Cuba and South Africa in the 13-year Angolan war, the
group said Friday.
   Also on Friday, the official Angolan news agency said Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Cuban diplomat Jorge Risquet
met to discuss the cease-fire, which was declared Monday.
   The news agency ANGOP said the Thurdsay meeting in Luanda, the
Angolan capital, also covered several unspecified bilateral issues.
The report, distributed in Lisbon, did not elaborate.
   In a military statement distributed in Lisbon, the rebel Union
for the Total Independence of Angola said it killed 10 soldiers
Wednesday in an ambush on an Army battalion just northwest of
Kuemba in the central province of Bie.
   On Tuesday, rebels ambushed government troops on a road near
Tomboko in northwestern Zaire province, killing seven soldiers, the
statement said. It said rebels killed 25 more soldiers Monday in a
battle near Chipendo in the southwestern province of Huila.
   Two guerrillas died and nine others were injured in the clashes,
the statement said.
   There was no independent confirmation of the claims.
   The rebels, with the backing of South Africa and the United
States, have fought since 1975 to force the Cuban and Soviet-backed
Marxist government to share power in the former Portuguese colony.
They are not a party to the cease-fire.
   Monday's cease-fire was the first step in a three-way peace
agreement to end war in the region, achieve a withdrawal of Cuba's
50,000 troops in Angola and create an independent state in
neighboring South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, which now is
controlled by South Africa.
   Risquet is a member of the ruling Cuban Communist Party's
Politburo and headed Cuba's delegation to ongoing peace talks
between the three countries.
   Another round is set to be held later this month.
   The peace accord also calls for the eventual withdrawal of
Cuba's estimated 50,000 troops in Angola by a date still to be
negotiated.
   The rebels have demanded direct talks with the government.
Angola has rejected that.
</TEXT>
