<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GettySculptures     08-12 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Getty Sculptures,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Getty Museum Pulls Disputed Sculptures From Exhibition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several pieces of sculpture on loan to the J.
Paul Getty Museum have been removed from display after an
investigator said they fit the descriptions of pieces stolen from
an excavation in Italy 10 years ago.
   Two marble heads and associated hands and feet were removed from
the museum's Magna Grecia gallery, museum spokeswoman Lori Starr
said Thursday.
   Earlier this week, Italian magistrate Silvio Raffiotta told the
Los Angeles Times he was investigating the theft of Greek sculpture
from an archaeological site in Morgantina, Sicily, and that he
believed pieces of stolen statuary _ a face, hands and feet _ had
turned up in the Getty Museum.
   ``No one has presented any evidence to us that they are from
Morgantina,'' Starr said. However, she said, the museum removed the
pieces because they may fit the description of objects allegedly
stolen from the Morgantina site.
   The museum does not own the pieces, Ms. Starr said, adding that
they have been on loan from a private collector and will be
returned to the collector.
   According to terms of the loan agreement, the museum cannot
reveal the lender's name, she said. Raffiotta has not indicated the
museum may have known the origin of the pieces.
   Last month, Graziella Fiorentini, director of antiquities in
Agrigento, Sicily, alleged that a fifth-century B.C. classical
Greek statue, believed to be that of the Greek goddess Aphrodite,
may have been illegally removed from Morgantina in 1979. Her
allegations have triggered an investigation by Italian authorities
and Interpol, the Paris-based international police agency.
   That 7{-foot statue, unveiled by Getty last month, is said to be
the only acrolithic figure that has survived relatively intact from
head to foot. Acrolithic figures are composed of separately carved
marble heads, hands and feet attached to limestone or wood bodies.
   Raffiotta, who is independently investigating the thefts, said
he does not believe the Aphrodite was removed from Morgantina, but
indicated that two other statues from Morgantina were on display at
the Getty. He described the allegedly stolen objects as pieces of
acrolithic statues.
</TEXT>
