<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-PLO     08-12 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Delegation Meets Jordanians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Zaid Rifai met Friday with a
high-level PLO delegation to discuss Jordan's decision to cut
official ties with Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   A senior PLO official said the talks centered on bilateral ties
in light of the recent Jordanian move and proposals for a
Palestinian government-in-exile, currently under discussion in the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   King Hussein two weeks ago severed legal and administrative ties
to the West Bank, which Jordan ruled from 1948 until 1967 when the
area was captured by Israel.
   State-run Jordan radio said only that Friday's meeting centered
``on issues of mutual concern.''
   The PLO official, who spoke on condition of anoymity, said the
two sides discussed the status of Jordanian passports held by
Palestinians, the rights of employees in the occupied territories
recently fired by Jordan and ``the implications of these measures
on the future of Palestinians.''
   Hussein has scrapped a $1.3 billion development plan for the
West Bank and Gaza strip, cancelled the salaries of 21,200 local
employees and dissolved the lower house of parliament, half of
whose 60 members represented the West Bank.
   But the king has not yet anounced a decision on the validity of
Jordanian passports held by most of the 850,000 West Bank
Palestinians.
   More than half of the 2.8 million Jordanians are of Palestinian
origin.
   The PLO official said the visiting delegation also was preparing
for a long-expected visit of the group's leader, Yasser Arafat.
   Asked if Arafat would visit Jordan this month, the official
replied: ``God willing, he might.'' Arafat was in Libya on Friday
for meetings with leader Moammar Gadhafi about his proposal to pay
the salaries of West Bank workers fired by Jordan, the official
Libyan news agency JANA said.
   A senior Jordanian official, who also requested anonymity, said
earlier this week that the PLO team would discuss the possibility
of Jordan's reconsidering its decision to sever ties with the
occupied territories.
   But Hussein told reporters last weekend that the option of
reversing the decision ``does not exist.''
   The PLO delegation has scheduled two more days of talks with
Jordanian officials.
</TEXT>
