<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MiracleRecovery     08-12 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miracle Recovery,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Emerges From Two Months In Coma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite doctors' fears that a
47-year-old woman would not survive massive head and chest
injuries, she emerged from a two-month coma by speaking her
husband's name and nodding to her doctor.
   Yung Hsu was struck by a truck June 2 when she and her husband,
Bill, crossed a street.
   ``I prayed for a miracle and it is true now. It came true,''
said Hsu, 47, who immigrated from Taiwan 24 years ago.
   Mrs. Hsu surprised her doctor Saturday by raising two fingers
and nodding her head to show she understood him.
   Hsu looked into his wife's eyes and saw recognition.
   ``I said, `If you hear me, nod your head,''' he said.
   Mrs. Hsu, a patient at Memorial Medical Center, nodded again.
   But what moved her husband most was when his wife spoke his name
Sunday.
   ``I called her name and she called me back,'' Hsu said. ``That
is the moment I was really happy.''
   Doctors said she has a chance for a full recovery, said Hsu.
   The driver of the truck, Brett Damon Hayes, 24, is scheduled to
be arraigned on drunken driving charges Aug. 18 in Orange County
Municipal Court.
