<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoastGuardMoney     08-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coast Guard Money,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Drug Team Eager To `Stir It Up With The Opposition'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard's busiest drug interdiction team is
delighted to have a share of $60 million in emergency money and
ready to ``stir it up with the opposition,'' a Coast Guard official
said Friday.
   ``There's nothing worse than being on a ship that won't get
under way,'' said Capt. John Linnon, chief of staff of the Seventh
Coast Guard District, which stretches from South Carolina, Georgia,
Florida and the Caribbean to Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula.
   ``The people in the Coast Guard are happy to get back to work.
We're ready to stir it up with the opposition,'' he said.
   Congress on Thursday shifted $60 million to the Coast Guard to
help restore a variety of operations cut last winter. The shift was
part of a $672 million emergency spending bill.
   ``I'm delighted with this action,'' the Seventh District
commander, Rear Adm. Martin H. Daniell, said in a statement. ``Now
we can get our planes back in the air and our cutters out to sea
where they can do their job.''
   ``The budget fight is not over,'' Linnon said, standing in front
of the polished white cutters at the Coast Guard's Base Miami
Beach. ``The $60 million is what we need to finish out the (fiscal)
year.''
   Linnon said the Seventh District, the busiest in drug
intervention efforts, had to cut to three of the biggest,
deep-water cutters per day and had seen seizures drop by half from
January to August. Now, the district will be able to put to sea six
or seven cutters.
   The district had already started to increase patrols in
anticipation of the budget shift.
   ``We've proven over the years that it (increased activity) makes
a difference,'' he said.
   The money will be spread among all 10 of Coast Guard districts
and will go toward a variety of needs, including resuming training,
replenishing spare parts, carrying out deferred maintenance and
resuming patrols. Linnon said he hasn't seen how the money will be
distributed, but more than 25 percent of District 7's budget is
spent on stopping drug traffic.
   ``I see this as an excellent signal that the Congress will
support the president's Coast Guard budget for the upcoming fiscal
year,'' said Adm. Paul A. Yost, commandant of the Coast Guard.
``Now that we have the $60 million we are ready to charge ahead.''
   In January, the Coast Guard said it was being forced to cut back
anti-drug efforts by 55 percent because of a shortage of money. The
impact of the cuts was most sharply felt in the Southeast because
90 percent of all Coast Guard seizures are made in the waters off
Florida, Georgia, South Carolina and the Caribbean Basin, officials
said.
   During the cutback, the Coast Guard averaged about 100 cutter
days per month in District 7, but that number could double with the
additional money.
   During the cutback, the Coast Guard had continued to respond to
reports of suspicious activity on the seas, but had cut back on
routine patrols.
</TEXT>
