<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     08-12 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criticism of Romania Urged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent historian and an editor
published open letters Friday urging the reformist Soviet weekly
Moscow News to condemn what they characterized as repression in
Romania.
   ``When human rights are trampled underfoot, it cannot be seen as
just an `internal affair,' whether this happens in South Africa,
Chile or Romania,'' wrote historian Miklos Kun, the son of Bela
Kun, who led the abortive Soviet republic established in Hungary in
1919.
   ``By what title do we condemn racial persecution ... dictatorial
regimes ... around the world if, in a Romania that belongs to the
socialist camp, there is not even the semblance of democracy?'' Kun
asked.
   He took issue with a Moscow News article on the dispute between
Warsaw Pact allies Hungary and Romania over the alleged
discrimination against ethnic Hungarians living in Romania.
   The article, published in a July edition of the Soviet weekly,
was careful not to take sides in the dispute.
   But Kun said he considers it ``incorrect'' that the weekly
``does not raise its voice against Romanian arbitrariness.''
Romania is socialism's ``last bastion of the cult of personality,''
he said, painting a dismal picture of alleged repression there.
   Kun's letter was published in the Aug. 14 edition of New Mirror,
along with a similar letter from the weekly's editor, Sandor
Fekete, who said he hoped Moscow News would drop its neutral stance.
   He said an open, informative press should be able to express its
opinion even if the Soviet government stays out of the
Hungarian-Romanian dispute.
   Moscow News recently started publishing a Hungarian-language
edition.
</TEXT>
