<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Best-DressedPolice     08-12 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Best-Dressed Police,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Stafford Police Department Is Nation's Best-Dressed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAFFORD TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next time Hollywood's
directors want to outfit actors for a cops 'n' robbers epic, they
should pay a visit to this tiny town, home of the nation's
best-dressed police.
   ``We stand for spit and polish,'' Chief Larry D. Parker, a
former military police officer, said Friday.
   The award has been handed out for 11 years by the National
Association of Uniform Manufacturers and Distributors, based in New
York.
   Stafford Township officers, working out of headquarters in the
Manahawkin section of the rural, southern New Jersey community,
bested more than 300 departments nationwide, said the executive
director of the association, Bernard J. Lepper.
   Oregon state police won the best-dressed state police award; the
Pinellas County sheriff's department in Florida won the top county
honors, and the Denver police department received the award for
best-dressed municipality with more than 200 officers.
   Stafford Township, with 37 officers and 10 uniformed, civilian
dispatchers, took the award for best-dressed municipality with
under 200 officers, and also walked away with the grand national
prize.
   The department's uniform consists of slate-gray trousers and a
midnight-blue shirt with matching epaulets and chrome buttons.
All-leather accessories _ including the belt and holster _ are made
of an intricate basket-weave design. A slate-gray Stetson hat
completes the outfit.
   ``We have daily inspections, and we've sent people home if they
don't pass,'' Parker said. ``If they need to change their trousers
or get a haircut, they go home and make up for it on their own
time.''
   Parker is an instructor at the Ocean County police academy, and
said he teaches his classes that ``90 percent of an officer's
effectiveness is determined by his uniform. If he looks sharp and
feels proud, all he really needs is some voice control and a sense
of personal control.''
   Even if a community cannot afford fancy uniforms, ``you can
still look sharp. A uniform can still be creased, be clean and
shoes can always be shined,'' he said.
   Lepper said the manufacturers assocation evaluates entrants on
image projection, ease of identification, reflection of the
department's authority and professionalism, practicality and
protection from weather and physical attacks.
   The police departments also are scrutinized on how carefully
they follow through on their dress code, he said.
   ``The single most important thing is that a police department
must have consistency,'' he said. ``We want every police officer to
look the same.''
   The judges included a master tailor, a New York City police
lieutenant and the publisher of Law and Order, a police magazine.
   The 56-year-old uniform association represents textile mills,
uniform manufacturers, dealer distributors and accessory
manufacturers, Lepper said.
   It also sponsors annual awards for the best-dressed high school
or college band, and the Image of the Year awards, which includes
uniforms from car rental agencies, airlines, real estate agencies
and other companies.
   ``A police officer's uniform is extremely important,'' Lepper
said. ``When someone has an auto accident or has been mugged or
assaulted, it's very comforting to see a police officer's uniform.''
   ``Of course, it's different if you're getting a parking
ticket,'' he joked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
