<1ST_LINE>r p AM-JacksonVideo     08-12 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Video,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Order Extended Barring Sale of Videotape Jackson Never Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson won an extension Friday of a
temporary court order barring a suburban company from selling or
distributing videotapes of his Democratic National Convention
speech.
   U.S. District Judge James B. Zagel extended a temporary ban and
indicated he would issue a preliminary injunction Tuesday barring
MPI Home Video from profiting from the former presidential
candidate's speech until the whole issue can be decided at trial.
   The case is set to go to trial Aug. 30 unless the two sides
reach agreement, said Henry Mason, a Jackson attorney.
   ``I'm pleased with the result,'' Mason said. ``He ruled in our
favor, on a preliminary basis.''
   But Eric Cohen, an attorney for Oak Forest-based MPI, said he
would appeal and declined further comment.
   Jackson, who was not in court Friday, contends the tape
exploited his name and literary and oratorical skills, and hurt his
livelihoood by diminishing his chances of selling his own tape of
the speech.
   In his ruling, Zagel agreed, saying there is ``more than
negligible probability that (Jackson) earns part of his living ...
on his oratory.'' He added that even the defendants acknowledged
their videotape ``will hurt anything Jackson tries to sell.''
   MPI President Waleed B. Ali and his attorneys argue that MPI
didn't need Jackson's authorization because his hour-long speech
July 19 in Atlanta was a news event, unprotected by federal
copyright law. MPI paid ABC for the rights to its coverage.
   But Zagel said the speech ``is an original literary work.'' The
judge added that the fact that Jackson had waited to copyright the
speech until after he learned of Ali's enterprise was insignificant.
   Ali said Thursday that he was motivated to make the tape by
money and the event's historic importance.
   ``I thought we had a hot-seller,'' Ali testified.
   As for the suggestion that he should have obtained Jackson's
permission before selling the tapes, he said, ``Why should our
medium be singled out as the only medium to get approval?''
</TEXT>
