<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ElderlyJudge     08-12 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly Judge,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toombs County Judge, 91, Elected To 12th Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYONS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toombs County Probate Judge Annie Laurie
Hussey is no ordinary politician.
   This week, Mrs. Hussey _ at 91 _ won her 12th consecutive
four-year term. She did not campaign nor did she spend a cent
except for a qualifying fee of $767.25.
   ``I just stayed in my office and worked,'' she said.
   ``I didn't see spending all that money on posters and cards.
I've lived here all my life and didn't see any use in having to
introduce myself to the public,'' she said.
   She received 3,110 votes to 2,695 votes for her opponent in the
Democratic primary, Jackie Driskell, a 41-year-old legal secretary.
There is no Republican candidate.
   ``It's as close a race as I ever run,'' Mrs. Hussey said in a
telephone interview Friday.
   ``The reason I ran again was that all the lawyers in town all
came to me and asked me to stay on,'' she said. ``That was a great
boost and I've tried to keep up with all the new laws to help
them.''
   Asked if she will run again in four years, Mrs. Hussey said:
``Time tells the tale. I don't know, but my health is better now
than when I was 50. I always have a checkup every six months. I
think that's the secret to my health.''
</TEXT>
