<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-NJ,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Farmers Eligible for Drought Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey farmers are eligible to apply for
Farmers Home Administration emergency loans to help cover part of
their crop drought losses, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng
announced Friday.
   Lyng said farmers in all of the state's 21 counties have eight
months in which to apply for the loans to help cover part of their
actual losses. To be eligible, they must be able to repay the FmHA
loan and any other loans, must be unable to get credit elsewhere,
and must have adequate security, he said.
   New Jersey is the 10th entire state designated eligible for FmHA
emergency drought loans. Others are Alabama, Delaware, Indiana,
Iowa, Maryland, Missouri, Ohio, Wisconsin and West Virginia.
