<HEAD>Police Arrest 26 More Abortion Foes, Including Four Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-six more anti-abortion activists were
arrested outside a women's clinic Friday, including the four people
who drove the the protesters to the site.
   The total number of arrests in the series of demonstrations,
which began July 19 during the Democratic National Convention,
reached 381 with the latest incident.
   The arrests of the four drivers marked a new strategy for
Atlanta police. The vehicles were impounded, and police said the
drivers would be charged with being party to a crime, a misdemeanor.
   The 22 others were arrested as they locked arms, sang and prayed
outside the Atlanta SurgiCenter, scene of a protest Thursday. Sgt.
Melvin Denson said Friday's protesters would be charged with
criminal trespass and obstructing highways and sidewalks.
   Twenty-two people were arrested at the clinic Thursday,
including six who were charged with terroristic acts after they
entered the clinic.
   On Friday, the demonstrators were under strict orders from their
leaders not to enter the clinic. A spokesman said Operation Rescue,
the group that organized the demonstrations, does not condone
actions such as entering the clinics.
   Many of those arrested in the series of demonstrations have
remained in jail because they refused to give their names,
identifying themselves only as Baby John Doe or Baby Jane Doe.
   On Friday, authorities said 160 remained behind bars.
   Six protesters had preliminary hearings Friday in Municipal
Court, and all but one were transferred to State Court for further
proceedings. A felony count of obstruction against the sixth was
transferred to Superior Court.
