<2ND_LINE>AM-Sophie's Choice,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Sophie's Choice' as Anti-Litter Slogan Draws Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Sophie's Choice'' is Mayor Sophie Masloff's
theme for her anti-litter campaign, but people familiar with the
book and film of the same name say the slogan is in poor taste.
   William Styron's book told the story of a Polish woman sent to a
World War II concentration camp who was forced by the Nazis to
choose which of her two children would be killed.
   ``I love Sophie dearly. I wish she had chosen another slogan by
virtue of the fact it can raise an issue,'' said Richard Marcovitz,
rabbi at Congregation B'nai Israel.
   ``I think it was in bad taste,'' said Councilwoman Michelle
Madoff.
   ``The reason it doesn't bother me is I know Sophie Masloff
personally and I know the furthest thing from her mind would be
anything that in the least bit would have any negative
implications,'' said Stanley Ruskin, chairman of the Pittsburgh
chapter of the American Jewish Committee.
   ``It's just a catch phrase. That's why I chose it, not for any
significance at all,'' the mayor said Thursday.
   ``This Sophie's Choice might not win an Academy Award, but it's
my No. 1 priority,'' said Mrs. Masloff.
   The clean-up campaign includes buying new street sweeping
machines, setting out additional trash containers, paving 70 miles
of city streets this year and cleaning every vacant city lot by
October.
