<HEAD>Robertson to Call for Unity at Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of former Republican candidate Pat
Robertson were talking unity Friday after months of wrangling with
the Bush campaign over delegations to the GOP National Convention.
   Aides to the television evangelist said his name will not be
placed in nomination against Vice President George Bush, and they
promised no more than traditional convention floor demonstrations
when Robertson delivers his prime-time address Tuesday night.
   His speech will focus on many of the issues Robertson has
stressed during the campaign, including foreign policy and moral
values.
   ``And there will be a call for unity,'' said Barbara N.
Gattullo, director of communications for Americans for Robertson.
   She said, ``There are no plans to put his name in nomination. He
will release his delegates.''
   Robertson, who suspended his campaign on May 16, has 93
delegates according to The Associated Press survey. Vice President
George Bush has 1,998 delegates, many more than the 1,139 needed to
nominate.
   The former presidential candidate, who has returned to the
Christian Broadcasting Network, also will campaign for Bush in the
fall, Ms. Gattullo said.
   The talk of party unity comes after bitter fights in states such
as Michigan and Georgia over representation for Robertson
supporters in the state parties and the delegations attending the
convention.
   The Michigan battle was resolved prior to the Republican
gathering this week. The Bush and Robertson campaigns settled their
dispute in Georgia on Wednesday with Robertson supporters gaining
28 of the state's 48 delegate seats.
   The solution to Georgia's fierce fight was still being hailed by
the Robertson people on Friday.
   ``Georgia was a matter of definition,'' said Ms. Gattullo.
   ``There's a feeling of harmony because of the fair treatment of
the Georgia delegation,'' said Marc Nuttle, former campaign manager
for Robertson.
   Later, Nuttle called the Georgia resolution ``the bellwether in
making the Republican Party the party of the 1990s.''
   Nuttle's comments came as he released results of a survey of 250
Robertson supporters conducted immediately after the Democratic
National Convention. It found 69 percent definitely or at least
probably supporting Bush to 17 percent for Dukakis with the rest
undecided.
   Sixty-six percent said they would vote for Bush even if they
learned that he had had full knowledge of the Iran-Contra affair.
   Bush's selection of a vice president, a major concern among
conservative groups, may affect support for the Republican nominee,
according to Nuttle, but only if the choice is a liberal.
   ``There is a wide range of tolerance for vice president,''
Nuttle said. ``There's no evidence to indicate it's a volatile
issue.''
</TEXT>
