<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Posner-Paintings     08-12 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Posner-Paintings,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwell Paintings To Be Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Miami Beach financier Victor
Posner says he has agreed to return 13 Norman Rockwell paintings he
took from Sharon Steel Corp. after he bought the company in 1969.
   The announcement in U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Warren Bentz's
courtroom Thursday by attorney Robert Cindrich was the company
chairman's first response to a lawsuit filed over the paintings.
   James W. Toren, a trustee appointed by the court to run Sharon
Steel during its Chapter 11 reorganization, sued for the return of
the art in June.
   The paintings have hung in Posner's Florida office for nearly 20
years.
   Cindrich said Posner does not have a 14th painting mentioned in
Toren's lawsuit. Russell Ober Jr., an attorney for the trustee,
said he will file a claim holding Posner responsible for that
painting.
   None of the attorneys could estimate the value of the paintings,
for which Sharon Steel paid Rockwell $50,000 in 1966.
   A single Rockwell illustration for a light bulb manufacturer
recently sold at auction for $200,000, said Linda Russell, an
assistant curator at the Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass.
   ``The Japanese are terribly interested in Rockwell,'' she said.
   Rockwell, best known for his folksy Saturday Evening Post cover
illustrations, died in 1978.
