<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeAcker     08-12 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Acker,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Wants Government Opinion Before Deciding To Remove Self From
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge removed from a Ku Klux
Klan case by an appeals court said Friday he wants to hear from the
nation's top civil rights enforcer before deciding to remove
himself from all government cases.
   U.S. District Judge William M. Acker Jr., during a hearing on
his own fitness for trial in government cases, said he did not know
how he will rule eventually.
   But, he said, ``I have made my mind up that I am not going to
rule on my motion to recuse until I hear from William Bradford
Reynolds,'' director of the civil rights division of the Justice
Department.
   The U.S. attorney in Birmingham said earlier the Justice
Department would not take part in Friday's hearing and would not
seek Acker's blanket removal from federal government cases.
   The Justice Department is involved in two long-running civil
rights cases in Alabama _ one involving the Ku Klux Klan and the
other involving allegations of segregation at the state's colleges.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals removed Acker from the
Klan case, saying his position against the government had become
hardened. Acker, 60, was appointed to the bench in 1982 by
President Reagan.
   By luck of the draw, however, Acker this week was assigned the
school case after the appeals court removed U.S. District Judge
U.W. Clemon, the first black federal judge in Alabama. Te appeals
court said Clemon could not be impartial because he had championed
desegregation efforts as a state senator and civil rights attorney.
   Since the Justice Department urged the appeals court to remove
him from the Klan case, Acker said he wants to know whether
Reynolds will object if he hears the school case. The Justice
Department had joined in the suit, which alleges race bias exists
in higher education programs and funding.
   ``I presume the 11th Circuit Court is reasonable,'' Acker said
Friday. ``They say I'm partial. If a reasonable person thinks I'm
partial, should I sit on federal cases?''
   Clemon, appointed to the bench by President Carter in 1980, was
among the spectators during Acker's hearing on his own motion for
recusal but did not comment. Three attorneys, who are not involved
in either case, did offer testimony that they had found Acker to be
fair and impartial when they had matters before him.
   Clemon said earliers this week that he was the victim of a
double standard demeaning to black federal jurists.
   Acker said he had invited responses from a wide variety of legal
and judicial organizations and individuals but had received only
one, from U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson of Birmingham in which
Donaldson said the United States ``has at this time insufficient
information to determine and no reason to believe that Judge
Acker's proposed general recusal is either necessary or
appropriate.''
</TEXT>
