<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirConditioning     08-12 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Conditioning,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Governor Relents, Will Back Air Conditioning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR L. SRB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer's unrelenting heat finally wore
down Gov. Tommy G. Thompson's resistance to air-conditioning the
Capitol.
   Thompson, who had vetoed a budget item for installation of air
conditioning, said Friday he was ``acquiescing.''
   The governor's surprise backing followed a facetious suggestion
from Rep. Marlin Schneider that impeachment proceedings might begin
if Thompson refused to budge.
   Statehouse employees were elated.
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' said Dianne McCaughy, a secretary
for Assembly Minority Leader Betty Jo Nelsen.
   Outside the governor's conference room, where Thompson made his
announcement, the mercury climbed to the 90-degree mark for the
30th day this summer. That was only 11 days short of a record set
in the mid-1930s, the Weather Service said.
   Several times this summer, when the temperature soared, the
Assembly has allowed workers in rooms that lacked window air
conditioners to take the afternooon off.
   Thompson, whose personal office has a room air conditioner as do
a number of legislators' offices, told reporters he encountered a
woman in the Capitol Thursday who told him she would ``be glad to
pay higher taxes'' for air conditioning in the building.
   ``I've acquiesced,'' Thompson said.
   Schneider said fears among the public that air conditioning the
70-year-old Capitol would lead to even lengthier legislative
sessions ``is absolutely ridiculous.''
   The reality, he said, is that workers' productivity drops in the
summertime because the building is so hot and uncomfortable.
   Schneider estimated that the project could cost as much as $6
million. About 1,000 people work in the building, he said.
</TEXT>
