<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-Book     08-12 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Book,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Assails Impeachment Conviction in Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham predicts he'll be
voted back into office by an electorate disgusted with the way he
was hounded from office by the state's political establishment.
   In a book titled ``Impeachment: The Arizona Conspiracy,'' Mecham
claims the real reason he was impeached and convicted of wrongdoing
in office was ``pure and simple raw political power exercised by
those groups who wanted to remain in control.''
   Mecham had the book printed privately and began selling it
Thursday for $2.95.
   ``It was clear that they (senators who voted to convict) did not
make that decision based on evidence,'' the former governor wrote.
   The Senate convicted Mecham on April 4 of misusing $80,000 from
the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership,
and of trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat.
   Mecham predicted public dissatisfaction with the impeachment
would lead to changes in the Legislature's makeup this fall,
adding, ``That should pave the way to win back the governorship
again.'' The next gubernatorial election is in November 1990, with
the winner to take office in January 1991.
   In May, Mecham was acquitted of criminal charges accusing him of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   ``In the final analysis, my error was not in what I did with the
(protocol) funds, but in thinking I was dealing with people who had
honor, integrity and the best interest of the state at heart,''
Mecham said in the book.
   On Thursday, Attorney General Bob Corbin filed a civil suit
asking that Mecham be forced to turn over the $80,000 remaining in
the protocol fund to the state. Mecham has insisted the fund is
private money and is seeking to return it to the donors himself.
   In his book, Mecham repeated his contention that some
establishment lawmakers, Corbin, the media and business leaders
banded together in a conspiracy to drive him from office.
   But he said they had only partly succeeded, adding, ``They have
not been able to fool all of the people in Arizona into believing
that Mecham was terrible for Arizona, a racial bigot or a mindless
buffoon ill-suited to be governor.''
</TEXT>
