<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CivilRightsCommission     08-12 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Civil Rights Commission,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Commission Approves New Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights on Friday
concurred in President Reagan's selection of William Barclay Allen,
a California professor, as the agency's chairman.
   He succeeds Clarence M. Pendleton Jr., who died June 5. The
commission's vote was 5-1.
   Allen, a professor of government at Harvey Mudd College in
Claremont, Calif., has served on the commission since April 1987.
He was an unsuccessful Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate in
1986.
   The 44-year-old Allen, designated by Reagan last Monday, said
then that he will not allow the commission ``to become an arm of
the advocacy groups in the civil rights movement.''
   Pendleton held a similar view, and his disagreements with civil
rights groups led to numerous charges and countercharges. Under
Pendleton, for instance, the commission majority took strong
positions against goals, timetables and quotas to remedy past
discrimination; and against giving women comparable pay to men in
jobs requiring similar skills.
   Allen called Pendleton ``the first bona fide civil rights
leader'' to serve as chairman.''
   ``I am not a civil rights leader, nor a black leader,'' Allen
said. ``I am rather an accomplished professional whose professional
and civic life demonstrate a commitment to the ideal of equal
rights for all.''
   Voting in favor of Allen were commissioners Francis S. Guess,
Robert Destro, Murray Friedman, Esther G.A. Buckley and Allen.
Commissioner Mary Frances Berry was opposed.
</TEXT>
