<HEAD>Home Firebombed After Family Speaks Out Against Gangs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Molotov cocktail was hurled through the
living room window of a couple who spoke out against gangs, and
authorities pledged they would wield ``a bigger knife'' to excise
gang violence from their city.
   The home of Jenny and Roscoe Bryant was heavily damaged Thursday
night, officials said.
   ``When decent, good people can't go to sleep at night without
having to worry that someone is going to throw something into their
house, that means there's a cancer that we've got to cut out,''
said Councilman Warren Dorris. ``We'll get a bigger knife if we
have to.''
   The bombing took place despite increased patrols. The Bryants
were among neighborhood residents who asked for the added
protection and met with officials of this northern Illinois city to
discuss gang violence.
   A bottle of flammable liquid was thrown through the window 10:30
p.m. Thursday, Battalion Fire Chief Frank Ragusa said.
   It was not the first time the Bryants experienced violence this
summer.
   A suspicious fire destroyed another home they owned; the family
dog was shot dead; their car and house were peppered with bullets.
   ``They (gang members) holler at me all the time saying I'm the
lady who wants to put them in jail,'' Mrs. Bryant said.
