<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreeNeedles     08-12 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Free Needles,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City To Begin Giving Needles To Addicts In November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial plan to provide free sterile
needles to drug addicts will begin in November as authorities try
to stem the spread of AIDS among drug abusers, the city health
commissioner said Friday.
   ``There were problems with law enforcement agencies, but we've
worked those bugs out,'' said Dr. Stephen C. Joseph, who expects
the program to start in about 10 weeks. ``They now agree with us
that this is not an illegal program.''
   The state Health Department approved the experiment this week,
Joseph said. The progam will involve 200 addicts and last six to
nine months.
   ``That's enough time for us to get a fair amount of data to
enable us to draw some conclusions,'' Joseph said. ``If something
goes wrong, if we are mistaken, we can stop things at any time.''
   Needles are already distributed in several other countries, but
no government agency in the United States has such a program. A
social service agency in Portland, Ore., however, announced plans
in June to begin a needle distribution program, but the program has
been held up.
   The use of dirty needles has become the leading method of
infection among new cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome in
New York City.
   If the New York experiment is a success, city officials hope to
broaden distribution among the city's estimated 200,000 intravenous
drug abusers. Sample blood tests indicate about half of that group
are already infected with the AIDS virus.
   Some prosecutors and leaders of the black community are among
those who oppose the needle plan, saying it will promote illicit
drug abuse.
   ``The end is commendable, of course,'' said Manhattan Borough
President David Dinkins. ``But I maintain that drug use is
unacceptable, and I do not accept the notion that we can make drugs
safer.''
</TEXT>
