<DOCNO> AP880812-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Navy-Pakistan     08-12 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy-Pakistan,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan to Lease Retiring US Warships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan, long troubled by the naval buildup
of arch-foe India, has struck a deal to lease up to eight of the 16
U.S. Navy frigates that are being retired for budgetary reasons,
officials said Friday.
   The deal, outlined to Congress on Thursday, makes all the more
final the Pentagon's grudging decision early this spring to suspend
the Reagan administration's drive for a 600-ship Navy.
   Although the ships are being leased and not sold to Pakistan _
and can be recalled if needed by the Navy _ ``it would probably
take a war for us to ask for them back,'' said one official who
asked not to be identified.
   Lt. Barbara Kent, a Navy spokeswoman, said Congress was informed
of the deal in a letter from Rear Adm. Thomas C. Lynch, the Navy's
chief of legislative affairs. Congress has 30 days to block the
transaction if it wishes to do so, she said.
   The spokeswoman said Pakistan would be allowed to inspect nine
frigates. According to another official who asked not to be named,
however, Pakistani officials have been told they can lease a
maximum of eight ships.
   A top congressional aide, who also requested anonymity, said
Congress was unlikely to intervene ``because the decision has
already been made to cut back the U.S. fleet.''
   ``The decision was made up here not to keep these ships in
service because of the cost of operating them, so if Pakistan wants
to take on that expense, we have no objection,'' the aide said.
   The ships, because of their age and boiler plants, require a
disproportionate number of sailors to operate compared with modern
warships.
   According to Lt. Kent, Pakistan has yet to say exactly how many
frigates it wants. The Navy, assuming Congress goes along, will
begin allowing Pakistani inspections of nine frigates in October,
she said.
   The Navy declined Friday to say how much Pakistan would pay for
the warships.
   But according to figures compiled by the Defense Security
Assistance Agency, the highest rental fee that Pakistan would be
charged for eight frigates would be $6.31 million per year.
   Pakistan is being offered an initial five-year lease on the
ships, but any agreement ``can be terminated at any time,'' the
Navy spokeswoman said.
   She identified the nine ships to be offered to the Pakistanis as
the Brooke, Ramsey, Schofield, Talbot, Page, Bradley, Edward
McDonnell, O'Callahan and Sample.
   The Brooke, Ramsey, Schofield, Bradley and O'Callahan are based
in San Diego, Calif. The Talbot and Edward McDonnell are based in
Mayport, Fla., while the Page is based in Norfolk, Va., and the
Sample in Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
   The deal with Pakistan is being struck five months after India
leased a nuclear-powered attack submarine from the Soviet Union for
its navy.
   ``The Indian navy is getting to be a powerful force,'' said one
Pentagon source. ``Pakistan is naturally concerned and they're
prepared to put forward the manpower needed to operate these
ships.''
   The American frigates being offered to Pakistan are of the
so-called Garcia and Brooke classes. They were built in the
mid-1960s.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci announced early this year in
unveiling the Pentagon's fiscal 1989 budget plan he had ordered the
Navy to retire the 16 frigates. He said the move was just one of
several designed to shrink U.S. military forces rather than
maintain a ``hollow'' force that wasn't ready to fight.
   That decision was stridently criticized by Navy Secretary James
H. Webb, who resigned in protest in February.
   Two months ago, the Navy announced it would decommission the
first 10 of the frigates by the end of this year and the remaining
six in 1989.
   The 16 ships are operated by more than 5,100 sailors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
