<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Seal Funding,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Body Funds Study of Dead Seals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
announced a grant of $54,500 Friday to a Dutch research group
trying to determine what is killing thousands of harbor seals in
the North Sea.
   It also allocated $654,000 to a four-year research project on
algae growth in the North Sea. Some seals have died in waters where
algae have increased, but no clear link has been established.
   The Dutch institute is trying to identify the viruses that have
killed up to half the harbor seal populations in Scandinanvian,
West German and Dutch waters. About 7,000 harbor seals have died
since April.
   The Dutch National Institute of Public Health and Environmental
Protection at Pieterburen also is trying to develop vaccines
against the viruses and looking into dangers they may pose for
other species, including humans.
</TEXT>
