<HEAD>Man Who Complained About Crime Arrested For Robbery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note `damn' in penultimate graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who criticized the local judicial
system in May for being lenient on lawbreakers was charged with
armed robbery on Friday.
   Rex M. Truelove, 20, was charged with aggravated robbery in
connection with the hold-up of Cook's Drive Thru beverage store
Thursday night.
   Police said Truelove entered the cashier's office at the
business, pointed a .22-caliber revolver at employee Kenny Haddix
and demanded money. Haddix gave the man between $400 and $500,
police said.
   In a letter to the editor in the May 10 edition of the Urbana
Daily Citizen, Truelove complained that an incident at a fast-food
restaurant resulted in only mild punishment. A man entered the
restaurant with a 9mm rifle May 1 while Truelove was present.
   ``Now they have one who attempted to rob a store and they are
releasing him with only fines to pay. I think the damn judicial
system is very intolerable to many citizens of Urbana,'' the letter
said.
   Police said the incident was not an attempted robbery but an
argument between Truelove, who worked at the restaurant, and
another man. The other man brandished a weapon and was charged with
aggravated menacing.
