<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Referendum     08-12 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Referendum,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Chiefs Not Receptive to Church Proposal on Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chile's military rulers gave no sign
Friday of accepting a Roman Catholic church proposal that they
negotiate with the opposition about the nominee for the October
presidential referendum.
   Gen. Fernando Matthei, chief of the air force, told a news
conference the idea was ``interesting'' but indicated he does not
plan such negotiations before the commanders meet Aug. 30 to select
the nominee. President Augusto Pinochet, the army commander, is
expected to be their choice.
   ``I'll take it into account when we meet in 18 days,'' Matthei
said.
   Adm. Jose Merino, the navy commander, said after the proposal
was made Thursday that ``it's too late'' for an accord with the
opposition.
   Pinochet, the army commander, indirectly rejected the bishop's
proposal in an address to businessmen Thursday. He said his
government would abide by the 1980 constitution, which says the
commanders of the three armed forces and the national police will
make the nomination.
   Bishops of the Episcopal Conference recommended negotiations
because ``Chile is becoming polarized and radicalized'' and the
referendum might result in a virtual tie unless the opposition
accepts the nominee, whose name will be alone on the ballot.
   Leaders of an opposition alliance formed to promote a ``no''
vote in the referendum expressed willingness to negotiate about a
choice.
   If the nominee gets a majority of the yes-or-no vote, he will
begin an eight-year term in March. If he loses, Pinochet is to
remain in office until an open presidential election in 1990.
   Pinochet, 72, led a coup in September 1973 that ousted the late
President Salvador Allende, an elected Marxist.
</TEXT>
