<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignFinances 1stLd-Writethru a0766 08-12 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Finances, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Leads All Candidates For Congress In PAC Contributions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with quotes, details; adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, led all
candidates for Congress in contributions from political action
committees in the first 18 months of the current election cycle,
according to the Federal Election Commission.
   Bentsen's campaign for re-election to the Senate collected
almost $1.7 million in contributions from PACs between Jan. 1,
1987, and June 30, 1988, the FEC reported this week. Sen. Pete
Wilson, R-Calif., was second, with $1.14 million in PAC
contributions.
   Bentsen is also running a simultaneous race as the vice
presidential running mate of Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis, who does not accept contributions from PACs.
   Bentsen's spokesman, Jack DeVore, said the senator had no plans
to stop accepting PAC contributions for his Senate campaign because
Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, does not accept them.
   ``Governor Dukakis has said on many occasions he did not try to
select a clone,'' DeVore said.
   He said Bentsen's plans for the Senate contest ``were made long
before this vice presidential nomination came up and he will
proceed with them.''
   The senior senator from Texas, Bentsen has been chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee since January 1987. In that role, he is
influential in shaping tax and trade legislation that affects
business and industry nationwide.
   The FEC said the senator's campaign also took in almost $4.3
million in contributions from individuals in the 18-month period,
which combined with PAC money totals and other sources totaled
almost $6.3 million for his race against Republican Rep. Beau
Boulter.
   That total puts Bentsen in second place in contributions to
Senate candidates, behind only Wilson, who had more than $6.8
million.
   Bentsen has spent more than $3 million on the Senate race and
had more than $3.8 million cash on hand at the end of June, the FEC
report said.
   He ranks fourth in spending among Senate candidates and is
second place for cash on hand, it said.
   Boulter, meanwhile, has raised $587,319 and spent $582,745. He
had debts of $152,777 at the end of June and $14,097 cash on hand,
the FEC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
