<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-USTrade     08-12 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-US Trade,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Begins Final Debate on Trade Deal With US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Final consideration of the U.S.-Canada Free Trade
Agreement began Friday with parliamentary debate on one of 102
amendments proposed by opposition parties trying to scuttle it.
   The agreement, which would scrap all duties over a 10-year
period and reduce non-tariff barriers, was proposed by Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and accepted late last year by the Reagan
administration.
   It is scheduled to take effect Jan. 1, but Mulroney now faces a
much tougher job than President Reagan to getting the agreement
ratified.
   Enabling legislation passed the U.S. House of Representatives on
Tuesday by a vote of 366-40 and the Senate is expected to give its
approval next month.
   In Canada, the main opposition Liberal Party and the socialist
New Democratic Party claim the agreement jeopardizes Canadian
resources and could change the nation's way of life.
   They want Mulroney, leader of the Conservative Party, to call a
general election, which in effect would let the voters decide
whether the it should be accepted.
   Mulroney need not call an election until his five-year term
expires in 12 months, but Canadian governments generally seek a new
mandate after about four years. He said this this week he wants
free trade and other key legislation passed before he considers an
election date.
   His Conservatives are expected to use their large majority in
the House of Commons to cut delaying tactics short next week and
secure a third and final reading of the measure next week.
   The bill could get bogged down in the Senate, Canada's appointed
second chamber that has a Liberal majority. Liberal leader John
Turner has asked the Senate to delay the bill until an election.
   Friday's debate in the Commons began with a Liberal amendment
noting that the pact does not define Canadian boundaries,
especially disputed waters in the Arctic. The government dismissed
the amendment as frivolous and refused to join the debate.
   Rep. John LaFalce, a Democrat from Niagara Falls, N.Y. and a
free-trade supporter, told Congress this week ``a major trade war''
could start if Canada does not ratify the accord.
   David Peterson, the Liberal premier of Ontario, responded:
``It's the largest trading partnership in the world. I'm not saying
there wouldn't be some hard feelings, but that would pass.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
