<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Solidarity     08-12 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solidarity,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Sees Change in Government Attitude</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government recognized a foundation
conceived by Solidarity, pointing to a softening of its stand on
activists of the outlawed independent trade movement, one of the
movement's leaders said Thursday.
   However, Zbigniew Bujak said the labor movement still faces
major obstacles in regaining legal status. Bujak led Solidarity in
the Warsaw region until the movement was banned after martial law
was imposed in December 1981.
   In an unexpected move, the government earlier this week approved
registration of a foundation conceived by Bujak and other
Solidarity leaders to help large families in need, Bujak said.
   ``I was completely surprised. I didn't expect such a decision.
It's certainly connected with a general trend of change toward
Solidarity activists,'' he said.
   Bujak said government registration of a health care foundation
now being organized by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa would
represent an even greater step in the trade group's efforts to
regain legal status.
   ``Registration of Lech's foundation, connected even in name with
Solidarity, will be a huge step toward legalization of the whole
Solidarity,'' said Bujak.
   The foundation's plans to operate three health care clinics have
been delayed because the government had refused to recognize it.
   Walesa declined to discuss the future of the foundation.
   Worker protests in August 1980 led to creation of Solidarity,
the only free trade union movement in the Soviet bloc.
   While Solidarity activists continue to fight court battles to
restore the movement's legal status at the factory level, the
group's leaders are trying to create foundations to help Polish
society with money received as gifts or prizes from abroad.
   The courts so far have refused every factory-level request to
restore legal status to Solidarity itself.
   Last year, Bujak shared the annual human rights award of the
U.S.-based Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Foundation, which carries a
prize of $40,000.
   Bujak's foundation for needy families initially will dispose of
about $2,200.
   Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize winner, and other Solidarity
leaders authorized creation of the Social Foundation for Workers
Solidarity last year to administer a $1 million grant from the U.S.
Congress.
</TEXT>
