<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOPRules     08-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Rules,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Shift Rules, Look for TV Boost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans approved convention rule changes
Friday they hope will get them more exposure on television:
dispensing with needless roll call votes and allowing governors and
members of Congress on the convention floor.
   Unlike the Democrats, Republicans do not automatically give
delegate status to high-ranking elected officials, and under
current rules the convention floor seating is restricted to the
delegates.
   Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., said it would be good to let the
politicians be seated on the floor of the convention so they could
``rub elbows with the backbone of the party.''
   But it's the reporters and the TV cameras that the politicians
are interested in.
   ``That's where the press is,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who
sponsored the change to allow the politicians to have non-voting
seats on the convention floor. ``That's what we need to get
elected.''
   The rule change, if given final approval by the entire
convention, would not take effect until 1992.
   The other change, which would dispense with an hour-long roll
call for the vice presidential nomination if there is just one
candidate, was designed to conserve precious prime time on the TV.
   That rule change, requested by Vice President Bush's campaign,
takes immediate effect if approved by the convention and would
allow the Republicans to forego a Thursday night roll call next
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
