<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0675 08-12 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Reportedly Take Over Strategic Northern Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th pvs to UPDATE with report of
Pakistani arrested for espionage; two Pakistanis killed in fight.
PICKS up 8th pvs `Azim Nasser ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-communist Afghan guerrillas have
captured Kunduz, a strategic provincial capital in northeastern
Afghanistan, according to an unconfirmed report cited Friday by
Western diplomats.
   The Moslem insurgents, who usually are the first to publicize
their takeovers of Afghan towns even when they are temporary, have
said nothing about capturing Kunduz, the capital of Kunduz province.
   Kunduz, about 150 miles north of the Afghan capital of Kabul,
would be a significant gain for the guerrillas fighting the
Soviet-backed government.
   The city, 40 miles south of the Soviet border on the main
highway leading from Kabul to the Soviet Union, would be the first
Afghan provincial capital the rebels have won in the 10-year war.
   Most Soviet troops leaving the country under an April 14
U.N.-sponsored withdrawal agreement are taking another road to the
border at Heiratan, about 100 miles west of Kunduz.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and have been
helping the Marxist government battle the guerrillas. The Soviets
agreed to withdraw half their estimated 100,000 troops by Monday
under a pullout plan that began May 15 and is to be completed by
Feb. 15.
   State-run Radio Kabul said foreign journalists and local Afghans
witnessed ``hundreds'' of Red Army soldiers cross into the Soviet
Union on Thursday and Friday.
   The radio reported that a Pakistani national was arrested
Thursday for espionage as he carried two explosive devices in the
eastern city of Jalalabad. The government-controlled Bakhtar News
Agency said the unidentified Pakistani led Afghan army forces to a
guerrilla ammunition depot in Caprahar, six miles south of
Jalalabad.
   Radio Kabul also said two Pakistanis were among 70 people killed
during a clash between Afghan army troops and U.S.-backed Moslem
guerrillas in eastern Logar province. There was no information on
when the fighting occurred.
   It described the two Pakistanis as ``advisers'' to the
guerrillas.
   Azim Nasser Zia of the National Islamic Front of Afghanistan
resistance organization said guerrillas who arrived about 10 days
ago from Kunduz said nothing of the capital's capture or its
vulnerability to an imminent guerrilla takeover.
   The Afghan News Agency, which claims to be a mouthpiece of the
seven-party guerrilla alliance but is operated by members of
Gulbadin Hekmatyar's Hezb-e-Islami, also could not confirm the
capture of Kunduz. The loose and often fractured resistance
alliance is based in Peshawar in northwest Pakistan.
   A strategic gain in Afghanistan's resource-rich north would
dampen any hopes the Afghan government might have for the north as
a fallback position if it is unable to hold Kabul.
   Western diplomats said Kabul might have designs on the north
after the government began heavy construction in the northern city
of Mazar-e-Sharif, appointed a deputy prime minister for the north
and consolidated its fighting forces under a single command.
   Afghan insurgents temporarily captured two provincial capitals
in southern and eastern Afghanistan since the Soviet withdrawal
began, but they were pushed back after heavy bombing attacks,
Western diplomats said.
   Pakistan, which has an estimated 2.5 million Afghan refugees as
well as guerrilla headquarters, signed the withdrawal agreement in
Geneva with the Afghan government. The United States, which backs
the insurgency, and the Soviet Union agreed to act as guarantors.
   The insurgents have said they will ignore the Geneva accord and
keep fighting until the government falls.
   Pakistan's foreign minister, Sahabzada Yaqub Khan, said Friday
that Pakistan is fully committed to the agreement and a political
settlement in Afghanistan.
   He said Soviet accusations Pakistan had violated the accord were
``false, motivated and propagandist.'' The Soviets have accused
Pakistan of continuing to channel weapons to the guerrillas.
   Khan said the accord carries the promise of the complete
withdrawal of foreign forces from Afghanistan, the return of peace
and independence and the safe return of refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
