<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 2259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg     08-12 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says He Won't Rule Out Officials' Removal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo said Friday that he may
yet remove from office the Yonkers city councilmen who are defying
a federal judge over an order to promote racial integration by
building 800 units of affordable housing.
   ``We certainly will not rule out removal by any means,'' the
governor said after meetings with the Yonkers NAACP and the
editorial board of the Gannett Westchester Rockland Newspapers.
   Federal and state officials, such as Sens. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and Alfonse D'Amato, should help persuade Yonkers to build
both low- and moderate-income housing, Cuomo said.
   The people of Yonkers ``have to have leadership locally and
otherwise that shows them the way, that shows them they can have
this housing, that shows them they can do the right thing by the
poor people without threatening their own property,'' the governor
said.
   ``No one needs to suffer a loss to find housing for 200 families
in a city as great as Yonkers,'' he said. Yonkers, the state's
fourth-largest city, has a population of 195,000.
   If an appeals court upholds a contempt finding next week, he
said, the recalcitrant council members should consider resigning.
   Cuomo said his role would be defined by U.S. District Judge
Leonard Sand, who found the city liable for segregating housing and
schools for 40 years.
   ``It's his jurisdiction,'' the governor said.
   Sand also found the city and four councilmen in contempt for
failing to endorse a resolution to build 800 units of affordable
housing to break the pattern of segregation.
   Each councilman was fined $500 daily. The city was fined $100 a
day, with fines to double daily. By the 22nd day of the fines, the
city would face the total elimination of its $337 million budget.
   But a three-judge appeals panel stayed the fines pending a full
hearing on the contempt order next week.
   Cuomo said he wanted to await the outcome of the appeals court
before taking any action. To remove elected officials is a lengthy
process, he observed.
   Earlier this week, the Yonkers Emergency Financial Control
Board, imposed to oversee city spending four years ago as a
condition of a bailout to stave off bankruptcy, assumed the reins
of city spending.
   It could find the officials in violation of the control board
act and set into motion a removal process, said Cuomo. However, he
stopped short of saying it would.
</TEXT>
