<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Soldier 1stLd-Writethru a0818 08-12 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soldier, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0818,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>British Soldier Shot to Death in Belgium</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with comment from Belgian authorities
and background on IRA campaign. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OSTEND, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen shot and killed a British soldier
Friday night as he sat in his car at a traffic light in this North
Sea port city, Belgian and British officials said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility. But suspicion fell
on the Irish Republican Army, which on Aug. 1 stepped up its
campaign against members of British security forces.
   The soldier was hit by five bullets when he stopped his vehicle
at the traffic light, the a Belgian news agency Belga reported. It
said the vehicle had British license plates and pulled a trailer.
   A Belgian police official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said initial details of the shooting were sketchy. But he said
authorities were looking for two men about 25 years old who were
seen running away after the killing.
   The police official said ``it was not excluded'' the shooting
was the work of the IRA.
   The British Ministry of Defense, in a statement in London,
confirmed that the soldier was killed at he waited at a traffic
light.
   The ministry statement said he was on leave from his unit in
West Germany and was on his way home to Britain. Many British
servicemen stationed in West Germany pass through the English
Channel port of Ostend on their way to and from Britain.
   Identification of the victim was withheld until his relatives
are informed.
   This summer, the outlawed IRA has claimed responsibility for a
series of attacks against British military personnel in both Great
Britain and on the Continent.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland. It wants to unite the province, which has a
Protestant majority, with the mainly Catholic Irish Republic.
   The IRA began its stepped-up campaign against members of the
British security forces on Aug. 1, when it bombed a barracks in
North London, killing one soldier and injuring nine others.
   The campaign continued with a series of separate attacks in
Northern Ireland last week in which the IRA killed a policeman, two
part-time soldiers of the Ulster Defense Regiment and two
Protestant civilians who were doing maintenance work on a police
station.
</TEXT>
