<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-12 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temperatures Reach Record Levels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The hot weather continued to pound out record high temperatures
Friday, especially in Michigan, and humidity reached almost
unbearable levels along the Ohio Valley and the northern Atlantic
Coast.
   Cloudiness and scattered showers and thunderstorms, remnants of
the former tropical storm Beryl, kept temperatures down Friday in
the south-central part of the nation, including western Missouri
and eastern Kansas.
   The Pacific Northwest escaped the heat Friday with temperatures
in the Portland and Seattle areas in the 70s.
   Overnight temperatures Thursday only dropped to the 75 to 80
degree range from Boston to northern New Jersey. The low
temperature at Portland, Maine, has been 60 degrees or higher for
20 consecutive days, the longest streak of low temperatures of 60
degrees or higher.
   Williamsport, Pa., and Detroit tied their record number of days
with 90 degrees or higher in one summer. It was the 37th day for
Williamsport and the 36th day for Detroit.
   Southeast Oklahoma received about 7 inches of rain over a
five-hour period.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed across much of the eastern
half of the nation but were scattered. Thunderstorms were
concentrated in the Ohio Valley, the north Atlantic states, western
portions of the central Plains and the northern Rockies.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended across the southern
Atlantic and Gulf Coast states.
   Rainfall during the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT included 1\
inches at Apalochicola, Fla.; two-thirds of an inch at Keesler Air
Force Base in Biloxi, Miss.; and about a half-inch at Cincinnati.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Santa Rosa, Calif., and Crescent City, Calif., to 102
degrees at Phoenix, Ariz. The nation's low Friday morning was 34
degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Records for the day included 86 degrees in Alpena, Mich., and 87
in Beckley, W.Va.
   Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms along the southern Atlantic Coast and southern
Georgia, Florida and Alabama to the lower Mississippi Valley.
Scattered showers and thunderstorms were also predicted from
Montana across the Great Plains, the upper and middle Mississippi
Valley and the Great Lakes region to the north Atlantic coastal
states. Showers and thunderstorms were expected to be numerous from
central Missouri to the upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast in the upper 80s and 90s across
most of the nation. Highs were expected in the upper 70s to mid 80s
in Maine, the northern Great Lakes, northern Minnesota and in
portions of the West. Readings were expected to only reach the
upper 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest and along the California
coast. Highs were to be over 100 degrees in parts of the southern
Plains and in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
