<HEAD>`Last Temptation' Opens Amid Protests; Critics Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 27 grafs to UDPATE with tight security, protests
in Chicago, Washington, D.C., and San Francisco; vandalism in Los
Angeles; decision by Florida movie chain not to show the film; and
Mormons announcing they are joining the protest. Picks up 24th graf
pvs `Scorsese, a...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY41</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' opened in
nine cities Friday amid tight security that included guards
standing as sentries alongside movie screens and theater patrons
being searched.
   Thousands of Christians furiously objected to the film, saying
it depicts Jesus as filled with doubts and lust, while some critics
praised it as a masterpiece.
   Filmgoers snaked around streets by the thousands for tickets to
the first showings, vastly outnumbering the protesters who turned
out in several cities.
   Uniformed security guards checked purses and bags of movie
patrons in New York, Los Angeles and Toronto, and guards also stood
alongside screens in those cities, but no disturbances were
reported.
   In New York, Rabbi Yosef Friedman, an Orthodox Jew, carried a
sign in front of the Ziegfeld Theater that read, ``Rabbis Protest
Mockery of Any Religion,'' while in Chicago, about 50 demonstrators
gathered.
   About 30 protesters in Washington, D.C., waved placards and
marched behind a mannequin of Jesus, while dozens of demonstrators
gathered outside theaters in San Francisco and Chicago.
   Although a demonstration by 25,000 Christians at Universal
Studios was peaceful and polite Thursday, 75 Los Angeles police
officers monitored the crowds at the Century Plaza Theater and
security guards checked purses and bags of movie patrons.
   Police Cmdr. William Booth said no officers will be in the
theater in Century City despite fears of slashed or spray-painted
screens.
   Vandals tossed balloons filled with paint at the Century City
theater about 5 a.m., splattering it with yellow paint, said
security guard Fabian Munez. By noon, someone had spread glue on
the floor in the women's rest room, said patron Jo Drott, 24.
   Hours before the film was to open, a group of directors
including Warren Beatty, James L. Brooks, Peter Bogdanovich,
Michael Mann, Sydney Pollack and Walter Hill called a news
conference to express support for the film's director, Martin
Scorsese.
   ``We owe a debt of gratitude to this group of somewhat misguided
zealots. The film now will be seen by a lot of curiosity-seekers,''
said John Badham, director of ``Short Circuit'' and ``WarGames.''
``What is not terrific is their effort to rewrite the Bill of
Rights.''
   The Directors Guild of America was the latest group to enter the
fray, which has spread from the studio lots to Congress to churches
nationwide.
   Protesters have declaimed the film as sacrilege, saying it
portrays Christ as a deranged and lust-driven human, who while
being crucified, dreams he marries and has sex with Mary Magdalene
and lives his life as an ordinary man.
   Cardinal Bernard Law, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Boston,
urged Catholics to boycott the film, calling it ``morally offensive
and repugnant to Christian belief.''
   ``It is inconceivable to me that a person of faith in Jesus
Christ would go to this movie,'' Law wrote in the archdiocese
newspaper. ``One way to be heard is by not going. Another way is to
write the producers.''
   But proponents say the film illustrates the central mystery of
Christianity, showing a fully human Jesus wrestling with doubts and
temptation, then rising above them to accept his role as God's son,
willingly crucified so the rest of humanity may be forgiven its sin.
   Willem Dafoe, who portrays Jesus in the film, said he is baffled
by protesters' complaints.
   ``I just think this is a beautiful, powerful, positive film.
Some people that for the most part haven't seen it are coming out
against it _ that I don't understand,'' he said in an interview on
NBC-TV's ``Today'' program.
   Universal Studios has accused the protesters of censorship for
asking the studio to destroy the film. In a suprise move, the
studio moved up the release date from Sept. 23 to Friday, saying it
wanted the public to judge the movie for itself but perhaps also
wishing to capitalize on the publicity.
   Church leaders opposing the movie have primarily been Protestant
evangelicals and conservative Catholics, many of whom have refused
to watch it. The Mormon Church also condemned the film Friday,
saying it ``trivializes the message and mission of Jesus Christ.''
   Other Christian leaders, such as the Episcopal bishop of New
York, said after a screening that they had no objections to the
release of the movie, and some said it was an enlightening or
educational tool.
   Film critics also had mixed opinions, some calling it
overwrought and boring at two hours, 40 minutes, others calling it
the most impressive biblical epic ever.
   Richard Corliss of Time magazine said Scorsese ``may have
created his masterpiece'' while Michael Medved of ``Sneak
Previews'' said it was ironic that so much controversy could be
generated ``by a movie this awful.''
   The movie opened Friday in nine major markets _ Los Angeles,
Chicago, Washington, San Francisco, Seattle, Minneapolis, New York,
Toronto and Montreal. Universal spokesman said no decision has been
made whether to add other cities next week.
   Several movie chains have refused to book the film, including
the Newton, Mass.-based General Cinema Theaters, the nation's
fourth-largest movie chain with 1,338 screens in 318 locations. The
company refused to say why, however.
   On Friday, The Wometco exhibition chain, which has more than 90
screens in Florida, said it also had chosen not to screen the film.
   Garth Drabinsky, chairman of Toronto-based Cineplex Odeon, which
is showing the film and is co-distributor, said supression of the
film would signal the beginning of the decline and fall of the
motion picture industry.
   Scorsese, a Roman Catholic, says his film is an affirmation of
faith that he hoped would provoke people to think about Jesus as a
man confronting temptation.
   Based on the 1955 novel by Nikos Kazantzakis, which was
denounced as heresy by the Greek Orthodox church, ``Last
Temptation'' has had a long journey to the big screen. Director
Sidney Lumet acquired the rights to the novel in 1971 but abandoned
the project because of difficulties in writing the screenplay.
   Barbara Hershey, who plays Mary Magdalene, urged Scorsese to
read the novel while she was filming ``Boxcar Bertha'' with him in
1972, and that began his 15-year quest to make the movie.
   During the journey, such actors as Robert DeNiro, Eric Roberts,
Aidan Quinn and even Sylvester Stallone were suggested for the role
of Jesus.
</TEXT>
