<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0671 08-12 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Begins Texas Campaign Visit With Pitch to Hispanic Voters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 2 grafs new to update with arriving; pickup 2nd prv; also
subs last graf to update with decision that Dukakis will not
accompany Bentsen to Florida next weekend</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen returned to his home state Friday to ask Hispanic
voters for support as he began a week of Texas campaigning that
will keep him visible while the Republican National Convention
dominates the national political scene.
   ``Texas is a real battleground, that's obvious,'' Bentsen said
as he arrived in San Antonio several hours late because of a delay
leaving Washington.
   In remarks prepared for delivery Friday night before the
Southwest Voter Registration Project, the Texas senator said,
``Given the importance of the Hispanic community in this election,
it is safe to assume that for the next three months you will be
courted by both major parties. You will get a lot of attention and
hear a lot of promises.
   ``Mike Dukakis, Lloyd Bentsen and a united, committed Democratic
Party will stand shoulder to shoulder with you,'' Bentsen said. An
advance copy of his speech was released Friday in Washington.
   Bentsen told the group, which works to increase Hispanic
political participation, that its efforts already were being felt
with a big increase in Hispanic elected officials.
   The large number of Hispanic voters in Texas and California,
which ``together have 76 electoral votes _ almost 30 percent of the
total needed to win _ could tip the balance of power and elect our
next president,'' he said.
   Bentsen asked the group in both English and Spanish to support
the Democratic ticket this year.
   The stop in San Antonio was the first in a week of Texas
appearances designed to ``shore up the traditional Democratic
support in the state, and turn them into believers in the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket,'' said Mike McCurry, the campaign's
spokesman.
   Dukakis planned to join his running mate at the end of the week.
   ``I think (the trip) underscores the high degree of importance
the ticket places on Texas,'' he said.
   Republican George Bush is a New England native who also claims
to be a Texan. But the Bentsen campaign will try to emphasize the
senator's deeper roots in the state. Bentsen was born in the Rio
Grande valley.
   ``He is clearly doing something George Bush cannot do ...
campaigning as the state's favorite son,'' McCurry said.
   By staying on the campaign trail, Bentsen also will be
constantly ready to respond to developments in New Orleans, the
site of the Republican convention.
   ``We know the Democratic ticket will be in for some sharp
attacks this week _ they might even say some things about Lloyd
Bentsen,'' McCurry said. ``We want to go back to our base and shore
it up while we are under attack.''
   After San Antonio, Bentsen planned to visit Kingsville, Laredo,
Brownsville and Houston this weekend. A quick trip to Arkansas was
scheduled for Monday and then it was back to Texas.
   Dukakis plans to join Bentsen late in the week for a visit to
the LBJ ranch and other events. Bentsen then will travel to Florida
next Saturday.
</TEXT>
