<2ND_LINE>AM-Van Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0807,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team Van, Truck Collision Kills Five</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ABI3</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout increasing injured to 13 sted at least 10,
fatalities all children and other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SWEETWATER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A van carrying a children's softball
team veered out of control and into the path of a tractor-trailer
in a highway construction zone Friday, killing five children and
injuring 13, authorities said.
   The victims were members of a Midland Boys Club team returning
home after playing in a tournament in Abilene.
   The Boys Club van was carrying 14 children and three adults when
the accident happened on Interstate 20 in west Texas, said Mike
Cox, spokesman for the state Department of Public Safety.
   A club spokesman said the children are ages 10 to 12.
   Cox said the van collided with a Coca-Cola truck in a
construction zone one mile east of Sweetwater where traffic had
been narrowed to two lanes.
   Two witnesses, Mike Hanthorn and Bob Rogers of Attica, Ind.,
said the van was traveling behind the truck when the van's driver
appeared to lose control.
   The van ran off the road, veered back onto the highway and
underneath the truck, the witnesses said. The truck dragged the van
about 150 yards before the tractor-trailer jackknifed.
   ``The truck was sitting directly on top of the van. The van was
crushed ... very flat,'' said paramedic Glen Jones, who was at the
scene.
   The truck driver, Billy Tibbs, 32, of Abilene, was listed in
stable condition at Rolling Plains Hospital in Sweetwater with
internal injuries suffered when he was thrown through the
windshield of his rig. He was the truck's only occupant, officials
said.
   Four of the injured were flown by helicopter to two Lubbock
hospitals, and all were reported in critical condition, including
Damon Polk, 23, of Midland, identified as the driver of the van.
   Six others were in stable condition in an Abilene hospital. One
child was hospitalized in Sweetwater, and another was treated and
released.
   Jones said the injured suffered fractured limbs, injured backs
and internal injuries.
   Pete Goetz, regional director of safety for Coca-Cola, said the
truck was based in Abilene and was heading west with a full load to
make deliveries.
   Billie McNatt, education director at the Midland Boys Club, said
the team had left Midland at 6:30 a.m. Friday for a tournament in
Abilene, and was returning home when the accident occurred at 1
p.m. Abilene is about 150 east of Midland.
   Friday was the last day of the Boys Club's summer program and
the club was holding a party when word came of the accident, Ms.
McNatt said.
   ``We were in the midst of our party right when we were notified
of it. ... We just had to cancel our party,'' she said. ``It's
horrible. I just cannot believe it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
