<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's pre-election debate on the future of
the occupied territories is turning into a battle of the generals.
   The liberal Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon Peres is
reassessing policy based on the recommendations of retired military
chiefs who believe giving back land may not jeopardize the nation's
security.
   But their positions are disputed by ex-generals aligned with the
right-wing Likud bloc of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. They argue
that a smaller Israel is a more vulnerable Israel.
   Much of the new thinking about the territories is coming from
the liberal, Labor-oriented Council for Peace and Security, which
includes among its members 30 major generals, 80 brigadier generals
and 100 colonels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Nicaraguan guerrillas
and supporters, some barefoot, ill and hungry, crossed into
Honduras this week in search of food and shelter, rebel and U.S.
officials said Friday.
   The exodus raised questions about the ability of the Contras, as
the rebels are known, to keep up their fight to overthrow the
leftist Sandinista government. Officials said they expect dozens
more such refugees in coming days.
   Visitors ferried to the Honduran-Nicaraguan border by the U.S.
Agency For International Development, or AID, quoted some of the
Nicaraguan refugees as saying Contra leaders ordered them to leave.
But Contra representatives said the supporters were afraid to stay
in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virus-killing blood cells vary widely from person
to person in the way they recognize the AIDS virus and easily lose
their memory for the microbe, making an AIDS vaccine very difficult
if not impossible, according to new research.
   Early attempts at making AIDS vaccines have failed to prompt
blood cells known as B cells to make antibodies that wipe out the
virus. Some experts contend that for a vaccine to work, it must
activate the other main branch of the body's immune defenses, the T
cells.
   However, the latest research suggests important obstacles to
building a vaccine that rallies T cells to give life-long
protection against the many strains of human immunodeficiency
virus, which causes AIDS.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intravenous drug abusers changed their practices
after community workers started warning about AIDS, but even users
in treatment have immune system troubles that may hinder their
fighting off the disease, two studies reported Friday suggest.
   Researchers also confirmed known links between psychological
states and immune system functioning, and suggested it may make a
difference with AIDS.
   The work was presented Friday at the annual meeting of the
American Psychological Association.
   The change in drug practices is significant because drug users
are often thought not responsive to health warnings, said
researcher John Watters.
   His study, done in San Francisco, found users cut back on
sharing of hypodermic needles, which can spread the AIDS virus, and
cleaned their needles more, as well as increasing their use of
condoms for sex.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi legislators worked Friday to
pass anti-corruption legislation inspired by an FBI investigation
that led to guilty verdicts against dozens of county officials, but
the House and Senate were not in agreement.
   The federal investigation into corrupt county purchasing
practices has resulted in charges ranging from extortion to mail
fraud against 56 supervisors in 25 counties. Of those, 42 have
pleaded guilty, six have been convicted, one has been acquitted,
one died before going to trial, one died after sentencing, and
another was declared mentally incompetent to stand trial. The
remaining ones still have charges pending.
   The state Senate prepared Friday to consider its version of a
county government reorganization bill, approval of which would
require negotiations between that chamber and the House.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders are Harvard Law graduates who could be
earning more than $100,000 a year. The participants are high school
and college students who could be at the beach. Instead, they're
working as a sort of urban Peace Corps that organizers hope will
set a national example.
   The program, called City Year, is a privately funded community
service project. Fifty students ages 18 to 21, from high school
dropouts to Brown University students, were culled from 150
applicants.
   They begin their days at 8 a.m. sharp on Boston Common with 20
minutes of calisthenics. If they're late, they do extra exercises.
They spend the rest of the day on various projects, battling the
summer's searing heat and humidity as well as urban blight.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
