<DOCNO> AP880812-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-LordsA-Leaping Adv17 1stLd-Writethru 08-12 0952</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lords A-Leaping, Adv 17, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0166,0975</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Aug. 17 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Lords A-Sleeping Now Lords A-Leaping</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, CORRECTS 19th graf ``But of ... political affiliation'' to
say that ``all but 66 are men'' (sted women).</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been nearly 80 years since the House of Lords
stuck one foot in the grave and its enemies began looking ahead to
a full burial.
   Yet this curious collection of princes, bishops, dukes,
marquises, earls, viscounts and barons seems to be staging a
miraculous deathbed recovery.
   Not only has the upper house beaten its elected partner, the
House of Commons, in the race to be televised, it also is handing
legislative defeats to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at more
than double the rate sustained by any Conservative government since
World War II.
   Those who despair of thwarting Mrs. Thatcher's radical
capitalist reforms in the Commons look increasingly to the Lords,
where most seats pass from father to son. The peers, who are not
elected and serve for life, can vote against the government with no
fear of party discipline.
   The Lords, top-heavy with conservative landowners, ought to be
the natural ally of Mrs. Thatcher's Conservatives. Yet it is the
opposition Labor Party, sworn enemy of inherited privilege, that is
benefitting most from the Lords' independence of mind.
   Mrs. Thatcher's 101-seat majority in the 650-member Commons
guarantees that bills pass in the lower chamber. But in the Lords
she has suffered 127 defeats since coming to office in 1979.
   In recent years the peers have opposed the abolition of London's
left-wing local government, rescued free eye and dental checkups,
restored free school transport in rural areas, stopped corporal
punishment in state schools, toned down a bill to abolish
university tenure, curbed the expansion of police stop-and-search
powers.
   The Commons still has the last word, and some measures,
including abolition of the London authority, ultimately become law
despite the Lords' resistance, but almost always with compromise
amendments.
   ``By and large the two houses have learned to live with each
other and the broad effect is that a lot of amendments made by the
House of Lords get accepted by the House of Commons,'' says Lord
Belstead, the Lords' Conservative leader.
   Lords-watchers now are divided into two camps: those who say a
house based on inherited privilege is bad, and those who say it's
bad but ...
   Hugo Young, a columnist in the left-leaning Guardian newspaper,
says the House of Lords relieves pressure for Britain to have an
elected upper chamber, like the U.S. Senate.
   ``It is proof that of all the democracies, Britain is the most
backward,'' argues Young.
   Lord Ponsonby, the Labor Party's chief whip, calls the
hereditary principle ``an intolerable affront to democracy.''
   But Ponsonby, himself a peer by inheritance, values the Lords as
a revising chamber where Commons' legislation is fine-tuned, and he
acknowledges that the Lords today is ``the best ally of the Labor
Party in the legislative process.''
   Although the House of Lords lost the right to make tax laws in
the 17th century, only in 1910 was it stripped of all power over
money bills and limited to two years the time period in which it
could delay a bill.
   The emasculation followed the Lords' veto of David LLoyd
George's liberal ``budget for the people,'' and most assumed that
the Lords, having thrown their reactionary weight about once too
often, would soon be scrapped altogether. Their power to delay a
bill was cut to one year in 1949.
   The creation of new peers remains a potent tool of government
patronage.
   Belstead maintains the Lords has opened up to new walks of life
_ actors, small businessmen, trade unionists, and women.
   But of the 1,191 peers, 759 are there by inheritance, only 10 of
them Laborites. All but four are white, all but 66 are men, and 446
are Conservatives to Labor's 117 and the centrist parties' 87. The
remainder are independents or declare no political affiliation.
   Only about 300 peers attend debates regularly, and in May the
government had to summon non-attenders to ensure passage of a
controversial property tax bill. The turnout of 509 was the second
biggest this century.
   The key to Mrs. Thatcher's defeats have been regular attenders
among the 266 independents, the ``crossbenchers.''
   Belstead, 55, a lanky former schoolteacher who inherited his
father's title in 1958, has no ready answer to why the House
survives.
   In an interview, he focused on the Lords' function as a revising
chamber, noting that peers work long hours and draw only 52-pounds
($88) for each session attended, plus expenses.
   The chamber also provides the Law Lords, nine ennobled judges
who sit as the country's highest court.
   Although they treasure their archaic rituals, the Lords boast of
an openness to change. They brought in electric lights before the
Commons, and have allowed their debates to be televised since 1984,
something the Commons only now is planning.
   All in all, it's a relaxed place. It's still quite acceptable to
fall asleep in mid-speech _ the giveaway is often the ear trumpet
sliding out of the hand _ or to ramble on at length about
grouse-shooting, leaky army boots, and what to do if Mrs. Thatcher
is at the hairdresser's during a nuclear alert.
   And then there's the joy of dressing up in ermine gowns and
two-peaked hats to welcome a new member.
   ``For one day of the year I was even prettier than my wife,''
remarked Len Murray when he went from being general secretary of
the national labor federation, the Trades Union Congress, to being
Lord Murray of Epping Forest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Aug. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
