<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   08-12 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0542</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks have boosted the prime lending
rate back into the double digits for the first time in three years,
reflecting the Federal Reserve's drive to push all interest rates
higher to stave off inflation.
   Thursday's half-percentage point hike in the prime, to 10
percent, pushed the lending rate to its highest level since the
spring of 1985.
   The increase is likely to pinch the pocketbooks of consumers who
already have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Commending ``the indomitable spirit'' of drought-stricken
farmers, President Reagan has signed the nation's largest-ever
disaster relief bill.
   Also on Thursday, the Agriculture Department said new surveys
point to a drought-damaged corn crop this fall of 4.48 billion
bushels, down 37 percent from last year's harvest and the smallest
output since 1983.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in July, the
third consecutive monthly increase, the government has reported,
but economists say rising interest rates threaten to dampen even
this modest growth rate in the months ahead.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that sales increased $632
million last month to a seasonally adjusted $134.0 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home prices and sales during the April-June
period portray a booming economy on the West Coast, some cooling in
the once red-hot Northeast, resurgence in the Midwest and a hint of
a turnaround in the Southwest, a trade group says.
   The National Association of Realtors said Thursday that three
California metropolitan areas posted the highest home appreciation
rates in the country.
   A 20.1 percent rise in prices from the second quarter of 1987 to
the same period this year made California's Anaheim-Santa Ana area
the costliest housing market in the nation. Median home prices
there were $204,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bally Manufacturing Corp. says it plans to spin
off its hotel-casino group, which accounts for nearly half of its
revenue, as a separate publicly-held company but will retain up to
a 15 percent stake in the business.
   Bally stockholders will receive, tax-free, one share of common
stock in the hotel-casino business for each share of Bally
Manufacturing they own on the effective date of the spin-off, the
Chicago-based company stated Thursday.
   Bally will retain all components of its leisure and
manufacturing businesses, including its chains of fitness centers
and video arcades and its gaming and exercise equipment businesses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has upheld a landmark patent
ruling in favor of Polaroid Corp., saying another judge in the case
against Eastman Kodak Co. was unbiased even though a relative owned
Kodak stock.
   ``Under the circumstances, I cannot find that it is the law that
Eastman Kodak obtain a vacation of this case up to this point,''
U.S. District Judge David Mazzone said Thursday.
   Kodak had asked Mazzone to throw out a 1985 decision by another
federal judge that Kodak had violated several Polaroid patents on
instant film and cameras.
</TEXT>
