<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InterestRates Bjt   08-12 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interest Rates, Bjt,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Quickly Follow Fed In Boosting Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY37 of Aug. 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses and consumers with bank loans priced
according to swings in the prime interest rate will feel the most
immediate impact from major banks' decisions to boost the rate for
the third time this year.
   The banks raised their base lending rates by a half-percentage
point to 10 percent on Thursday _ a more than 3-year high _ in
reaction to the Federal Reserve's drive to push all interest rates
higher to curb inflation.
   The prime rate increase, the second in a month, puts the key
lending rate in double-digit territory for the first time since
June 1985.
   Because the prime is used to calculate a wide range of fixed-and
adjustable-rate loans, the change will affect consumers who already
have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months.
   A higher prime rate will affect small- to medium-sized
businesses and consumers more so than large corporations, which
borrow more cheaply in the open market by issuing commercial paper,
or short-term unsecured IOUs.
   Home equity lines of credit usually are pegged to the prime
rate, while many adjustable-rate home mortgages are tied to
interest paid on Treasury bills.
   Elizabeth G. Reiners, an economist at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
said higher borrowing costs may have a significant effect on the
spending habits of consumers, who have been buying on credit in
increasing numbers lately.
   ``If you have to pay more (for loans) then you have less money
to buy things like furniture, clothing ... and other little
niceties,'' she said.
   ``It will slow the economy, but it won't stop it in its
tracks,'' said Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for the
investment firm Nikko Securities Co. International. ``That's a
healthy thing right now.
   ``You try to get your flu shot before you get the flu ... That's
preventative medicine. That's what the Fed is doing,'' Brusca said.
   Financial markets took Thursday's news in stride after
weathering the storm that followed the Fed's increase in a key
lending rate earlier in the week.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed
up 5.16 to 2,039.30. Bond prices, which generally decline in the
face of rising interest rates, ended mixed.
   The dollar lost ground against all key foreign currencies,
although some European traders credited the prime rate hike for
preventing a free fall.
   Chase Manhattan Bank was the first to announce the prime hike
Thursday morning, with other major banks across the country quickly
following suit.
   The increase brings the prime to its highest level since June
18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from 10 percent.
   The prime was at 8.5 percent at the beginning of the year. The
banks raised it to 9 percent on May 11 and then to 9.5 percent on
July 14.
   Economists widely had anticipated the latest boost the Fed
signaled its desire to tighten credit on Tuesday by raising its
discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6 percent, citing inflationary
pressures. The discount rate is the interest the Fed charges on
loans to member banks.
   Economists said the subsequent boost in the prime reflected the
rising of borrowing costs faced by the banks. Rates banks pay on
products such as certificates of deposits or money market accounts
have been forced up, although not at the same pace as bank loans.
   The trend toward higher interest rates reflects prevailing
concerns in the credit markets that the economy might be
overheating and inflation creeping up. Higher inflation erodes the
value of fixed-rate investments such as Treasury bonds, forcing
borrowers to pay higher interest rates to attract investors.
   Many analysts predict interest rate will continue to head higher
but discount a big increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
