<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid-Kodak     08-12 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid-Kodak,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Out Patent Case Decisions in Polaroid Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp.'s patent court victory over rival
Eastman Kodak Co. was upheld by a federal judge, who ruled that
another judge in the case was unbiased despite a relative's Kodak
stock holdings.
   U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone on Thursday rejected
Kodak's request to throw out a 1985 decision by another federal
judge who found Kodak had violated several Polaroid patents on
instant film and cameras.
   Kodak attorney Richard E. Carlton immediately appealed the
decision to the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Mazzone's ruling came during the first hearing to set a schedule
for the damages portion of the case. Polaroid has requested $5.7
billion in damages for the patent infringements.
   The damages trial tentatively is set to begin in January.
   Kodak had argued in the 12-year-old patent case that all of
federal Judge Rya Zobel's rulings in the case should be vacated
because Zobel's mother-in-law owned 1,000 shares of Kodak stock
worth about $100,000 when the trial began in 1981.
   Zobel withdrew from the case in June shortly after her
mother-in-law died and she was named as a beneficiary of the stock,
which had increased to 2,150 shares because of stock splits.
   ``Under the circumstances, I cannot find that it is the law that
Eastman Kodak obtain a vacation of this case up to this point,''
Mazzone said. ``I do not think that would be fair or be equitable
to everyone.''
   Mazzone said Zobel made it clear at the outset of the trial in
October 1981 that her mother-in-law owned the Kodak stock. He said
neither Kodak nor Polaroid raised the issue during the initial
trial, after Zobel's ruling in 1985 or during a lengthy appeal
process.
   ``She said she did not think that was a disqualifying reason,''
Mazzone said, ``I don't think that was incorrect. Eastman Kodak did
not disagree with it.''
   Polaroid attorney Herbert Schwartz called the decision
``entirely proper and correct and obviously sound.''
   Polaroid, the Cambridge-based camera company that pioneered
instant photography, sued Kodak in 1976 after the Rochester, N.Y.,
camera company introduced its own line of instant film and cameras.
   Zobel ruled in September 1985 that Kodak had infringed on seven
of about 150 Polaroid patents, and barred Kodak from the business
in January 1986.
   On May 9, she told both sides that she intended to remove
herself from the case because she and her husband were
beneficiaries of her mother-in-law's estate. The judge acquiesced
after both sides encouraged her to continue in the case and asked
her for time to research the situation.
   But in a motion filed June 15, Kodak called for Zobel's
immediate disqualification and dismissal of all her rulings in the
case since October 1981. One week later, she withdrew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
