<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-12 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell today in early European trading
hampered by a European-wide outage of a computerized trading
system. Gold prices rose slightly.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading patterns were motivated by
profit-taking ahead of a holiday weekend in several European
countries. Selling pressure was increased by the computer outage,
they said.
   ``People are afraid they won't be able to get out of their
positions since trading goes only by phone and half our phone lines
here are already out of order,'' said one dealer at a major bank in
Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Dealers also said they were waiting for American trade figures
for June to be released on Tuesday. Analysts expect the trade
deficit to range between $11.5 billion and $12.5 billion, compared
with May's $11 billion deficit.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar finished the week at 133.05 yen, down 1.02 yen from
Thursday's close. Later, in London, it was quoted at 132.90 yen.
   Traders said the dollar opened lower in Tokyo and moved up
slightly after Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told reporters
exchange rates should be left to market forces. They said the
market interpreted his comments as an indication Japanese monetary
authorities are not planning to intervene or raise interest rates
to curb the dollar.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8805 West German marks, down from 1.8995; 1.5710
Swiss francs, down from 1.5905; 6.3675 French francs, down from
6.4350; 2.1245 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,395.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,406.50; and 1.2215 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2231.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7150, compared
with $1.7010 Thursday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price
for gold this morning of $428.40 a troy ounce, up slightly from
late Thursday's bid $428. Trading was very quiet.
   In Zurich, the bid price for gold was $428.70, little changed
from $428.65 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 80 cents to close at a bid
$430.99.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.75 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $6.70.
</TEXT>
