<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Mixed, Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed
mixed today after a sluggish trading session ahead of the annual
summer holiday period, while the U.S. dollar fell back against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 230.11-point
winner Thursday, gained another 48.53 points or 0.17 percent to
close the day's trading at 27,833.51.
   ``Forecasts on U.S. trade figures due out next week have not
been very good and that's affecting the market, with participants
sitting back,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama, an analyst with Wako
Securities in Tokyo. Seasonal U.S. trade statistics are due out
next Tuesday.
   Volume of shares traded on the first section was estimated at a
light 500 million, down from 600 million shares Thursday and the
lowest full-day figure to date this year.
   ``It's a seasonal trend. Volume usually declines in August with
the baseball season under way and the `obon' holidays coming up,''
said Yoneyama. Many Japanese, including traders, take holidays
during the holiday starting Aug. 13.
   The U.S. currency finished the week's trading at 133.05 yen,
down 1.02 yen from Thursday's close. The dollar recovered slightly
from its lower 132.85-yen opening and fluctuated between 132.77 yen
and 133.30 yen during today's session.
   There will be no stock or currency dealings in Tokyo on
Saturday. The foreign currency trading is conducted on weekdays and
the Tokyo Stock Exchange is closed on the second and third
Saturdays of each month.
