<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gould-Micro     08-12 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gould-Micro,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gould Sells Semiconductor Division to Micro Devices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gould Inc., which has been shedding divisions for
several years, has announced it is selling its Semiconductor
Division to California Micro Devices Corp. for about $70 million.
   In addition, the electronics firm announced Thursday it will lay
off about 40 people, or about 30 percent, because of the
Semiconductor sale and the previously announced divestiture of its
Industrial Automation Systems Group.
   The sale of Semiconductor, based in Pocatello, Idaho, is subject
to federal regulatory approval and is part of Gould's
debt-reduction and stock-repurchase program announced in May,
officials said. The sale is expected to go through within three
months.
   The Semiconductor Divison, which employs about 1,600 people at
Pocatello and at a packaging plant in the Philippines, had 1987
revenues of about $100 million.
   ``Gould's decision to divest the semiconductor business is based
on the company's strategy of focusing on those business areas that
offer the best opportunity for long-term growth in markets where it
is able to develop critical mass, and, at the same time, maximize
shareholder value,'' James F. McDonald, the company's chairman and
chief executive officer, said Thursday.
   Gould said the staff reductions at its headquarters would be
across all company functions. The company said it would provide
furloughed employees with severance pay and help find new jobs.
   After selling the Semiconductor subsidiary, Gould's revenues are
expected to be more than $650 million, down from 1987 revenue of
$933.4 million. Its total worldwide employment will be more than
6,500.
   The Semiconductor Division, known as American Microsystems Inc.
when it was acquired by Gould in 1982, makes custom integrated
circuits, among other products.
   Gould designs, develops and manufactures computers and
electronic products used in information processing, defense,
engineering and scientific applications.
</TEXT>
