<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Shows Inflation On The Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with report on wholesale
prices; will be led with Commerce Department report on business
inventories and sales during June, due at 10 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation at the wholesale level rose to an annual rate of 5.7
percent in July, reflecting big boosts in a wide variety of
products, including clothng, automobiles, furniture and poultry,
the government said today.
   The Labor Department reported that wholesale prices rose 0.5
percent last month, the biggest gain since March. Price increases
were widespread across a wide variety of non-food items, such as
drugs, which were up 1.1 percent and cosmetics, up 1.7 percent.
   In June, the department's Producer Price Index for finised goods
rose 0.4 percent, or at an annual rate of 4.6 percent, more than
double the 2.2 percent rate of wholesale price inflation for all of
1987.
   Today's report comes just three days after the Federal Reserve
initiated an increase in interest rates to fight inflation.
   On Thursday, major U.S. banks reacted quickly to the Fed's move
by boosting the prime lending rate a half percentage point to 10
percent, the highest level since the spring of 1985.
   The prime rate hike, though, didn't upset the financial markets
because it was a widely expected response to the Fed's earlier
action, in which the central bank raised the discount rate half a
percentage point to 6.5 percent.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
5.16 Thursday to 2,039.30. The average had had fallen nearly 100
points over the five previous sessions, partly because of
interest-rate jitters.
   The dollar lost ground against all key foreign currencies,
indicating that the boost in the prime rate was not seen as a
powerful lure for foreign money.
   The dollar's weakness in turn hurt bond prices, which finished
mostly unchanged or lower.
   Because the prime is used to calculate a wide range of fixed-and
adjustable-rate loans, the increase is likely to pinch the
pocketbooks of consumers who already have seen borrowing costs rise
in recent months.
   ``It will slow the economy, but it won't stop it in its
tracks,'' explained Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for
the investment firm Nikko Securities Co. International. ``That's a
healthy thing right now.
   ``You try to get your flu shot before you get the flu ... That's
preventative medicine. That's what the Fed is doing.''
   The increase brings the closely watched rate to its highest
level since June 18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from
10 percent.
   At the start of the year, the prime stood at 8.5 percent. It was
raised to 9 percent on May 11 and then another half percentage
point on July 14.
   The trend toward higher interest rates reflects prevailing
concerns in the credit markets that the economy might be
overheating and inflation creeping up.
   In indicator of economic activity, the Commerce Department
reported that retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in July. But
economists warned that rising interest rates threaten to dampen
even this modest growth rate in the months ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
