<HEAD>Long Distance Company Reports Loss, CEO Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president and chief executive
officer of ALC Communications Corp., the nation's fourth-largest
long-distance telephone company, has resigned after the company
reported a $6.6 million loss in the second quarter.
   Geore Vasilakos, who resigned Thursday, will be replaced by
Richard Irwin, a CTI director who was named ALC board chairman last
week, ALC said.
   ``With the recent change in control at the company, he wanted to
give the new board the opportunity to make some immediate
changes,'' the company said in announcing Vasilakos' resignation
Thursday.
   ALC had a net loss of $6.6 million on net revenue of $99.9
million for the quarter ending June 30, compared with a net profit
of $1.1 million on revenue of $99.9 million in the second quarter
of 1987.
   The company had a loss of $9.8 million on revenue of $201.6
million for the first six months of the year, compared with a
profit of $3.8 million on revenue of $205 million in the first half
of 1987.
   ALC said its long-distance traffic was up 17 percent in the
first six months of the year compared with a year earlier, but the
losses resulted from price cuts totaling 18 percent in the highly
competitive long-distance business.
   The company has had money problems since Allnet merged with
Lexitel in 1986 to form the nation's fourth-largest long-distance
network. It laid off 200 workers, including 40 in Michigan, in June
in an attempt to cut operating losses.
   ALC completed a $15-million stock sale Aug. 5 to Communications
Transmission Inc. of Austin, Texas, giving CTI two of five seats on
the ALC board.
</TEXT>
