<2ND_LINE>BC-Lumber Sales,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Wood Product Sales Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. wood product sales to Pacific Rim
countries will reach $3 billion this year, up more than 15 percent
from 1987, according to a government report.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., has released details of the report,
which will be officially unveiled at a hearing he will hold Monday
in Portland.
   The report said most of the wood products sold to the Pacific
Rim countries were harvested and milled in the Pacific Northwest.
   Wyden said the report also indicates that Northwest forest
manufacturers are threatened by a series of trade barriers in these
countries, which will be the subject of Monday's hearing by Wyden's
Small Business Subcommittee on Regulation and Business
Opportunities.
   ``Strengthening foreign sales of Northest wood products has got
to be a top priority for our government,'' Wyden said in a
statement this week.
   ``We've knocked down some of the tariff barriers. But non-tariff
obstacles like arbitrary building code restrictions are just as
costly to our industry.''
   Witnesses at Monday's hearing will include Michael T. Kelley,
deputy assistant secretary of commerce for basic industries;
representatives of major timber products associations; Richard
Reiten, director of the Oregon State Economic Development
Department; and Frank Martin, general manager of the Port of Coos
Bay.
