<2ND_LINE>PM-Posner,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwell Paintings To Be Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miami Beach industrialist Victor Posner
agreed to return 13 Norman Rockwell paintings he took from Sharon
Steel Corp. after buying the company in 1969.
   The announcement in U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Warren Bentz's
courtroom Thursday by Robert Cindrich, a Posner attorney, was the
company chairman's first response to a lawsuit filed over the
paintings.
   James W. Toren, a trustee appointed by the court to run Sharon
Steel during its Chapter 11 reorganization, sued for the returned
of the art.
   The paintings depicting scenes from Sharon's plant in Farrell
have hung in Posner's Florida office for nearly 20 years.
   Cindrich said Posner does not have a 14th painting mentioned in
Toren's lawsuit. Russell Ober Jr., an attorney for the trustee,
said he will file a claim in court holding Posner responsible for
the 14th.
   None of the attorneys could estimate the value of the paintings,
for which Sharon Steel paid Rockwell $50,000. A single Rockwell
illustration for a light bulb manufacturer recently sold at auction
for $200,000, said Linda Russell, an assistant curator at the
Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass.
</TEXT>
