<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Soar On USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, oat and soybean futures soared their
permitted limits at today's opening on the Chicago Board of Trade
in reaction to the Agriculture Department's assessment of the
drought's toll on crop production.
   In a report issued after the markets closed on Thursday, The
USDA predicted this year's U.S. corn production would fall 37
percent below last year's harvest, soybean production would decline
by 23 percent and wheat production would drop by 14 percent.
   Analysts said the government's soybean production estimate of
1.47 billion bushels _ the smallest harvest since 1976 _ was the
biggest surprise.
   ``The market must work higher to seek a price that will
discourage usage or we're simply going to run out of soybeans, and
the market won't let that happen,'' said Rich Feltes, director of
commodties research for Refco Inc., a Chicago-based commodity
brokerage house.
   Corn and oat futures are limited to daily moves of 10 cents a
bushel and soybeans to 30 cents a bushel. The exchange has removed
the limits on the soybean contract for August delivery, which
leaped more than 50 cents a bushel at the opening.
   In early trading, wheat was 9{ cents to 10 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.92 a bushel; corn was 5}
cents to 10 cents higher with September at $3.06{ a bushel; oats
were 10 cents higher across the board with September at $2.84{ a
bushel; and soybeans were 30 cents to 59 cents higher with August
at $9.15 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .58 cent higher with August
at 68.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent to .60 cent
lower with August at 80.30 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to 1
cent higher with August at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .68 cent to 1.93 cent higher with August at 36.40 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Thursday while pork futures were
higher.
</TEXT>
