<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-Formula     08-12 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Formula,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T To Offer Karmarkar Algorithm Commercially</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. said Friday
it was offering a computer-based system for solving business
problems that is based on a formula invented in 1984 by Bell
Laboratories mathematician Narendra Karmarkar.
   AT&T said the system would cost $8.9 million, including free
training, and would be ideal for customers such as airlines and
companies in the process industries, such as oil, chemicals and
paper.
   The Karmarkar algorithm greatly speeds up the solution of
mathematical problems that involve the interaction of thousands of
variables. It was originally used to help AT&T plan the growth of
its phone network.
   AT&T said an airline, for example, could use the system to
improve the efficiency of its routing system, including the
scheduling and allocation of planes and crews. Chemical companies
could use it to balance the input of raw materials and the output
of final products, AT&T said.
   The system, known as Korbx, is being offered by a new AT&T unit,
Advanced Decision Support Systems, based in Whippany, N.J. Some
systems, but fewer than 10, have been sold, said the new unit's
president, Aristides Fronistas.
   The Karmarkar algorithm traces a path inside the ``region'' of
all potential solutions to a problem until it arrives at the best
one. An algorithm is simply a rule of thumb, or a special method
for solving a certain kind of problem.
   Bell Laboratories received three patents related to the Korbx
system in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
