<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StoreCards Bjt   08-12 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Store Cards, Bjt,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Considers Deregulating Some Interest Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's retail stores would be
able to charge unlimited interest rates on their credit-card
accounts under legislation being considered by Gov. George
Deukmejian.
   The proposal, supported by the retailers but opposed by consumer
groups, would repeal during a three-year period the current 18
percent interest ceiling that was established 28 years ago. Bank
credit cards would not be affected.
   Democratic state Sen. Ralph Dills, who introduced the bill, said
current limit prevents stores from offering credit to poorer
consumers.
   The no-limit interest policy would ``open up some credit
opportunities that don't exist at this time,'' added Democratic
Assemblyman Dick Floyd.
   But critics charge the proposal would result in $450 million in
additional interest charges over three years.
   Assemblyman Lloyd Connelly, a Democrat, described the measure as
``clearly the worst consumer bill of the year.'' He said California
consumers pay an extra $50 million in interest rates for each
percentage point added to interest rates by stores.
   Deukmejian, in 1982, 1984 and 1986, approved temporary increases
in the interest limit to 19.2 percent. However, last year the
governor vetoed another increase, noting that the prime lending
rate had fallen from over 20 percent in 1980 to between 8 percent
and 9 percent in 1987, and ``the record is devoid of evidence
supporting the need for the higher ceiling.''
   Deukmejian, who rarely discusses pending legislation, has
declined to discuss his position on the bill. He has until the end
of this month to decide its fate.
   The Assembly approved the bill in a 49-22 vote Monday; the
Senate passed it in June.
   The bill would take effect Jan. 1, 1989 and expire three years
later, at which time the Legislature could decide to extend or kill
it based on a review by a non-partisan state legislative analyst.
   Assemblyman Frank Hill, a Republican who was a key backer of the
bill, said that if stores are limited to 18 percent they can offer
credit only to customers considered lower risks or raise their
prices to compensate for the loss.
   The current ceiling ``is hurting California consumers as well as
the retail industry,'' Hill said. Deregulation would ``let the
marketplace set the rates.''
   Democratic Assemblyman Rusty Aerias, a critic of the bill, said
that a New York study found that stores actually did not offer poor
people more credit after deregulation. ``This is a reverse Robin
Hood where we're robbing from the poor,'' he said.
   According to an Assembly finance committee, 16 other states have
deregulated retail credit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0704EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ChipOutlook Adv15   08-12 1163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chip Outlook, Adv 15,1199</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Aug. 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Semiconductors Prices Are Down, But Electronics Makers Still Worry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY26 of Aug. 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe shortage of computer memory chips is
slowly beginning to ease, but U.S. electronics makers remain deeply
concerned about their vulnerability to Japan's control of the
critical components.
   Memory chips are the plywood of the worldwide electronics
industry _ essential to products ranging from personal computers to
copying machines.
   The supply crunch has left U.S. electronics makers wringing
their hands over lost sales, foregone profits, delayed product
introductions and worsened relations with customers.
   Although Japanese companies such as NEC Corp., Hitachi Ltd. and
Toshiba Corp. account for 80 to 90 percent of worldwide sales of
memory chips, few people are accusing those companies of
delibrately engineering the shortages.
   In fact, there is a shortage of memory chips inside Japan, which
has surpassed the United States to become the world's largest
consumer of chips.
   ``Some major, major major corporations in Japan can't find
product. They're coming to us,'' said Larry Gurewitz, an owner of
H&R Enterprises in Canoga Park, Calif., which deals in used and
surplus chips.
   Nevertheless, the vulnerability of U.S. companies to Japanese
suppliers has been highlighted by the chip squeeze. The dominance
in memory chips gives the Japanese a base to solidify control of
the products that use the chips.
   ``The Japanese have a large stake in supplanting (U.S.-based)
merchant producers as the providers of leading-edge chip
technologies,'' said Michael G. Borrus, deputy director of the
Berkeley Roundtable on the International Economy.
   If the Japanese companies succeed in gaining unquestioned
leadership in chip technology, they will be able to reserve the
latest chips for their own computers, phone switches, satellites
and other equipment before making them available to U.S. and
European rivals, Borrus said.
   ``At stake for the U.S. economy is not simply the $25 billion
market for semiconductors, but the current $0.5 trillion market for
the final products that incorporate semiconductors, soon to be a $1
trillion market,'' Borrus writes in a new book, ``Competing for
Control: America's Stake in Microelectronics.''
   So far the threat from Japan is more theoretical than real. For
example, Toshiba, the world's biggest producer of 1-megabit DRAMs
(pronounced dee-rams), allocates more than 60 percent of its output
of the chips to U.S. customers even though its own personal
computer unit in Japan is short on them.
   But the potential for manipulation is starkly obvious,
especially considering that DRAMs can account for up to a quarter
of the cost of building a computer.
   Sun Microsystems Inc. is one company that has felt the sting of
the chip shortage. The booming Silicon Valley maker of computer
workstations, which just cracked the $1 billion barrier in annual
sales, says its revenue would have been $100 million higher if chip
shortages had not delayed deliveries.
   Sun occupies a market that Japanese competitors have scarcely
touched, yet is heavily dependent on chips from companies that are
potential rivals.
   A similar dilemma faces another U.S. computer industry star,
Cray Research Inc., which relies on Japanese-made chips at the same
time it fends off Japanese challenges to its role as the world's
leading maker of supercomputers.
   Cray has never taken a position on whether a strong, U.S.-based
semiconductor industry is needed.
   Ironically, for all the problems of a chip shortage, the
greatest long-term danger to the U.S. electronics industry could
come from an eventual chip glut.
   The last glut drove several of the biggest U.S.-based DRAM
suppliers out of the business because they could not afford the
huge losses, and the next one could wreak similar havoc.
   Japanese companies are better able to sustain losses on chips
because they make other products that tide them over. In the United
States, only International Business Machines Corp. is in a similar
position. IBM is the world's largest DRAM producer, but sells none
to outsiders.
   The only two U.S.-based companies that still sell DRAMs on the
open market are Texas Instruments Inc. and Micron Technology Inc.,
which have earned windfall profits that will enable them to keep
current on the technology.
   For now, a bust in memory chip prices is still a distant threat.
Toshiba, in a statement prepared for The Associated Press, said
``we are afraid that the current unusual supply-demand relations
will not ease until the middle of 1989.''
   Shortages of the older 256-kilobit DRAMs could prevail even
longer because production lines for them have been retooled for the
new chips. There are also growing shortages of 1-megabit static
random access memories, or SRAMs.
   Average U.S. spot prices have fallen to $37 apiece in July from
$47.50 in April for the most advanced memory chips in mass
production, the 1 million-bit dynamic random access memories known
as 1-megabit DRAMs.
   That is still way above the $19.50 spot price that prevailed in
July 1987, according to Dataquest Inc., the market research firm.
   In April, some desperate customers paid as much as $65 apiece
for small quantities of 1-megabit DRAMs, according to Mark Giudice
of Dataquest. It became common for companies to pillage memory
chips from older computers and other equipment.
   The supply squeeze in memory chips seems to have two main
sources, the main one being the sticky transition to the new,
hard-to-build megabit chips from the older 256-kilobit variety.
   Producing the new chips demands unprecedented precision and
cleanliness, and it has taken chipmakers longer than expected to
gear up production. At the same time, a boom in sales of personal
computers and other gear has increased the demand for the chips.
   A secondary reason for the squeeze is the 1986 accord between
the United States and Japan to prevent ``dumping'' of Japanese-made
chips at unfairly low prices. In order to prop up prices to comply
with the accord, the Japanese government instructed its chip makers
to hold back on production.
   That anti-dumping accord was supposed to lure more U.S.
companies back into producing DRAMs by guaranteeing them some
protection when chip prices begin skidding, an inevitable process
given the improving yields from existing fabrication lines and the
start-up of new ones.
   So far, though, few companies have been lured back. Motorola
Inc. is starting up DRAM production again. But American Telephone &
Telegraph Co., in spite of the accord, dropped out of the DRAM
business last year.
   The reluctance of U.S. companies to enter or stay in the market
is understandable considering the roughly $300 million it takes to
build a state-of-the-art fabrication plant and the boom-bust nature
of chip prices.
   In the long run, many analysts say, sustaining a healthy chip
industry in the United States will probably depend on more
government initiatives such as the anti-dumping accord and _
importantly _ closer cooperation between U.S. chipmakers and U.S.
chip users.
   ``We're both realizing that adversarial isn't the best way to
go,'' said Stan Victor, a Texas Instruments spokesman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Aug. 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     08-12 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0349</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated again today as rising
interest rates kept a damper on the market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.25 to 2,038.05
by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
607 up, 762 down and 531 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 155.73 million shares with an
hour to go.
   A big chunk of that activity was concentrated in a few electric
utility issues that were the targets of trading strategies keyed to
their approaching dividend payments.
   Otherwise, analysts said the market was weak and listless, still
struggling to recover its balance after the Federal Reserve's move
Tuesday to raise its discount rate.
   In the credit markets today, prices of long-term government
bonds fell by roughly $5 for each $1,000 in face value, putting
their yields in the 9.45-9.5 percent range.
   The report that the producer price index of finished goods rose
0.5 percent in July was in line with advance estimates. But
analysts said some traders were troubled by the 0.6 percent
increase in the index after the volatile food and energy components
were excluded.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Electric rose ] to
40]; American Telephone & Telegraph fell ] to 25{, and American
Express was unchanged at 28.
   National Semiconductor dropped ] to 9~ in active trading. The
company said it will take a one-time charge of about $18 million in
its current fiscal quarter, and also said it believed analysts'
estimates of its earnings for the quarter were too high.
   Trans World Airlines climbed 2[ to 37\. The company scheduled a
shareholder meeting for Sept. 7 to vote on Chairman Carl Icahn's
proposal to take the company private.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.07 to 148.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .51 at 296.23.
</TEXT>
