<DOCNO> AP880812-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AudiSettlement Bjt   08-12 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Audi Settlement, Bjt,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audi Mulls Options in Sudden Acceleration Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car owners involved in a lawsuit alleging some of
Audi of America's cars are defective are forming a ``barricuda
network'' to attack the company after a judge threw out a tentative
settlement, a company official contended Friday.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas Rakowski on Thursday threw out
the proposed settlement between the company and a class of Audi car
owners who alleged that Audi 5000 sedans suddenly accelerate
without warning.
   ``I sense a barricuda network setting up where everybody wants
to get a piece of the meat and to get into the deep pockets of
Audi,'' said Tom McDonald, a spokesman for Volkswagen of America
Inc., of which Troy, Mich.-based Audi is a subsidiary.
   McDonald contended Friday that the Audi Victims Network, a group
of Audi car owners based in Washington, D.C., was advising some of
its members to withdraw from the class-action lawsuit and file
individual lawsuits against the company. Such a move could cost the
company thousands of dollars in legal fees, he said.
   McDonald said only 1,500 of the 340,000 owners of the Audi
sedans covered by the proposed settlement of the class-action
lawsuit refused to agree to it. He blamed the settlement's
rejection on the victims network.
   ``The Audi Victims Network has not been a headache to us, it's
been a major disease to Audi,'' McDonald said.
   Stephen Nassau, an attorney for the victims network, said he had
advised his clients to withdraw from the class-action suit because,
under terms of the proposed settlement, owners would have had to
buy another Audi.
   The group of about 800 Audi owners contend their cars suddenly
accelerate without warning, Nassau said.
   ``Some people have put their cars away and refuse to drive or
sell them,'' he said. ``Why would they want to buy another one?
   ``I would say if we were barricudas, there must be sharks
circling in the waters as well,'' he said, referring to Audi
officials trying to eliminate complaints from car owners.
   The case stems from a 1987 class-action lawsuit alleging that
Audi 5000s were defective because of sudden acceleration problems.
The settlement would have applied to owners of Audi 5000s built
between 1978 and 1986.
   Audi officials maintain that owners have been unable to prove
their Audi 5000 sedans have any defects and say the settlement
rejected by Rakowski is fair.
   Under terms of the settlement, proposed in June by attorneys for
both sides, Audi car owners who bought another Audi would have been
offered rebates of up to $2,000, but would have had to free the
company from all liability.
   The judge recommended Thursday that both sides try to negotiate
a new settlement and report any progress at a hearing scheduled for
Aug. 31.
   ``After the ruling, we have to look at all our options,''
McDonald said. ``One option is to renegotiate; the other is to
litigate.''
   Nassau said the victims network may ask the judge to let them
become a third party in the case.
   ``There's no question that we're going to be watching to see
what happens next,'' Nassau said a day after Rakowski approved his
motion to throw out a previous judge's ruling giving preliminary
approval to the settlement.
   Nassau's motion called for vacating Circuit Judge Harold
Siegan's earlier ruling, contending the judge had not given
``proper scrutiny'' to the matter before approving it.
   After giving the proposed settlement the preliminary go-ahead,
Siegan removed himself from the case in July, saying he had a
potential conflict of interest because he was friends with an
attorney in the case.
   Thursday's ruling was a victory for the Center for Auto Safety,
a Washington-based group formed by consumer activist Ralph Nader.
The center contended that the Audi acceleration problem was linked
to at least 1,650 accidents, causing 402 injuries and five deaths.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
