<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 2018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InsilcoBuyout     08-12 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insilco Buyout,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders Suing To Block Management Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five groups of Insilco Corp.
shareholders have filed suit against the company, seeking to thwart
a $950 million management-led leveraged buyout they consider
``grossly unfair and inadequate.''
   Insilco's board of directors accepted the $29-a-share offer
earlier this month in what some analysts described as an
anti-takeover defense for the high-technology and specialty
consumer products concern.
   In a leveraged buyout a company is acquired largely with
boreowed money repaid from the target company's profits or asset
sales.
   Stockholders want to prevent that deal from being completed. In
complaints filed in New Haven Superior Court, they charge Insilco
would be worth a lot more in ``an open auction for the company.''
   ``The directors have the duty to maximize shareholder value,''
William Barnes, an attorney for Sam and Marilyn Pill of Brooklyn,
N.Y., wrote in one of five civil suits filed Tuesday.
   Insilco disclosed in filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission last week that it received several unsolicited buyout
offers since the management bid. It said it entered into
confidentiality agreements with certain groups but declined to
identify the parties.
   Insilco Vice President and Treasurer Malcolm Todt said Thursday
the company believes the tender offer from management is fair.
   Named as defendants were Insilco, 12 directors and ISC Holdings
Inc., the new holding company created by Insilco management to
acquire the Meriden-based company.
   In recent years, Insilco, once known as the International Silver
Co., has restructured itself into an industrial holding company
with operating companies that make products for high-technology
industries and speciality consumer markets.
   Insilco makes Red Devil paints, Rolodex rotary files, metal
cartridges and other projectiles for the defense industry and
Dual-Lite emergency lighting equipment.
   Insilco earned $11.7 million, or 55 cents per share, in the
second quarter, compared with $11 million, or 52 cents a share,
last year. Revenue totaled $196.4 million, up from $154.3 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
