<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-12 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower In Unexpected Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, surprising many analysts who
had expected a strong performance following the government's crop
production report.
   Corn, oat and soybean futures opened sharply higher as expected
but corn prices plunged their permitted daily limit shortly after
the opening, sparking a sell-off in the adjacent trading pits. Only
oat futures closed higher while most corn futures finished down the
10-cents-a-bushel limit.
   ``It's astonishing,'' said Katharina Zimmer, grain analyst with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   In a report issued after the markets closed on Thursday, the
USDA predicted the drought would lower this year's U.S. corn
production by 37 compared to last year. The agency estimated
soybean production at 23 percent below last year's level and said
wheat production would drop by 14 percent.
   ``I guess the markets may be giving us a signal today that the
USDA report did not provide any new bullish information that wasn't
already in the market,'' said Mario Balletto, Merill Lynch's
soybean analyst.
   Balletto said traders apparently want to see signs of new export
business before they are willing to bet on higher prices.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.80 a bushel; corn was 4\
cents to 10 cents lower with September at $2.87\ a bushel; oats
were 4{ cents to 6{ cents higher with September at $2.80 a bushel;
and soybeans were 11 cents lower to 6 cents higher with August at
$8.50 a bushel.
</TEXT>
