<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-InsiderTrading 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Insider Trading, 1st Ld-Writethru,0212</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with Kean to sue company, other
details; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The securities arm of National Westminster Bank
PLC said it fired two market-makers in stocks for insider trading.
   County Natwest Woodmac Ltd. said Friday that, as one of three
stockbrokers of Grand Metropolitan PLC, it was informed on Monday
that Grand Met was about to announce its intention to sell its
Inter-Continental hotel chain after several parties had shown an
interest.
   County Natwest said that ``through a breach of internal
procedures, which did not involve (the) corporate finance
department, this information reached two market-makers.''
   The two market-makers, Russell Kean and Stephen Floyd, dealt in
Grand Met shares even though they had been informed that they could
not because they were ``in receipt of privileged information,'' the
company said.
   Kean traded 2 million pounds, or about $3.4 million, worth of
shares of Grand Met, a major British hotels and beverage company,
County Natwest said.
   The two men were fired Wednesday after the London Stock Exchange
detected what it regarded as suspicious trading and traced it back
to County Natwest.
   Kean's lawyer said Kean made no personal profit through the
share dealings connected with his dismissal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
