<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Neiman'sMarcus Bjt   08-12 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Neiman's Marcus, Bjt,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Family Member Of Neiman-Marcus Leaving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Marcus said Friday he is leaving as
chairman of the pricey retailer Neiman-Marcus, marking the end of
the Marcus family's affiliation with the deparment store founded by
his grandfather in 1907.
   Marcus, who was also chief executive of the 22-store,
Dallas-based chain, said he would have no further direct connection
with the famous retailer.
   Marcus, 50, is the last founding family member to hold a
corporate position in the 81-year-old Dallas institution founded by
Herbert Marcus Sr. that over the years has attracted international
attention and prestige.
   Today, the Neiman-Marcus stores are part of Neiman-Marcus Group
Inc., which also includes the retailers Bergdorf-Goodman and
Contempo Casuals. Neiman-Marcus Group is owned by General Cinema
Corp., which also owns movie houses and soft-drink bottling
concerns.
   Allen I. Questrom, 48, a former vice chairman of Federated
Department Stores Inc., has been named president and chief
executive of Neiman-Marcus stores. Questrom left Federated in May,
after Toronto-based Campeau Corp. took control of the
Cincinnati-based retailer.
   Marcus' resignation is effective Sept. 1, while Questrom will
join the company Sept. 7, Neiman-Marcus said in a statement.
   For the past nine months, the company had been trying to fill
the vacancy left by the departure of its president and chief
operating officer, David Dworkin.
   The title of chairman will not exist in the new Neiman-Marcus
corporate structure, officials said. Questrom will report to Robert
J. Tarr Jr., president and chief operating officer of Neiman-Marcus
Group and General Cinema.
   Marcus, who became chairman in 1978, said in an interview with
the Dallas Morning News Thursday he felt comfortable with handing
the reins to Questrom although he had not yet formulated his next
business plans.
   After graduating from Harvard University, Marcus joined the
store in 1962 at age 24 as an assistant buyer. He moved up through
the ranks and was named president 10 years later.
   ``Some management science book said 10 years as CEO is long
enough, at least for the company, if not the individual,'' Marcus
said.
   Referring to Questrom's impending arrival, Marcus said, ``We
have the type of stewardship that allows me with confidence to
explore some other ideas and opportunities.''
   Before being named Federated vice chairman in January, Questrom
was chairman and chief executive officer of Los Angeles-based
Bullock's, a subsidiary of Federated now owned by R.H. Macy & Co.
Inc. From 1978 to 1984, Questrom was chairman and chief executive
of Federated's Atlanta-based Rich's division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880812-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-12 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fluctuated without direction against
major foreign currencies Friday as traders began looking ahead to
next week's release of U.S. monthly trade figures.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
was bid at $431 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $429.30 an
ounce late Thursday.
   Traders are reluctant to hold big currency positions because of
the possibility of a surprise Tuesday when the Commerce Department
releases the June merchandise trade deficit.
   Many traders are expecting a shortfall of $10 billion to $12
billion. The deficit was $10.9 billion in May.
   The dollar was weakened only briefly by a government report that
wholesale prices rose at an annual rate of 5.7 percent in July,
said Rick Lloyd, foreign exchange and money market trading manager
for Security Pacific National Bank in Los Angeles.
   Keith Dipple, chief dealer at Banque Francaise de Commerce
Exterieure, said the dollar still was suffering from a market
perception that it moved a ``little too far, too quickly'' Tuesday
when it shot up following the U.S. Federal Reserve's
half-percentage point increase in its key bank lending rate, the
discount rate.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7155 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7010 Thursday. The
dollar also weakened later in New York, as sterling rose to $1.7130
from $1.7103.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar finished the week at 133.05 yen, down 1.02 yen from
Thursday's close. Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.15 yen. In
New York, the dollar rose to 133.28 yen from 132.74 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8833 West German marks, unchanged;
1.5777 Swiss francs, up from 1.5735; 1.2111 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2198; 6.3965 French francs, up from 6.3863; and 1,397.50
Italian lire, unchanged.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8805 West German marks, down from 1.8995; 1.5750 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5905; 6.3810 French francs, down from 6.4350;
2.1146 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1425; 1,395.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,406.50; and 1.2195 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2231.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 80 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid
$430.99 an ounce.
   Later, gold rose in London to a late bid price of $431.50 a troy
ounce, compared with late Thursday's bid of $428.
   In Zurich, gold closed at a bid $432.50 an ounce, compared with
$428.65 late Thursday.
   At the end of the trading day on the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery rose to $431.30 a troy
ounce from $429.30 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion rose on the London market to a late bid price of
$6.73 a troy ounce from $6.70 Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $6.712 a troy ounce from
$6.685 Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
