<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, The NYSE's ... to 148.55., to reflect NYSE's
revision of its composite index.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined slightly in a sluggish
session Friday under the continuing influence of rising interest
rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.78 to
2,037.52, extending its loss for the week to 81.61 points.
   That ranked as the biggest weekly decline for the average since
it fell 108.42 points March 21-25.
   Declining issues narrowly outnumbered advances on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 679 up, 742 down and 530 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 176.96 million
shares, against 173 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 198 million shares.
   A big chunk of the day's activity was concentrated in a few
electric utility issues that were the targets of trading strategies
keyed to their approaching dividend payments.
   Otherwise, analysts said the market was weak and listless, still
struggling to recover its balance after the Federal Reserve's move
Tuesday to raise its discount rate.
   In the credit markets Friday, prices of long-term government
bonds declined slightly, putting their yields in the 9.42-9.5
percent range.
   The Labor Department's report that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.5 percent in July was in line with advance
estimates. But analysts said some traders were troubled by the 0.6
percent increase in the index after the volatile food and energy
components were excluded.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Electric rose \ to
40\; American Telephone & Telegraph fell | to 25\, and American
Express was off [ at 27~.
   National Semiconductor dropped { to 9} in active trading. The
company said it will take a one-time charge of about $18 million in
its current fiscal quarter, and also said it believed analysts'
estimates of its earnings for the quarter were too high.
   Trans World Airlines climbed 2[ to 37\. The company scheduled a
shareholder meeting for Sept. 7 to vote on Chairman Carl Icahn's
proposal to take the company private.
   Polaroid dropped 1 to 42[. Shamrock Holdings revised its offer
for the company, but analysts said traders were disappointed that
the bid hadn't been raised more substantially.
   Best Buy, discussed as a prospective takeover candidate, gained
2| to 12\.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $1.02 billion, or 0.04
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .07 to 148.53.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell .32 to 301.94, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was down .20 at 262.55.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped .16 to 378.95. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 296.48, down .26.
</TEXT>
