<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     08-12 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices declined moderately Friday, rounding
out a traumatic week of steep losses that catapulted interest rates
to their highest levels this year.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond fell about ] point,
or $3.75 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate
trends, rose to 9.42 percent from 9.38 percent late Thursday.
   The yield on the 30-year bond has not been this high since Dec.
11, 1987, when it reached 9.44 percent.
   Bond prices took a beating this week after the Federal Reserve
raised its discount rate on Tuesday. The increase in the discount
rate, the interest the Fed charges on loans to major financial
institutions, was the first such hike since last October's stock
market crash. A rise in interest rates sends bond prices lower.
   The central bank raised the discount rate a half-percentage
point, to 6.5 percent, to stem inflationary pressure on the
economy. Many market watchers had expected the Fed to tighten its
reins on the money supply _ but few were anticipating that dramatic
a move.
   ``It's just been a lousy week,'' said Mitchell Held, chief
financial economist for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   He suggested that Friday's more tempered decline in bond values
was caused by a residue of negative sentiment from the week.
   The yield on the key 30-year issue jumped from 9.10 percent on
Monday, the day before the discount-rate hike, to Friday's 9.42
percent.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds Friday, prices of
short-term government issues were unchanged to 1-32 point lower,
intermediate maturities slipped 5-32 point to 3-16 point, and
20-year issues lost 5-32 point, according to figures provided by
Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, edged up 0.67 to 1,126.55.
   Corporate bonds were slightly lower. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, slipped
0.02 to 280.28.
   Three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, edged up 1 basis point to
a discounted rate of 7.00 percent and a yield of 7.21 percent.
Six-month bills rose 3 basis points to a discounted rate of 7.45
percent to yield 7.84 percent while one-year bills were up 1 basis
point at 7.65 percent to yield 8.21 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discounted rate is the interest rate the market uses to price bills.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 8[ percent, up from 8 1-16
percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
