<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Macmillan     08-12 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Macmillan,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Reports Lower Second-Quarter Net</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK N(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover target Macmillan Inc. on Thursday
reported its second-quarter net income slipped 9 percent despite
higher sales.
   Separately, the Robert M. Bass Group said it was extending its
$1.95 billion bid for the pubishing and information services giant.
The Texas-based Bass group has been joined by British media magnate
Robert Maxwell in the bid for Macmillan.
   Net income for the quarter ended June 30 totaled $13.2 million,
or 49 cents a share, compared with $14.5 million, or 57 cents a
share, in the year-ago period. The company noted that 1987 results
reflected a $3.8 million gain from the sale of the company's
software division.
   Revenue during the quarter rose 11 percent to $241 million,
compared with $217.5 million in the second quarter of 1987.
   For the first six months, Macmillan reported net income of $10.6
million, or 43 cents a share, down 12 percent from $12 million, or
49 cents a share, in the year-ago period.
   Revenue during the first two quarters were up 11 percent at
$423.6 million, from $382.6 million a year ago.
   The Bass group began bidding for Macmillan in May. Its
$75-a-share tender offer for the company, which was to expire
Friday, has been extended to Aug. 26. The Bass group apparently
wants to keep its offer alive while the two sides meet again in
court.
   A hearing has been scheduled for Aug. 15 in Macmillan's bid to
overturn a preliminary injunction that the Delaware Chancery Court
had granted Bass in an effort to block Macmillan's defensive
restructuring plan.
   While the two sides were squabbling in court, Maxwell
Communication Corp. came on the scene with an $80-a-share bid that
values Macmillan at $2.32 billion.
   Maxwell's bid is conditioned upon termination of Macmillan's
restructuring plan and redemption of the company's poison pill.
</TEXT>
