<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-12 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights,0534</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of Pennsylvania's Peach Bottom
nuclear power plant has been fined $1.25 million, the largest fine
in Nuclear Regulatory Commission history, because 33 reactor
workers slept or were negligent on the job.
   The NRC on Thursday also announced fines ranging from $500 to
$1,000 against the 33 present and former reactor operators, the
first such civil penalties ever proposed for individual operators.
   The agency said the 33 fines ``involved sleeping and-or other
acts of inattention to duty'' at Philadelphia Electric Co.'s
dormant Peach Bottom plant on the Susquehanna River in Delta, Pa.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   July's hot weather cost Americans over a
quarter-billion dollars more than normal in keeping cool, the
government has reported.
   The national air conditioning bill for July was $4.3 billion,
some $255 million more than would have been expected in normal
weather, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said
Thursday.
   That averaged out to a July air conditioning bill of $104 for
the typical home, $6 more than normal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five top officers of the investment group
Princeton-Newport Partners have pleaded innocent to racketeering
charges, and their lawyers criticized what they called a ``broad
attack on Wall Street.''
   A sixth defendant was not present at Thursday's arraignment at
federal court in Manhattan, but his lawyer entered an innocent plea
for him.
   All six were named last week in a 35-count indictment on charges
of racketeering and conspiracy, the first time a racketeering
charge has been leveled against securities traders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker has
agreed to plead guilty to fraud charges and cooperate with the
ongoing probe of insider trading with advance copies of Business
Week magazine.
   William Dillon, 33, was charged Thursday with a single count of
wire fraud for an alleged scheme to obtain and trade on information
from copies of Business Week secretly purchased from printing
personnel before they hit newsstands.
   According to court documents, Dillon allegedly purchased 129
different securities between May 1986 and last month, making some
$94,000 in profits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donnay SA rose to top seed among the
world's tennis racket makers when Bjorn Borg wielded its wares, but
as the Swedish champion's career faded, so did the company's
fortunes.
   People close to the Belgian company said Thursday that
family-owned Donnay's debts have mushroomed to $35 million, and
there is little hope of reaching an accord with creditors to avoid
bankruptcy.
   Donnay's creditors refuse to provide fresh capital unless the
company comes up with an acceptable restructuring plan.
</TEXT>
