<1ST_LINE>d f BC-BoeingOrder     08-12 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing Order,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southwest Orders 20 737s; Boeing Sets New Record For Annual Orders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southwest Airlines has ordered 20 Boeing 737-300
jetliners, Boeing Commercial Airplanes said Thursday, giving the
unit of Boeing Co. a record for new commercial aircraft orders for
the fourth consecutive year.
   The Southwest order, worth about $560 million, brings the value
of announced orders so far in 1988 to $20.3 billion, bettering
1987's record of $19.9 billion.
   For 1988, 458 jet planes have been ordered, just three fewer
than 1978's record of 461. In 1987, 366 jets were ordered.
   The order by Dallas-based Southwest includes 12 of the
twin-engine jets to be delivered in June 1991, and eight previously
unannounced twinjets, three of which were delivered earlier this
year. The other five planes will be delivered starting in April
1989.
   The 737-300, which carries 137 passengers in Southwest's
configuration, has been Boeing's best seller, with 39 customers
ordering 790 planes. Orders for all 737 models total 2,186.
</TEXT>
