<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoPrices     08-12 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Prices,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Raises Prices on 1989 Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Friday it will raise
prices of its 1989 automobiles an average of 2.9 percent because of
higher manufacturing costs.
   New prices announced by GM President Robert Stempel include
increases up to 4.6 percent for the redesigned, larger 1989
Cadillac Sedan DeVille, and more than 5 percent from current
discounted levels for the popular Chevrolet Corsica four-door sedan.
   Prices of some cars, including GM's most expensive, the $56,533
Cadillac Allante, and its least expensive, the $6,399 Pontiac
LeMans Coupe, will be unchanged, GM Comptroller John E. Rhame said.
   However, Stempel said, discounts on options have cut prices of
some models enough so that even with the increases, their 1989
introductory prices will be down from a year earlier.
   ``For example, the 1989 introductory prices for the Chevrolet
Corsica and Beretta, two of our most popular cars, are on average 4
percent to 5 percent lower than their comparably equipped
counterparts at 1988 introductory price levels,'' he said.
   Rhame said that as an example, the manufacturer's suggested
retail price at the start of the 1988 model year for a Corsica with
options including air conditioning, automatic transmission, tilt
wheel, tinted glass, rear window defogger and cruise control was
$11,618.
   With options discounts, the price of that car now would be
$10,618, he said. For 1989 it will be $11,168, a 5.2 percent
increase, but still down 3.9 percent from the 1988 introductory
level.
   The base price of the Cadillac Sedan DeVille will rise to
$25,435 from $23,404 for 1988, Rhame said.
   The high-volume Chevrolet Cavalier 4-door sedan will have a base
price of $8,595, up from $8,195, with the addition of rear-seat
shoulder belts as standard equipment for 1989, he said.
   Base prices will drop on some models, such as the Oldsmobile
Cutlass Calais two-door coupe, which will start at $9,995, down
from a 1988 base price of $10,320.
   GM's light truck prices will increase an average of 3 percent,
Rhame said, although specific truck prices were not released.
   Earlier this month, Ford Motor Co. announced price increases for
1989 ranging from 1.9 percent to 5.3 percent on six of its most
popular cars.
   Chrysler said in late July it will raise 1989 prices an average
of 3 percent, with increases up to 9 percent on some popular models
such as mini-vans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
